42\u0fb2\u0f74\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f50\u0f60\u0f0b\u0f51\u0fad\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f62\u0f92\u0fb1\u0f74\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f5b\u0f7a\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f92\u0fb1\u0f53\u0f0d \u0f66\u0f7a\u0f58\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f59\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f90\u0f7c\u0f62\u0f0d The Philosophical Schools: The Ornament Beautifying the Dakpo Lineage]''' (Mind Only)\n\n'''2017-2018: [https://wisdomexperience.org/product/interconnected-paperback/ Interconnected: Embracing Life in Our Global Society]'''\n\n* [https://dharmaebooks.org/interconnected-russian/ \u0412\u0437\u0430\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u044c]\n\n'''2003-2017: [https://www.namsebangdzo.com/Music-in-the-Sky-p/9788178221939.htm Music in the Sky]'''\n\n* [https://dharmaebooks.org/muzyka-na-niebie/ Muzyka na Niebie]\n\n'''2016: [https://dharmaebooks.org/\u0f56\u0f66\u0fa1\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f56\u0fb2\u0f72\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42/ \u0f56\u0f66\u0fa1\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f56\u0fb2\u0f72\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f66\u0f74\u0f58\u0f0d The Radiant Smile of Jamyang Zhepa]'''\n\n'''2015: [https://karmapafoundation.eu/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/Nurturing-Compassion_ENG.pdf Nurturing Compassion]''' (Teachings from the First Visit to Europe)\n\n* [https://karmapafoundation.eu/kfe-publications/nurturing-compassion/ Available in 13 languages]\n\n'''2013-2014: The Heart Is Noble: Changing the World from the Inside Out''' ([https://www.namsebangdzo.com/Heart-Is-Noble-Changing-the-World-from-the-Inside-p/9781611800807.htm print] | [https://www.amazon.com/Heart-Noble-Changing-World-Inside-ebook/dp/B00BSZUCOK/ref=sr_1_1?keywords=The+Heart+is+Noble&qid=1570771482&sr=8-1 ebook])\n\n* [https://www.namsebangdzo.com/Heart-is-Noble-23815-39640-20043-24515-p/9789866091209.htm \u5d07\u9ad8\u4e4b\u5fc3]\n* [https://www.namsebangdzo.com/Heart-Is-Noble-Changing-the-World-from-the-Inside-p/9788478089062.htm Corazon es Noble Como Cambiar el Mundo Desde Dentro Hacia Fuera]\n\n'''2007-2011: [http://www.ktdpublications.com/kagyu-monlam-books/ The Kagyu Monlam Book]'''\n\n'''2009: [https://www.namsebangdzo.com/Future-Is-Now-p/15858.htm The Future is Now: Timely Advice for Creating a Better World]'''\n\n'''2009: [http://www.ktdpublications.com/traveling-the-path-of-compassion/ Traveling the Path of Compassion: A Commentary on The Thirty-Seven Practices of a Bodhisattva]'''\n\n* [https://dharmaebooks.org/na-sciezce-wspolczucia/ Na \u015bcie\u017cce wsp\u00f3\u0142czucia]\n\n'''2006: [http://www.ktdpublications.com/ceremony-of-offering/ Ceremony of Offering to the Gurus]'''<ref>This list may not include ''all'' publications by Ogyen Trinley Dorje; in particular, titles published in Chinese.</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n{{Main|Karmapa controversy}}\n[[Mipham Chokyi Lodro]], 14th [[Shamarpa]] (the second-longest recognized tulku lineage in the Karma Kagyu tradition, and who in previous incarnations has held and transmitted the Kagyu lineage between Karmapas), did not recognize Ogyen Trinley Dorje and instead proclaimed [[Trinley Thaye Dorje]] ({{bo|w=Mtha'-yas Rdo-rje}}), whom he purportedly identified a few years earlier than the recognition of Orgyen Thrinley Dorje in a dream as the true Karmapa. Shamarpas camp argue that until the reincarnation line of the Shamarpas was forbidden by the government of the Dalai Lama,<ref>see: [[Shamarpa#Controversy]]</ref> the successive Shamarpas were the persons in charge to recognize the Karmapas, whereas the [[Dalai Lama]]s played no role in the recognition.<ref>[https://karmapaissue.wordpress.com/affirmation-of-prof-samuel-geoffrey-concerning-the-historical-role-of-the-dalai-lamas-in-recognizing-the-karmapas/ Prof. Geoffrey Brian Samuel in: \u201cAffirmation of Geoffrey Brian Samuel,\u201d Lama vs. Hope and Ors, CIV-2004404-001363, High Court of New Zealand Auckland Registry, 11 November 2004].</ref>\n\nMany of the previous Karmapas have left a letter stating the details of their rebirth (this is an aspect of the special self-recognizing [[siddhi]] of the Karmapas) to assist in the recognition of their future incarnation, and thus the Shamarpa's recognition through a dream has come under scrutiny. On the other side Shamarpa questioned the authenticity of the \"prophecy letter\" which the 16th Karmapa allegedly had written and asked Situ Rinpoche for a forensic test of the letter, which Situ Rinpoche refused.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://karmapaissue.wordpress.com/2015/03/10/the-letter-of-prediction/ |title = The \"letter of prediction\"|date = 10 March 2015}}</ref> Ogyen Trinley Dorje is supported by the majority of the Kagyu hierarchy,<ref>{{cite news |title=Tibetan Lama Faces Scrutiny and Suspicion in India |first=Jim |last=Yardley |authorlink=Jim Yardley |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/08/world/asia/08tibet.html?pagewanted=all |newspaper=New York Times |date=2011-02-08 |accessdate=2011-02-08 |quote=After the death of the previous Karmapa, a bitter feud broke out between the high lamas charged with identifying his successor: at least two other people now claim to be the Karmapa, though a majority of Tibetans, including the Dalai Lama, recognize Ogyen Trinley Dorje. |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wM5g7lzg?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/08/world/asia/08tibet.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all |archivedate=2011-02-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> including two lamas who have played a role in finding previous Karmapas: [[Tai Situpa]] and [[Goshir Gyaltsab]]. A fourth such lama, the 3rd [[Jamgon Kongtrul]], died early on during the controversy. Ogyen Trinley Dorje was enthroned at [[Tsurphu Monastery]].\n\nOther high Kagyu lamas who support Ogyen Trinley Dorje include the 9th [[Traleg Kyabgon Rinpoche]];{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}} the 9th [[Thrangu Rinpoche]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rinpoche.com/controversy.htm |title=The Karmapa Controversy |work=HomePage of Thrangu Rinpoche |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wM6qZszC?url=http://www.rinpoche.com/controversy.htm |archivedate=2011-02-09 |accessdate=2011-02-08 |quote=I have concluded with absolute certainty that Urgyen Trinley Drodul Dorje from Tibet is the 17th Karmapa. |url-status=dead }}</ref> the 7th [[Dzogchen Ponlop Rinpoche]] and his [[Nalandabodhi]] organization;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nalandabodhi.org/teachers/lineage-masters.aspx |title=Lineage Masters |year=2009 |work=Nalandabodhi: Gateway to the Buddhist Science of Mind |publisher=Nalandabodhi |accessdate=2011-02-08}}</ref> the 12th Surmang [[Choseng Trungpa]]; the 7th [[Yongey Mingyur Rinpoche]];{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}} the 3rd [[Tenga Rinpoche]];<ref>[http://www.karmapa-europe.net/html/lettre_tenga_rinpoche.html Lettre de Tenga Rinpoch\u00e9 \u00e0 Sharmapa et Topgala] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805165115/http://www.karmapa-europe.net/html/lettre_tenga_rinpoche.html |date=2011-08-05 }}</ref> the [[Third Bardor Tulku Rinpoche]]; [[Khenpo Tsultrim Gyamtso Rinpoche]]; [[Bokar Tulku Rinpoche]];<ref>[http://www.karmapa-europe.net/html/lettre_bokar_rinpoche.html Lettre de Bokar Rinpoch\u00e9 \u00e0 Sharmapa et Topgala]</ref> [[Khenpo Karthar Rinpoche]] (abbot of [[Karma Triyana Dharmachakra]]);<ref>[http://www.kagyu.org/gallery/index.php?ktora=ktd&year=2008&cat_id=280]</ref> [[Sakyong Mipham]] and his organization, [[Shambhala Buddhism]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shambhala.org/community/2008/karmapa.php |title=Shambhala Welcomes His Holiness the Seventeenth Karmapa to America! |year=2008 |work=shambhala.org |publisher=Shambhala International (Vajradhatu) |location=Halifax, Nova Scotia |accessdate=2011-02-08}}</ref> Drupon Rinpoche and Lama Norlha Rinpoche, among others. He is also recognized as Karmapa by both the current [[14th Dalai Lama]] and the government of [[China]].\n\nAlso sided with Orgyen Trinley Dorje are tulkus he has identified, such as the 11th [[Nenang Pawo]], and those identified by Tai Situ Rinpoche such as the 3rd [[Kalu Rinpoche]]. There are now two recognitions of the 4th [[Jamgon Kongtrul]], one sided with each Karmapa.\n\n=== 2011 police raid on Karmapa offices ===\n\nIn January 2011, the Himachal Pradesh Police seized money in currencies of 25 countries including China, valued at over {{INR}} 60 million, during raids on the offices of a trust backed by Ogyen Trinley Dorje.<ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article1134697.ece\n| title = Foreign currency seized from monastery\n| publisher = The Hindu\n| date = 2011-01-29\n| accessdate = 2011-01-29\n| location=Chennai, India\n}}</ref> They also seized several [[traveler's cheque]]s and land deal documents, suspecting a [[hawala]] scam. Initially, the police suspected that the money was being used to spread Chinese influence in India, and that the Karmapa was a Chinese agent helping the Chinese government control Buddhist monasteries in India.<ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_money-stashing-karmapa-may-be-tried_1500335\n| title = Money-stashing karmapa may be tried\n| publisher = [[DNA (newspaper)|DNA]]\n| authors = Vineeta Pandey & Ajay Bharadwaj \n| date = 2011-01-29\n| accessdate = 2011-01-29\n}}</ref> They said even if the Karmapa was able to explain the source of the money recovered, he might be held liable for violating the Foreign Exchange Regulation Act.<ref name=\"DNAINDIA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_no-clue-about-the-cash-karmapa_1500661 |title=No clue about the cash:Karmapa|publisher=DNAINDIA |accessdate=29 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Karmapa denied all the allegations and said that the seized money came via the donations from his followers.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.hindu.com/2011/02/01/stories/2011020158031500.htm | title = China denies Karmapa links, Tibetans express anger | author = Ananth Krishnan | date = 2011-01-29 | accessdate = 2011-02-01 | publisher = [[The Hindu]] | location=Chennai, India}}</ref> A ''New York Times'' report on the matter noted that an unnamed rival Karmapa candidate has \"close ties to Indian intelligence officials.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = China: Officials Say Tibetan Lama Is Not a Chinese Spy as India Says | first = Edward | last = Wong | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/05/world/asia/05briefs-China.html | newspaper = New York Times | date = 2011-02-04 | accessdate = 2011-02-08 | archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5wM5CQfF3?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/05/world/asia/05briefs-China.html?_r=1 | archivedate = 2011-02-08 | url-status = dead }}</ref> On 11 February 2011, it was reported that the central Indian government had cleared the Karmapa of all charges, finding that the money in question had been donated by followers.<ref>\"[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/12/world/asia/12briefs-India.html India: Tibetan Lama Cleared in Cash Inquiry, Report Says].\" The New York Times, 11 February 2011.</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, the Himachal Pradesh Police filed a chargesheet against Ogyen Trinley Dorje, naming him as an accused in the cash and foreign currency seizure case.<ref>[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2011/12/08/international/i003657S56.DTL India police charge Tibet holy man in money probe]. San Francisco Chronicle, 8 December 2011.</ref> The Karmapa's office claimed that Dorje was not involved in the financial administration.<ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/-Karmapa-not-involved-in-financial-administration-of-office-/885568/ \u2018Karmapa not involved in financial administration of office\u2019]. Indian Express, 9 December 2011.</ref>\n\n====Charges dropped====\nIndian police said on Tuesday 24 April 2012 that they had dropped all criminal charges against Ogyen Trinley Dorje.<ref>[http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/a/-/world/13513919/india-drops-charges-against-top-tibetan-monk/ The West Australian]</ref>\n\n====Criminal proceedings opened====\nA judge at the Himachal Pradesh High Court issued an order for authorities to open criminal proceedings over the recovery of around 1 million USD in foreign currency during a raid on his Buddhist monastery. His spokesman stated that \"He strongly believes truth will prevail at the end\".<ref>http://news.sky.com/story/1515983/top-tibetan-monk-on-money-laundering-charge</ref>\nKarmapa, along with nine other accused, was charged on 7 December 2012 and was asked by the court to appear personally on 6 March 2013. He failed to appear as he was out of Dharamsala. All the accused were {{Asof|2015|07|lc=y}} on bail.<ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/karmapa-ogyen-trinley-dorje-suffers-high-court-blow/1/450133.html Start Criminal Proceedings against Karmapa: Himachal HC to Govt], in ''[[India Today]]'', July 09, 2015, Retrieved 26 November 2018</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Karmapa controversy]]\n* [[Kagyu]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* ''The Dance of 17 Lives : The Incredible True Story of Tibet's 17th Karmapa'', by Mick Brown. New York, NY: Bloomsbury USA, 2005. {{ISBN|1-58234-598-8}}\n* ''Music in the Sky: The Life, Art & Teachings of the 17th Karmapa Ogyen Trinley Dorje'', by Michele Martin.  Ithaca, New York: Snow Lion Press, 2003.  {{ISBN|1-55939-195-2}}.\n* ''Karmapa of Tibet: The Politics of Reincarnation'', by Lea Terhune. Somerville, MA: Wisdom Publications, 2004. {{ISBN|0-86171-180-7}}\n* [http://www.facenfacts.com/NewsDetails/18612/tibet-vulnerable-to-climate-change-says-karmapa.htm  Tibet vulnerable to climate change] ( FacenFacts)\n* [http://www.kagyu.org/ Karma Triyana Dharmachakra \u2013 The Office of Ogyen Trinley Dorje's center and branches in the United States] (re-retrieved Feb 1, 2011)\n* [http://www.ted.com/talks/lang/eng/his_holiness_the_karmapa_the_technology_of_the_heart.html TED.com Talk: \"The technology of the heart\" (Live via interpreter), Nov 2009] (retrieved Feb 1, 2011)\n* [http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/the-karmapa-breaks-his-silence/358897/ \"The Karmapa breaks his silence\"] Business Standard article dated May 23, 2009 (re-retrieved Feb 1, 2011)\n* [http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1807103,00.html TIME Magazine article on Karmapa] Time.com, May 15, 2008 (re-retrieved Feb 1, 2011)\n* [http://whoiskarmapa.com/ Who Is Karmapa (Karmapa is coming to the USA!)] (re-retrieved Feb 1, 2011)\n* [http://www.simhas.org/ The 17th Karmapa Ogyen Trinley Dorje at Simhas.org] (retrieved Feb 1, 2011)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070223012938/http://www.karmapa.net/ 17th Karmapa Ogyen Trinley Dorje Links at Karmapa.net] (re-retrieved Feb 1, 2011)\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n\n*[https://www.facebook.com/AryaKshema/ Arya Kshema]\n*[https://adarsha.dharma-treasure.org Adarsha]\n*[http://dharmaebooks.org Dharma Ebooks]\n*[https://dharma-treasure.org Dharma Treasure]\n*{{TED speaker|2=His Holiness the Karmapa}}\n*[http://www.kagyumonlam.org/ Kagyu Monlam]\n*[https://digital-toolbox.dharma-treasure.org Ketaka]\n*[http://www.khoryug.com Khoryug]\n*[https://issuu.com/layjang Layjang \u2013 Karmapa's Office Bulletin]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/karmapa Official Facebook page]\n*[https://www.instagram.com/karmapa/ Official Instagram page]\n*[https://twitter.com/karmapa17 Official Twitter page]\n*{{Official website|http://www.kagyuoffice.org/}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/user/Karmapateachings Official YouTube channel]\n*[https://kagyuoffice.org/karmapa-podcast/ Podcasts]\n*[https://kagyuoffice.org/teachings/ Teachings]\n*[https://kagyuoffice.org/karmapa-videos/ Video Library]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|bu}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rangjung Rigpe Dorje]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Karmapa|Reincarnation of the Karmapa]]<br /><sup>Co-claimant along with [[Thaye Dorje]]</sup>|years=1992-present<br />Recognized in 1992}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Karmapas}}\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dorje, Ogyen Trinley}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Lamas]]\n[[Category:21st-century Tibetan people]]\n[[Category:Buddhist monks from Tibet]]\n[[Category:Karmapa claimants|*]]\n[[Category:Lamas from Tibet]]\n[[Category:Rinpoches]]\n[[Category:Tibetan dissidents]]\n[[Category:Tibetan environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Tibetan Lamas]]\n[[Category:Tibetan poets]]\n[[Category:Tibetan writers]]\n[[Category:Tulkus]]\n[[Category:Buddhist vegetarianism]]\n[[Category:Vegetarianism activists]]\n", "name_user": "Discospinster", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 9 bare reference(s) with reFill 2 - remove squatted domain", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ogyen_Trinley_Dorje"}
{"title_page": "Hillary Clinton email controversy", "text_new": "An extensive Russian disinformation campaign to sabotage Hillary and help her opponent cost her the presidential election despite winning the popular vote\n\nSome experts, officials, and members of [[United States Congress|Congress]] contended that Clinton's use of a private [[Message transfer agent|messaging system]] and a private server violated federal law, specifically 18 U.S. Code \u00a7\u202f1924, regarding the unauthorized removal and retention of classified documents or materials, as well as State Department protocols and procedures, and regulations governing [[recordkeeping]]. Clinton responded that her use complied with federal laws and State Department regulations, and that former secretaries of state had also maintained personal email accounts. News reports by NBC and CNN indicated that the emails discussed \"innocuous\" matters already available in the public domain. For example, the [[Drone strikes in Pakistan|CIA drone program]] has been widely discussed in the public domain \n\nThe controversy was a major point of discussion and contention during the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]], in which Clinton was the Democratic nominee. In May, the [[Office of the Inspector General of the Department of State|State Department's Office of the Inspector General]] released a report about the State Department's email practices, including Clinton's. In July, FBI director [[James Comey]] announced that the FBI investigation had concluded that Clinton had been \"extremely careless\" but recommended that no charges be filed. Clinton's opponent, then presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]], used the nickname \"Crooked Hillary\" to criticize Clinton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/01/05/trumps-nicknames-for-rivals-from-rocket-man-to-pocahontas.html|title=Trump's nicknames for rivals, from 'Rocket Man' to 'Pocahontas'|first=Kaitlyn|last=Schallhorn|date=April 17, 2018|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2016, days before the election, Comey notified Congress that the FBI had started looking into newly discovered emails. On November 6, Comey notified Congress that the FBI had not changed its original conclusion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/2016/11/06/fbi-not-recommending-charges-over-new-clinton-emails/93395808/|work=USA Today|title=FBI declares it is finally done investigating Hillary Clinton's email|authors=Schouten, Fredreka, Kevin Johnson & Heidi Przybyla|date=November 6, 2016}}</ref> Comey's timing was contentious, with critics saying that he had violated Department of Justice guidelines and precedent, and prejudiced the public against Clinton.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/11/james-comey-fbi-clinton-230851|title=Will Comey survive the Clinton email flap?|work=Politico|access-date=April 18, 2018}}</ref> The controversy received more media coverage than any other topic during the presidential campaign.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cjr.org/analysis/fake-news-media-election-trump.php|title=Don't blame the election on fake news. Blame it on the media.|work=Columbia Journalism Review|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://shorensteincenter.org/news-coverage-2016-national-conventions/|title=News Coverage of the 2016 National Conventions: Negative News, Lacking Context|date=September 21, 2016|work=Shorenstein Center|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://cyber.harvard.edu/publications/2017/08/mediacloud|title=Partisanship, Propaganda, and Disinformation: Online Media and the 2016 U.S. Presidential Election {{!}} Berkman Klein Center|website=cyber.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=December 7, 2017}}</ref> Clinton and other observers argue that the reopening of the investigation contributed to her loss in the election. In April 2018, Comey said in his new book \"A Higher Loyalty\" that, in hindsight, he wondered about whether his decision was unconsciously influenced by the fact that he thought it extremely likely that Clinton would become the next President.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/13/james-comey-clinton-investigation-poll-numbers-522958|title=Fact-check: Comey didn't say he reopened Clinton investigation because of poll numbers|work=Politico|access-date=April 18, 2018}}</ref> On June 14, 2018, the Department of Justice's Office of the Inspector General released [[Inspector General report on FBI and DOJ actions in the 2016 election|its report]] on the FBI's and DOJ's handling of Clinton's investigation, finding no evidence of political bias and lending support for the decision to not prosecute Clinton.<ref name=\"highlights\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/live-news/inspector-general-report-clinton-email-investigation-2018-06-14-live-updates/|title=Highlights of DOJ inspector general report on handling of Clinton email probe|date=June 14, 2018|work=CBS News|access-date=June 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|4}}\n\n==Background==\n===Clinton's use of BlackBerrys===\n[[File:U.S. Air Force Col. Peggy Poore, commander, 65th Air Base Wing, greets Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton during a stop at Lajes Field, Azores, Portugal, June 3, 2009 090603-F-MK264-040.jpg|thumb|Clinton holding a Blackberry phone in 2009]]\nPrior to her appointment as Secretary of State in 2009, Clinton and her circle of friends and colleagues communicated via [[BlackBerry]] phones.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/how-clintons-email-scandal-took-root/2016/03/27/ee301168-e162-11e5-846c-10191d1fc4ec_story.html|title=How Clinton's email scandal took root|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> State Department security personnel suggested this would pose a security risk during her tenure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/26/us/politics/state-department-hillary-clinton-emails.html|title=Hillary Clinton Is Criticized for Private Emails in State Dept. Review|date=May 26, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> The email account used on Clinton's BlackBerry was then hosted on a private server in the basement of her home in [[Chappaqua, New York]], but that information was not disclosed to State Department security personnel or senior State Department personnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/may/31/hillary-clinton/fact-checking-hillary-clintons-claim-her-email-pra|title=Not 'allowed': Clinton's email talk misses the mark|publisher=politifact.com|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSetting up a secure desktop computer in her office was suggested, but Clinton was unfamiliar with their use<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/27/us/politics/hillary-clinton-state-department-email-inquiry.html|title=Hillary Clinton Wasn't Adept at Using a Desktop for Email, Inquiry Is Told|date=May 27, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> and opted for the convenience of her BlackBerry,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-31819843|title=Hillary Clinton: Private email set up for 'convenience'|publisher=BBC|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> not the State Department, government protocol of a secured desktop computer. Efforts to find a secure solution were abandoned by Clinton,<ref name=\"lawnewz.com\">{{cite web|url=http://lawnewz.com/high-profile/we-now-know-more-about-why-clinton-set-up-private-server-and-its-sketchyy/|title=NSA Refused Clinton a Secure Phone, She Set Up Private Server Instead|publisher=lawnewz.com|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> and she was warned by State Department security personnel about the vulnerability of an unsecured BlackBerry to hacking.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2015/3/3/govt-cybersecurity-source-clintons-office-warned-private-email-use.html|title=Revealed: Clinton's office was warned over private email use|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> She affirmed her knowledge of the danger, and was reportedly told that the [[Bureau of Diplomatic Security]] had obtained intelligence about her vulnerability while she was on a trip to Asia, but continued to use her BlackBerry outside her office.<ref name=\"WP032716\">{{cite news|author1=Robert O'Harrow Jr.|title=How Clinton's email scandal took root|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/how-clintons-email-scandal-took-root/2016/03/27/ee301168-e162-11e5-846c-10191d1fc4ec_story.html|accessdate=March 28, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=March 27, 2016|quote=\"The issue here is one of personal comfort\", one of the participants in that meeting, Donald Reid, the department's senior coordinator for security infrastructure, wrote afterward in an email that described Clinton's inner circle of advisers as \"dedicated [BlackBerry] addicts\". ... \"Her attention was drawn to the sentence that indicates (Diplomatic Security) have intelligence concerning this vulnerability during her recent trip to Asia. ... \"}}</ref>\n\n===Domain names and email server===\n[[File:Clintonemail.com Outlook Web App.png|thumb|A screenshot of the default Outlook Web App login page that is displayed when navigating to [https://mail.clintonemail.com/owa Clinton's email service]]]\nAt the time of Senate confirmation hearings on Hillary Clinton's nomination as Secretary of State, the [[domain name]]s clintonemail.com, wjcoffice.com, and presidentclinton.com were [[Domain registration|registered]] to Eric Hoteham,<ref name=\"ABCNews.Hoteham\">{{cite web|title=Hillary Clinton Email Mystery Man: What We Know About Eric Hoteham|author=Meghan Keneally|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/hillary-clinton-email-mystery-man-eric-hoteham/story?id=29413827|date=March 5, 2015|publisher=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=March 19, 2015}} (The name Eric Hoteham is similar to that of Eric Hothem, a former Clinton aide.)</ref> with the home of Clinton and her husband in Chappaqua, New York, as the contact address.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://washington.cbslocal.com/2015/03/04/clinton-private-server-listed-under-mysterious-untraceable-name|title=Who Is Eric Hoteham? Clinton Private Server Listed Under Mysterious, Untraceable Name|publisher=Washington.cbslocal.com|date=March 4, 2015|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sick|first=Gary|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/03/hillary-clinton-email-5-questions-115876.html|title=5 questions: The Clinton email|publisher=Politico.com|date=March 9, 2015|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref> The domains were pointed to a private email server that Clinton (who never had a state.gov email account) used to send and receive email, and which was purchased and installed in the Clintons' home for [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2008|her 2008 presidential campaign]].<ref name=NYT8815>{{cite news|author1=Scott Shane  |author2=Michael S. Schmidt|title=Hillary Clinton Emails Take Long Path to Controversy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/09/us/hillary-clinton-emails-take-long-path-to-controversy.html|accessdate=August 8, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=August 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe email server was located in the Clintons' home in Chappaqua, New York, from January 2009 until 2013, when it was sent to a [[data center]] in New Jersey before being handed over to Platte River Networks, a Denver-based [[information technology]] firm that Clinton hired to manage her email system.<ref name=AP0813 /><ref>Natasha Bertrand, [http://www.businessinsider.com/platte-river-hillary-clinton-private-server-2015-8 \"VP of Cybersecurity Firm Hired by Hillary Clinton: 'We would never have taken it on' if we knew of the ensuing chaos\"], ''Business Insider'', August 19, 2015.</ref><ref name=WP81215>{{cite news|author1=Tom Hamburger  |author2=Karen Tumulty|title=Hillary Clinton's e-mail server turned over to FBI|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/clintons-e-mail-server-turned-over-to-fbi/2015/08/12/aba5feea-4160-11e5-8ab4-c73967a143d3_story.html|accessdate=August 14, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=August 12, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Clintonserver>{{cite news|last1=Labott|first1=Elise|title=Hillary Clinton to turn over private email server to Justice Department|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/11/politics/hillary-clinton-email-server-justice-department/index.html|accessdate=August 12, 2015|publisher=CNN|date=August 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=server>{{cite news|last1=Dilanian|first1=Ken|title=Clinton relents, gives up possession of private email server|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/40f1d5d9d6cc411a83e8466253e6ef3e/us-official-fbi-has-hillary-clinton-emails-home-server|agency=Associated Press|date=August 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe server itself runs a [[Microsoft Exchange Server|Microsoft Exchange 2010]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2015/03/clintons-email-hosted-on-exchange-2010-server-now-not-in-chappaqua|title=Update: Clinton's e-mail is on a hosted Exchange 2010 server, not in Chappaqua|access-date=July 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mail.clintonemail.com/owa|title=Outlook Web App|website=mail.clintonemail.com|access-date=July 6, 2016}}</ref> server with access to emails over the internet being delivered by [[Outlook Web App]]. The web page is secured with a [[TLS/SSL|TLS certificate]] to allow information to be transmitted securely when using the website. However, for the first two months of its use \u2013 January 2009 through March 29, 2009 \u2013 the web page was reportedly not secured with a TLS certificate, meaning that information transmitted using the service was unencrypted and may have been liable to interception.<ref name=\"WP032716\"/>. HOWEVER THERE IS NO EVIDENCE AT ALL SHOWING IT WAS.\n\n===Initial awareness===\nAs early as 2009, officials with the [[National Archives and Records Administration]] (NARA) expressed concerns over possible violations of normal federal government record-keeping procedures at the State Department under then-Secretary Clinton.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gerstein|first=Josh|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/03/state-department-email-rule-hillary-clinton-115804.html?hp=t4_r|title=Clinton private email violated 'clear-cut' State Dept. rules|publisher=Politico.com|date=March 6, 2015|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, near the end of Clinton's tenure as Secretary of State, a nonprofit group called [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]], or CREW, filed a [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|FOIA]] request seeking records about her email. CREW received a response in May 2013: \"no records responsive to your request were located.\"<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">O'Harrow Jr., Robert.  [https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/how-clintons-email-scandal-took-root/2016/03/27/ee301168-e162-11e5-846c-10191d1fc4ec_story.html \"How Clinton's email scandal took root\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'''', March 27, 2016.</ref> Emails sent to Clinton's private clintonemail.com address were first discovered in March 2013, when a hacker named \"[[Guccifer]]\" widely distributed emails sent to Clinton from [[Sidney Blumenthal]], which Guccifer obtained by illegally accessing Blumenthal's email account.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=Hacker Begins Distributing Confidential Memos Sent To Hillary Clinton On Libya, Benghazi Attack|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/buster/sidney-blumenthal/hacker-distributes-memos-784091|website=The Smoking Gun|accessdate=September 30, 2015|date = March 18, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title=Hacked Emails Show Hillary Clinton Was Receiving Advice at a Private Email Account From Banned, Obama-Hating Former Staffer |url=http://gawker.com/5991563/hacked-emails-show-hillary-clinton-was-receiving-advice-at-a-private-email-account-from-banned-obama-hating-former-staffer |accessdate=September 30, 2015 |first=John |last=Cook |website=Gawker |date=March 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001023951/http://gawker.com/5991563/hacked-emails-show-hillary-clinton-was-receiving-advice-at-a-private-email-account-from-banned-obama-hating-former-staffer |archivedate=October 1, 2015  }}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|title='Guccifer' hacks Hillary Clinton's e-emails via aide's account|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2013/03/19/guccifer-hacker-hillary-clinton-sidney-blumenthal-george-hw-bush/2001429/|accessdate=September 30, 2015|website=USA Today|date=March 22, 2013|last=Acohido|first=Byron}}</ref> The emails dealt with the [[2012 Benghazi attack]] and other issues in [[Libya]] and revealed the existence of her clintonemail.com address.<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\":2\"/>\n\nBlumenthal did not have a security clearance when he received material from Clinton that has since been characterized as classified by the State Department.<ref>Gerstein, Josh. [http://www.politico.com/story/2015/10/hillary-clinton-sidney-blumenthal-emails-benghazi-hearings-215083 \"Clinton's emails from Blumenthal spark tension\"], [[Politico]] (October 22, 2015): \"At least one [email] has been deemed classified by State, including information Clinton sent to Blumenthal, who had no security clearance.\"</ref><ref>Morrison, Micah.  [https://nypost.com/2015/10/31/hillary-clintons-rogue-agenda-why-sid-blumenthal-matters/ \"Hillary Clinton's rogue agenda: Why Sid Blumenthal matters\"], ''[[New York Post]]'', October 31, 2015; \"The November 2009 e-mail was sent by Wilson to Blumenthal, who passed it on to Clinton. Most of Clinton's reply to Blumenthal is redacted as classified.\"</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2014, lawyers from the State Department noticed a number of emails from Clinton's personal account, while reviewing documents requested by the House Select Committee on Benghazi. A request by the State Department for additional emails led to negotiations with her lawyers and advisors. In October, the State Department sent letters to Clinton and all previous Secretaries of State back to [[Madeleine Albright]] requesting emails and documents related to their work while in office. On December 5, 2014, Clinton lawyers delivered 12 file boxes filled with printed paper containing more than 30,000 emails. Clinton withheld almost 32,000 emails deemed to be of a personal nature.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\"/> Datto, Inc., which provided [[data backup]] service for Clinton's email, agreed to give the FBI the hardware that stored the backups.<ref name=WP10715>{{cite news|author1=Tom Hamburger  |author2=Rosalind S. Helderman|title=FBI probe of Clinton e-mail expands to second data company|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/fbi-probe-of-clinton-e-mail-expands-to-second-data-company/2015/10/06/3d94ba46-6c48-11e5-b31c-d80d62b53e28_story.html|accessdate=October 7, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of May 2016, no answer had been provided to the public as to whether 31,000 emails deleted by Hillary Clinton as personal have been or could be recovered.<ref>Emery, Eugene.  [http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/apr/03/hillary-clinton/hillary-clinton-i-have-now-put-out-all-my-emails/ \"Hillary Clinton spins on \u2018Meet the Press,\u2019 says she put out all her emails\"], ''[[Politifact]]'' (April 3, 2016).</ref>\n\nA March 2, 2015 ''[[New York Times]]'' article broke the story that the Benghazi panel had discovered that Clinton exclusively used her own private email server rather than a government-issued one throughout her time as Secretary of State, and that her aides took no action to preserve emails sent or received from her personal accounts as required by law.<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\" /><ref name=\"nytimes.com\">Michael S. Schmidt, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/03/us/politics/hillary-clintons-use-of-private-email-at-state-department-raises-flags.html Hillary Clinton Used Personal Email Account at State Dept., Possibly Breaking Rules], ''The New York Times'', March 2, 2015.</ref><ref>Jack Gillum - \"H [https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/ap-finds-hillary-clinton-used-private-server-official-email/ illary Clinton used private server for official email\"], Associated Press, March 4, 2015. Retrieved November 14, 2016.</ref> At that point, Clinton announced that she had asked the State Department to release her emails.<ref name=NYT0315>{{cite news|author1=Schmidt, Michael S.|title=Hillary Clinton Asks State Department to Vet Emails for Release|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/06/us/politics/hillary-clinton-asks-state-dept-to-review-emails-for-public-release.html?ref=politics&_r=1|accessdate=November 5, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=March 5, 2015}}</ref> Some in the media labeled the controversy \"emailgate.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Anthony |last=Zurcher |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-31806907 |title=Hillary Clinton's 'emailgate' diced and sliced |work=BBC News |date=March 11, 2015 |archivedate=March 12, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312173705/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-31806907 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Kurt |last=Eichenwald |url=http://www.newsweek.com/hillary-clinton-emailgate-312784 |title=Why Hillary Clinton's 'Emailgate' Is a Fake Scandal |work=Newsweek |date=March 3, 2015 |archive-date=March 10, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150310235140/http://www.newsweek.com/hillary-clinton-emailgate-312784 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Margaret |last=Hartmann |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2015/08/hillary-clinton-legal-emailgate.html |title=Could Hillary Clinton Face Criminal Charges Over Emailgate? |work=New York |date=August 21, 2015 |archive-date=November 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20161103202304/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2015/08/hillary-clinton-legal-emailgate.html |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n==Use of private server for government business==\nAccording to Clinton's spokesperson Nick Merrill, a number of government officials have used private email accounts for official business, including secretaries of state before Clinton.<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-hillary-clinton-emails-20150303-story.html|title=Hillary Clinton's use of private email not unusual, but still raises questions|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 3, 2015|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nState Department spokesperson [[Marie Harf]] said that: \"For some historical context, Secretary [[John Kerry|Kerry]] is the first secretary of state to rely primarily on a state.gov email account.\"<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\">Domenico Montanaro, [https://www.npr.org/sections/itsallpolitics/2015/04/02/396823014/fact-check-hillary-clinton-those-emails-and-the-law Fact Check: Hillary Clinton, Those Emails and the Law], NPR (April 2, 2015).</ref> John Wonderlich, a transparency advocate with the [[Sunlight Foundation]], observed while many government officials used private email accounts, their use of private email servers was much rarer.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|title = Howard Dean: 'Tremendous' number of public officials have done what Hillary Clinton did with email|url = http://www.politifact.com/punditfact/statements/2015/aug/18/howard-dean/howard-dean-tremendous-number-public-officials-hav/|website = @politifact|access-date = February 9, 2016}}</ref> A [[Bush White House email controversy|notable exception]] was during the [[George W. Bush|Bush administration]], when dozens of senior White House officials conducted government business via approximately 22 million emails using accounts they had on a server owned by the Republican National Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/2016/09/23/george-w-bush-white-house-lost-22-million-emails-497373.html|title=George W. Bush's White House \"lost\" 22 million emails|first=Nina Burleigh On 9/12/16 at 7:31|last=AM|date=September 12, 2016|website=Newsweek}}</ref>\n\nDan Metcalfe, a former head of the Justice Department's Office of Information and Privacy, said this gave her even tighter control over her emails by not involving a third party such as Google and helped prevent their disclosure by Congressional subpoena. He added: \"She managed successfully to insulate her official emails, categorically, from the FOIA, both during her tenure at State and long after her departure from it\u2014perhaps forever,\" making it \"a blatant circumvention of the [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|FOIA]] by someone who unquestionably knows better.\"<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\" /><ref>{{cite web|title = Hillary's Email Defense Is Laughable|url = http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/03/hillary-clinton-email-scandal-defense-laughable-foia-116116|website = Politico.com|access-date = February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Harf, use by government officials of personal email for government business is permissible under the [[Federal Records Act]], so long as relevant official communications, including all work-related emails, are preserved by the agency. The Act (which was [[Presidential and Federal Records Act Amendments of 2014|amended in late 2014]] after Clinton left office to require that personal emails be transferred to government servers within 20 days) requires agencies to retain all official communications, including all work-related emails, and stipulates that government employees cannot destroy or remove relevant records.<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\"/> NARA regulations dictate how records should be created and maintained, require that they must be maintained \"by the agency\" and \"readily found,\" and that the records must \"make possible a proper scrutiny by the Congress.\"<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\"/> Section 1924 of [[Title 18 of the United States Code]] addresses the deletion and retention of classified documents, under which \"knowingly\" removing or housing classified information at an \"unauthorized location\" is subject to a fine, or up to a year in prison.<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\"/>\n\nExperts such as Metcalfe agree that these practices are allowed by federal law assuming that the material is not supposed to be classified,<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\"/><ref>{{cite web|author1=Bob Cusack  |author2=Molly K. Hooper|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/237012-the-backer-who-could-hurt-hillary|title=The Hillary backer who will pose problems for her 2016 bid|newspaper=The Hill|date=March 26, 2015}}</ref> or at least these practices are allowed in case of emergencies,<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> but they discourage these practices, believing that official email accounts should be used.<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\"/>\n\nJason R. Baron, the former head of [[litigation]] at NARA, described the practice as \"highly unusual\" but not a violation of the law. In a separate interview, he said, \"It is very difficult to conceive of a scenario\u2014short of nuclear winter\u2014where an agency would be justified in allowing its cabinet-level head officer to solely use a private email communications channel for the conduct of government business.\"<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/><ref>Merica, Dan.[https://twitter.com/danmericaCNN/status/572842630855430145 Report via CNN Tweet (March 3, 2015), \"Jason Baron, former head of litigation at the NARA, says Clinton didn't 'violate' the law. 'The Federal Records Act is amorphous enough.'\"]</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Seitz-Wald|first=Alex|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/hillary-clinton-email-problem-not-going-away|title=Hillary Clinton's email problem is not going away|publisher=[[MSNBC]]|date=March 4, 2015|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref> Baron told the Senate Judiciary Committee in May 2015 that \"any employee's decision to conduct all email correspondence through a private email network, using a non-''.gov'' address, is inconsistent with long-established policies and practices under the Federal Records Act and NARA regulations governing all federal agencies.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Eugene Kiely|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2015/09/more-spin-on-clinton-emails|title=More Spin on Clinton Emails|publisher=FactCheck.org|date=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== May 2016 report from State Department's inspector general ===\nIn May 2016, [[Office of the Inspector General of the Department of State|the Department's Office]] of the [[Inspector General of the Department of State|Inspector General]] [[Steve A. Linick]] released an 83-page report about the State Department's email practices.<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\" /><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/apps/g/page/politics/state-department-report-on-clintons-email-practices/2039/?tid=a_inl Office of the Secretary: Evaluation of Email Records Management and Cybersecurity Requirements], Office of the Inspector General of the U.S. Department of State and Broadcasting Board of Governors (May 2016) (republished by ''The Washington Post'').</ref><ref>Morello, Carol and Yang, Jia. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2016/05/25/here-are-the-most-critical-parts-of-the-state-dept-inspector-general-report-on-clintons-email-use/?tid=a_inl Here are the most critical parts of the State Department inspector general report on Clinton\u2019s email use], ''The Washington Post'', May 25, 2016.</ref> The Inspector General was unable to find evidence that Clinton had ever sought approval from the State Department staff for her use of a private email server, determining that if Clinton had sought approval, Department staff would have declined her setup because of the \"security risks in doing so.\"<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\"/> Aside from security risks, the report stated that \"she did not comply with the Department's policies that were implemented in accordance with the Federal Records Act.\"<ref>Dilanian, Ken. [https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/clinton-broke-federal-rules-email-server-audit-finds-n580131 \"Clinton Broke Federal Rules With Email Server, Audit Finds\"], [[NBC News]], May 25, 2016.</ref> Each of these findings contradicted what Clinton and her aides had been saying up to that point.<ref>Lerer, Lisa; Lucey, Catherine. \"[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/ap-fact-check-some-clinton-email-misstatements/ AP Fact Check: Some Clinton email misstatements]\". Associated Press. Public Broadcasting System. May 31, 2016.</ref><ref>Carroll, Lauren. [http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/may/31/hillary-clinton/fact-checking-hillary-clintons-claim-her-email-pra \"Fact-checking Hillary Clinton's claim that her email practices were 'allowed'\"], Polifact, May 31, 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2016/05/ig-report-on-clintons-emails/|title=IG Report on Clinton's Emails| publisher=factcheck.org|author=Kieley, Eugene|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=November 21, 2018}}</ref> The report also stated that Clinton and her senior aides declined to speak with the investigators, while the previous four Secretaries of State did so.<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\"/>\n\nThe report also reviewed the practices of several previous Secretaries of State and concluded that the Department's record keeping practices were subpar for many years.<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\"/> The Inspector General criticized Clinton's use of private email for Department business, concluding that it was \"not an appropriate method\" of document preservation and did not follow Department policies that aim to comply with federal record laws. The report also criticized Colin Powell, who used a personal email account for business, saying that this violated some of the same Department policies.<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\"/> State Department spokesman Mark Toner said the report emphasized the need for federal agencies to adapt \"decades-old record-keeping practices to the email-dominated modern era\" and said that the Department's record-retention practices had been improved under the current Secretary of State [[John F. Kerry]], Clinton's successor.<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\"/> The report also notes that the rules for preserving work-related emails were updated in 2009.<ref>Browne, Ryan and Evan Perez. [http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/25/politics/state-department-report-faults-clinton-over-email-use/ \u201cState Department report slams Clinton email use\u201d], [[CNN]], May 25, 2016: \"while the report acknowledges personal email use by previous secretaries, it also notes that the rules for preserving work emails sent from a personal email account were updated in 2009, the year Clinton took office\".</ref>\n\nInspector General Linick wrote that he \"found no evidence that staff in the Office of the Legal Adviser reviewed or approved Secretary Clinton's personal system,\" and also found that multiple State employees who raised concerns regarding Clinton's server were told that the Office of the Legal Adviser had approved it, and were further told to \"never speak of the Secretary's personal email system again.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/5/25/11771850/hillary-clinton-emails-inspector-general-report|title=What the new inspector general report on Hillary Clinton's emails actually says|author=Andrew Prokop|date=May 25, 2016|work=Vox}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/26/opinions/clinton-email-server-ig-report-opinion-cox/|title=Hillary Clinton's shrinking email defense|author=Douglas Cox|date=May 26, 2016|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2016/05/state-department-hillary-clinton-violated-record-keeping-rules|title=State Department Inspector General Finds Hillary Clinton Violated Recordkeeping Rules|work=Mother Jones}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/26/us/politics/state-department-hillary-clinton-emails.html|title=Hillary Clinton Is Criticized for Private Emails in State Dept. Review|date=May 26, 2016|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nClinton campaign spokesman [[Brian Fallon (press secretary)|Brian Fallon]] issued a statement saying: \"The report shows that problems with the State Department's electronic record-keeping systems were long-standing\" and that Clinton \"took steps that went much further than others to appropriately preserve and release her records.\"<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\" /> However, the Associated Press said, \"The audit did note that former Secretary of State Colin Powell had also exclusively used a private email account. ... But the failings of Clinton were singled out in the audit as being more serious than her predecessor.\"<ref name=\"APMay26Report\">{{cite web|authors=Michael Biesecker & Bradley Klapper|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/e9cf125b8af1417a8cdd0b3526a1ce9e/apnewsbreak-state-dept-audit-faults-clinton-emails|title=Clinton email use broke federal rules: inspector's report|agency=Associated Press|date=May 26, 2016}}</ref> The report stated that \"By Secretary Clinton's tenure, the department's guidance was considerably more detailed and more sophisticated, Secretary Clinton's cybersecurity practices accordingly must be evaluated in light of these more comprehensive directives.\"<ref name=\"APMay26Report\" />\n\n== Server security and hacking attempts ==\n\n===Encryption and security===\nIn 2008, before Hillary Clinton became Secretary of State, [[Justin Cooper (aide)|Justin Cooper]], a longtime aide to Clinton's husband, former President [[Bill Clinton]], managed the system. Cooper had no security clearance or expertise in computer security.<ref name=WP0804>Carol D. Leonnig, Rosalind S. Helderman & Tom Hamburger, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/fbi-looks-into-security-of-clintons-private-e-mail-setup/2015/08/04/2bdd85ec-3aae-11e5-8e98-115a3cf7d7ae_story.html FBI Looking into the Security of Hillary Clinton's Private e-mail Setup], ''The Washington Post'', August 4, 2015.</ref> Later, Bryan Pagliano, the former IT director for Clinton's 2008 presidential campaign, was hired to maintain their private email server while Clinton was Secretary of State.<ref name=WP0901>Helderman, Rosalind S. & Carol D. Leonnig, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/clintons-personally-paid-state-department-staffer-to-maintain-server/2015/09/04/b13ab23e-530c-11e5-9812-92d5948a40f8_story.html \"Clintons personally paid State Department staffer to maintain server\"], ''The Washington Post'', September 5, 2015.</ref><ref name=Joseph0901>Joseph, Cameron.[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/hillary-clinton-won-apologize-private-email-server-article-1.2348855 Hillary Clinton 'takes responsibility' for email controversy, but won't apologize for using private server], ''Daily News'' (New York), September 5, 2015.</ref> Pagliano had invoked the [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] during congressional questioning about Clinton's server. In early 2016, he was granted immunity by the Department of Justice in exchange for cooperation with prosecutors.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perez|first1=Evan|title=DOJ grants immunity to ex-Clinton staffer who set up email server|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/02/politics/hillary-clinton-email-server-justice-department/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 2, 2016|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref> A Clinton spokesman said her campaign was \"pleased\" Pagliano was now cooperating with prosecutors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-clinton-email-investigation-justice-department-grants-immunity-to-former-state-department-staffer/2016/03/02/e421e39e-e0a0-11e5-9c36-e1902f6b6571_story.html|title=Justice Dept. grants immunity to staffer who set up Clinton email server|last=Goldman|first=Adam|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 2, 2016|accessdate=March 3, 2016}}</ref> As of May 2016, the State Department remained unable to locate most of Pagliano's work-related emails from the period when he was employed by that department under Secretary Clinton.<ref>Fishel, Justin.  [http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/emails-found-hillary-clintons-senior-staffer-state-department/story?id=38989504 \"Emails From Hillary Clinton\u2019s IT Director at State Department Appear to Be Missing\"], ''[[ABC News]]'', May 9, 2016.</ref>\n\nSecurity experts such as [[Chris Soghoian]] believe that emails to and from Clinton may have been at risk of [[Hacker (computer security)|hacking]] and [[Computer and network surveillance|foreign surveillance]].<ref name=\"Greenberg\"/> [[Marc Maiffret]], a cybersecurity expert, said that the server had \"amateur hour\" vulnerabilities.<ref name=AP1013/> For the first two months after Clinton was appointed Secretary of State and began accessing mail on the server through her BlackBerry, transmissions to and from the server were apparently not encrypted. On March 29, 2009, a [[Public key certificate|digital certificate]] was obtained which would have permitted encryption.<ref name=\"WP032716\"/>\n\nFormer [[Director of the Defense Intelligence Agency]] [[Michael T. Flynn]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://video.foxnews.com/v/4157397774001/michael-flynn-weighs-in-on-hillary-clinton-email-controversy/?#sp=show-clips/primetime|title=Michael Flynn weighs in on Hillary Clinton email controversy|publisher=Fox News Channel|date=April 6, 2015}}</ref> former [[United States Secretary of Defense]] [[Robert Gates]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/266674-former-defense-secretary-says-clinton-server-may-have-been-compromised|title=Ex-Pentagon chief: Iran, China or Russia may have gotten to Clinton server|work=TheHill}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/600728/did-russia-read-hillary-clintons-emails-robert-gates-says-odds-are-pretty-high|title=Did Russia read Hillary Clinton's emails? Robert Gates says the odds are 'pretty high'|publisher=theweek.com}}</ref> and former deputy director of the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] [[Michael Morell]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/05/michael-morrell-foreign-governments-have-hillarys-email-118007|title=Hillary Clinton emails: Former CIA head says foreign governments have access|newspaper=Politico}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/politics-ideas/hillary-clinton-email-scandal-victim|title=Hillary's Tell-Tale Server|author=Noah Rothman|magazine=Commentary Magazine}}</ref> have said that it is likely that foreign governments were able to access the information on Clinton's server. [[Michael Hayden (general)|Michael Hayden]], former [[Director of the National Security Agency]], Principal Deputy [[Director of National Intelligence]], and [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]] said \"I would lose all respect for a whole bunch of foreign intelligence agencies if they weren't sitting back, paging through the emails.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2016/02/21/ex-nsa-chief-backs-apple-iphone-back-doors/80660024/|title=Ex-NSA chief backs Apple on iPhone 'back doors'|date=February 21, 2016|newspaper=USA Today}}</ref>\n\n===Hacking attempts===\nClinton's server was configured to allow users to connect openly from the Internet and control it remotely using Microsoft's [[Remote Desktop Services]].<ref name=AP1013>{{cite news|author1=Jack Gillum  |author2=Stephen Braun|title=Exclusive: Clinton server's software had hacking risk|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/467ff78858bf4dde8db21677deeff101/only-ap-clinton-server-ran-software-risked-hacking|accessdate=October 13, 2015|agency=Associated Press|date=October 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt is known that hackers were aware of Clinton's non-public email address as early as 2011.<ref>[http://www.cbsnews.com/news/russian-hackers-tried-to-infiltrate-hillary-clintons-emails/ \"Hackers linked to Russia tried to infiltrate Hillary Clinton's emails\"], [[CBS News]] (September 30, 2015): \"these messages show hackers had Clinton's email address, which was not public. ... \"</ref> Secretary Clinton and her staff were aware of hacking attempts in 2011, and were reportedly worried about them.<ref>Gerstein, Josh.  [http://www.politico.com/story/2016/05/clinton-email-problems-223573 \"Why Clinton\u2019s email problems are here to stay\"], ''[[Politico]]'', May 25, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, according to server records, a hacker in [[Serbia]] scanned Clinton's Chappaqua server at least twice, in August and in December 2012. It was unclear whether the hacker knew the server belonged to Clinton, although it did identify itself as providing email services for clintonemail.com.<ref name=AP1013/> During 2014, Clinton's server was the target of repeated intrusions originating in Germany, China, and South Korea. Threat monitoring software on the server blocked at least five such attempts. The software was installed in October 2013, and for three months prior to that, no such software had been installed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2015/10/08/clinton-server-hack-attempts-came-from-china-korea-germany/ADRRitdZev3O1FhIFQT1SP/story.html|title=Sources of attempts to hack Clinton's e-mail server ID'd|accessdate=February 21, 2016|author1=Ken Dilanian  |author2=Jack Gillum}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5ad0f6bb57eb487f84e98fe9a74a08b1/clinton-subject-hack-attempts-china-korea-germany|title=Clinton subject to hack attempts from China, Korea, Germany|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Pagliano, security logs of Clinton's email server showed no evidence of successful hacking.<ref name=\"nyt-apuzzo\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/04/us/politics/security-logs-of-hillary-clintons-email-server-are-said-to-show-no-evidence-of-hacking.html | title=Security Logs of Hillary Clinton's Email Server Are Said to Show No Evidence of Hacking | last=Apuzzo|first=Matt|newspaper=The New York Times| date=March 3, 2016 | accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> The ''New York Times'' reported that \"forensic experts can sometimes spot sophisticated hacking that is not apparent in the logs, but computer security experts view logs as key documents when detecting hackers,\" adding the logs \"bolster Mrs. Clinton's assertion that her use of a personal email account ... did not put American secrets into the hands of hackers or foreign governments.\"<ref name=\"Greenberg\">Andy Greenberg, [https://www.wired.com/2015/03/clintons-email-server-vulnerable Why Clinton's Private Email Server Was Such a Security Failure], ''Wired'', March 4, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"nyt-apuzzo\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/live-from-boulder/2015/10/2016-presidential-debate-hillary-clinton-emails-215291|title=Debate fact check: No evidence Clinton's server was hacked|last=Marks|first=Joseph|newspaper='[[Politico]]|date=October 28, 2015|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Romanian people|Romanian]] hacker Marcel Lehel Laz\u0103r (aka \"[[Guccifer]]\") distributed private memos from [[Sidney Blumenthal]] to Clinton on [[Libyan Civil War (2011)|events in Libya]] that he had acquired by hacking Blumenthal's email account.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/buster/sidney-blumenthal/hacker-distributes-memos-784091|title=Hacker Begins Distributing Confidential Memos Sent To Hillary Clinton On Libya, Benghazi Attack|date=March 18, 2013|website=The Smoking Gun|accessdate=March 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/private-emails-reveal-ex-clinton-aides-secret-spy-network|title=Private Emails Reveal Ex-Clinton Aide's Secret Spy Network|date=March 27, 2015|publisher=ProPublica|accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref> In 2016, Laz\u0103r was extradited from Romania to the U.S. to face unrelated federal charges related to his hacking into the accounts of a number of high-profile U.S. figures,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-guccifer-idUSKCN0WY5MK|title=Hacker 'Guccifer' extradited from Romania, appears in U.S. court|date=April 1, 2016|accessdate=June 11, 2016|agency=Reuters}}</ref> pleading guilty to these charges.<ref>Catherine Herridge & Pamela K. Browne. [http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/05/25/hacker-who-claims-breached-clinton-server-pleads-guilty-strikes-deal-with-feds.html Hacker who claims he breached Clinton server pleads guilty, strikes deal with feds], Fox News (May 25, 2016).</ref><ref>Hosenball, Mark. [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-clinton-emails-hacker-idUSKCN0YF2KZ \"Hacker who exposed Hillary Clinton's email server expected to plead guilty\"], Reuters.com, May 24, 2016.</ref> While detained pending trial, Laz\u0103r claimed to the media that he had successfully hacked Clinton's server, but provided no proof of this claim.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/05/04/us/politics/ap-us-clinton-email.html|title=US Judge: Clinton May Be Ordered to Testify in Records Case|date=May 4, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Officials associated with the investigation told the media that they found no evidence supporting Laz\u0103r's assertion,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/federal-prosecutors-in-virginia-assisting-in-clinton-email-probe/2016/05/05/f0277faa-12f0-11e6-81b4-581a5c4c42df_story.html|title=Officials: Scant evidence that Clinton had malicious intent in handling of emails|date=May 5, 2016|accessdate=May 6, 2016|work=The Washington Post|last=Zapotosky|first=Matt}}</ref> and Clinton press secretary [[Brian Fallon (press secretary)|Brian Fallon]] said \"There is absolutely no basis to believe the claims made by this criminal from his prison cell.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/hacker-guccifer-i-got-inside-hillary-clinton-s-server-n568206|title=Hacker 'Guccifer': I Got Inside Hillary Clinton's Server|author=Cynthia McFadden|publisher=NBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/05/04/romanian-hacker-guccifer-breached-clinton-server-it-was-easy.html?intcmp=hpbt1|title=Romanian hacker Guccifer: I breached Clinton server, 'it was easy'|author=Catherine Herridge, Pamela K. Browne|publisher=Fox News Channel}}</ref> FBI Director James Comey later stated in a congressional hearing that Guccifer admitted his claim was a lie.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-director-set-to-appear-before-congressional-committee-to-answer-questions-on-clinton-investigation/2016/07/07/eb43ec7e-43c1-11e6-88d0-6adee48be8bc_story.html?tid=sm_fb|last=Zapotosky|first=Matt|title=House Republicans grill FBI director Comey on Clinton emails|work=The Washington Post|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to security researchers at [[Secureworks]] the email leak was caused by Threat Group-4127, later attributed to [[Fancy Bear]], a unit that targets governments, military, and international non-governmental organizations. The researchers report moderate confidence that the unit gathers intelligence on behalf of the Russian government.<ref name=\"secureworks.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.secureworks.com/research/threat-group-4127-targets-hillary-clinton-presidential-campaign|title=Hillary Clinton Email Targeted by Threat Group-4127|publisher=secureworks.com|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720175418/https://www.secureworks.com/research/threat-group-4127-targets-hillary-clinton-presidential-campaign#|archive-date=July 20, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Deletion of emails==\n\nIn 2014, months prior to public knowledge of the server's existence, Clinton chief of staff [[Cheryl Mills]] and two attorneys worked to identify work-related emails on the server to be archived and preserved for the State Department. Upon completion of this task in December 2014, Mills instructed Clinton's computer services provider, Platte River Networks (PRN), to change the server's [[retention period]] to 60 days, allowing 31,830 older personal emails to be automatically deleted from the server, as Clinton had decided she no longer needed them. However, the PRN technician assigned for this task failed to carry it out at that time.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2016/09/the-fbi-files-on-clintons-emails/|title=The FBI Files on Clinton's Emails - FactCheck.org|date=September 7, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the existence of the server became publicly known on March 2, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/03/us/politics/hillary-clintons-use-of-private-email-at-state-department-raises-flags.html|title=Hillary Clinton Used Personal Email Account at State Dept., Possibly Breaking Rules|publisher=|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> the [[Select Committee on Benghazi]] issued a subpoena for Benghazi-related emails two days later. Mills sent an email to PRN on March 9 mentioning the Committee's retention request.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\"/> The PRN technician then had what he described to the FBI as an \"oh shit moment,\" realizing he had not set the personal emails to be deleted as instructed months earlier. The technician then erased the emails using a free utility, [[BleachBit]], sometime between March 25 and 31.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/03/us/politics/hillary-clinton-fbi.html|title=F.B.I. Papers Offer Closer Look at Hillary Clinton Email Inquiry|publisher=|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> ''Bloomberg News'' reported in September 2015 that the FBI had recovered some of the deleted emails.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2015/09/23/442797133/fbi-investigators-recover-clinton-emails-thought-to-have-been-deleted|title=FBI Investigators Recover Clinton Emails Thought To Have Been Lost|website=NPR.org}}</ref>\n\nSince this episode, Clinton critics have accused her or her aides of deleting emails that were under subpoena, alleging the server had been \"bleached\" or \"acid-washed\" by a \"very expensive\" process<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2016/09/trump-pence-acid-wash-facts/|title=Trump, Pence 'Acid Wash' Facts - FactCheck.org|date=September 8, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> in an effort to destroy evidence, with candidate Donald Trump stating the day before the 2016 election that \"Hillary Clinton erased more than 30,000 emails as part of a cover-up.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factba.se/search#30,000+emails|title=Donald Trump Complete - Search Tweets, Speeches, Policies - Factbase|last=Factbase|website=Factbase|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> Trump reiterated his position as late as August 2018, asking \"Look at the crimes that Clinton did with the emails and she deletes 33,000 emails after she gets a subpoena from Congress, and this Justice Department does nothing about it?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factba.se/search#emails|title=Donald Trump Complete - Search Tweets, Speeches, Policies - Factbase|last=Factbase|website=Factbase|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Classified information in emails==\nIn various interviews, Clinton has said that \"I did not send classified material, and I did not receive any material that was marked or designated classified.\"<ref name=Allen0821 /> However, in June and July 2016, a number of news outlets reported that Clinton's emails did include messages with some paragraphs marked with a \"(c)\" for \"Confidential.\"<ref name=\"BBC20160705\">{{cite news|author=Staff|title=FBI recommends no charges against Hillary Clinton over emails|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-36711711|work=[[BBC News]]|date=July 5, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016|quote=But investigators found that a number of messages that were marked classified at the time were sent from her account.}}</ref><ref name=\"FoxNews2016-06-11\">{{cite news|last1=Herridge|first1=Catherine|last2=Browne|first2=Pamela K.|date=June 11, 2016|title=Despite Clinton claims, 2012 email had classified marking|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/06/11/despite-clinton-claims-2012-email-had-classified-marking.html|publisher=[[Fox News Channel]]|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\nThe FBI investigation found that 110 messages contained information that was classified at the time it was sent. Sixty-five of those emails were found to contain information classified as \"Secret;\" more than 20 contained \"Top-Secret\" information.<ref name=\"PolitiFact2016-07-06\">{{cite news|last=Carroll|first=Lauren|date=July 5, 2016|title=FBI investigation undermines Clinton email defense|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2016/jul/05/fbi-investigation-undermines-clinton-email-defense|newspaper=[[PolitiFact]]|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Wapo-2016-07-05\">{{cite news|last=Cillizza|first=Chris|date=July 5, 2016|title=Hillary Clinton's email problems might be even worse than we thought|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/07/05/hillary-clintons-email-problems-might-be-even-worse-than-we-thought|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref> Three emails, out of 30,000, were found to be marked as classified, although they lacked classified headers and were only marked with a small \"c\" in parentheses, described as \"portion markings\" by Comey. He added it was possible Clinton was not \"technically sophisticated\" enough to understand what the three classified markings meant<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-james-comey-hillary-clinton-email-probe/story?id=41044927|title=What FBI Director James Comey Really Said About Hillary Clinton Email Probe|publisher=ABC News|date=August 2, 2016|accessdate=September 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.cnbc.com/gallery/?video=3000548237|title=Clinton not technically sophisticated: FBI interview|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=September 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Kiely\">{{cite web|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2016/07/revisiting-clinton-and-classified-information|title=Revisiting Clinton and Classified Information|last=Kiely|first=Eugene|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016|publisher=Factcheck.org}}</ref> which is consistent with Clinton's claim that she wasn't aware of the meaning of such markings.<ref name=\"BusinessInsider20160902\">{{cite web|author=Pamela Engel|title=Hillary Clinton said she didn't know what the 'C' markings in emails stood for|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/hillary-clinton-fbi-report-classified-markings-2016-9|website=[[Business Insider]]|date=September 2, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2018|quote=Hillary Clinton told investigators that she wasn't aware that a \"C\" marking in emails she received on her private server indicated that the information was classified }}</ref>\n\nClinton personally wrote 104 of the 2,093 emails that were retroactively<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/clinton-on-her-private-server-wrote-104-emails-the-government-says-are-classified/2016/03/05/11e2ee06-dbd6-11e5-81ae-7491b9b9e7df_story.html|title=Clinton, on her private server, wrote 104 emails the government says are classified|first1=Rosalind S.|last1=Helderman|first2=Tom|last2=Hamburger|date=March 5, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=April 21, 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/jul/06/hillary-clinton/fbi-findings-tear-holes-hillary-clintons-email-def/|title=FBI tears holes in Hillary Clinton's email defense|publisher=|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2016/jul/19/politifact-sheet-hillary-clintons-email-controvers/|title=The GOP's opening over Hillary Clinton's email|publisher=|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> found to contain information classified as \"confidential.\"<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\">Helderman, Rosalind and Hamburger, Tom. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/state-dept-inspector-general-report-sharply-criticizes-clintons-email-practices/2016/05/25/fc6f8ebc-2275-11e6-aa84-42391ba52c91_story.html State Dept. inspector general report sharply criticizes Clinton's email practices], ''The Washington Post'', May 25, 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/clinton-on-her-private-server-wrote-104-emails-the-government-says-are-classified/2016/03/05/11e2ee06-dbd6-11e5-81ae-7491b9b9e7df_story.html|title=Clinton, on her private server, wrote 104 emails the government says are classified|author=Rosalind S. Helderman|date=March 5, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> Of the remaining emails that were classified after they were sent, Clinton aide [[Jake Sullivan]] wrote the most, at 215.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nAccording to the State Department, there were 2,093 email chains on the server that were retroactively marked as classified by the State Department as \"Confidential,\" 65 as \"Secret,\" and 22 as \"Top Secret.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/01/us/politics/last-batch-of-hillary-clintons-emails-is-released.html|title=Last Batch of Hillary Clinton's Emails Is Released|date=March 1, 2016|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2016-02-29/state-dept-wins-dispute-over-clinton-email-on-north-korea|title=State Dept completes Clinton email release, more than 52k out including 2,100 with info now deemed classified|last=Klapper|first=Bradley|date=February 29, 2016|newspaper=U.S. News and World Report|accessdate=March 1, 2016|last2=Lee|first2=Matthew}}</ref>\n\nAn interagency dispute arose during the investigation about what constitutes \u201cclassified\u201d status when information acquired and considered \u201cowned\u201d by intelligence agencies is also independently and publicly available through \u201cparallel reporting\u201d by the press or others. In one reported instance, an email chain deemed by the intelligence community to contain classified information included a discussion of a ''New York Times'' article that reported on a CIA drone strike in Pakistan; despite wide public knowledge of the drone program, the CIA \u2014 as the \"owning agency\" \u2014 considers the very existence of its drone program to be classified in its entirety. [[Assistant Secretary of State for Legislative Affairs]] [[Julia Frifield]] noted, \"When policy officials obtain information from open sources, \u2018think tanks,\u2019 experts, foreign government officials, or others, the fact that some of the information may also have been available through intelligence channels does not mean that the information is necessarily classified.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/06/us/politics/agencies-battle-over-what-is-top-secret-in-hillary-clintons-emails.html|title=Agencies Battle Over What Is 'Top Secret' in Hillary Clinton's Emails|first1=Steven Lee|last1=Myers|first2=Mark|last2=Mazzetti|date=February 5, 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/secrecy-defines-obamas-drone-war/2011/10/28/gIQAPKNR5O_story.html|title=Secrecy defines Obama's drone war|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n===State Department inspector general reports and statements===\nA June 29, 2015, memorandum from the Inspector General of the State Department, Steve A. Linick, said that a review of the 55,000-page email release found \"hundreds of potentially classified emails.\"<ref name=CNN3>Labott, Elise.[http://www.cnn.com/2015/07/24/politics/hillary-clinton-email-justice-department \"Clinton emails Included Classified Information\"], CNN, July 24, 2015.</ref> A July 17, 2015, follow-up memo, sent jointly by Linick and the [[United States Intelligence Community|Intelligence Community]] (IC) inspector general, I. Charles McCullough III, to [[Under Secretary of State for Management]] [[Patrick F. Kennedy]], stated that they had confirmed that several of the emails contained classified information that was not marked as classified, at least one of which was publicly released.<ref name=CNN3/>\n\nOn July 24, 2015, Linick and McCullough said they had discovered classified information on Clinton's email account,<ref name=NYT72415>{{cite news|author1=Michael S. Schmidt  |author2=Matt Apuzzo|title=Hillary Clinton Emails Said to Contain Classified Data|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/25/us/politics/hillary-clinton-email-classified-information-inspector-general-intelligence-community.html|accessdate=July 25, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=July 24, 2015}}</ref> but did not say whether Clinton sent or received the emails.<ref name=NYT72415/> Investigators from their office, searching a randomly chosen sample of 40 emails, found four that contained classified information that originated from U.S. intelligence agencies, including the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and the National Security Agency (NSA).<ref name=NYT72415/> Their statement said that the information they found was classified when sent, remained so as of their inspection, and \"never should have been transmitted via an unclassified personal system.\"<ref name=NYT72415/>\n\nIn a separate statement in the form of a letter to Congress, McCullough said that he had made a request to the State Department for access to the entire set of emails turned over by Clinton, but that the Department rejected his request.<ref name=NYT72415/><ref name=WSJ3>Byron Tau, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/investigation-sought-into-hillary-clintons-emails-1437714369 Hillary Clinton Sent Classified Information Over Email While at State Department], ''The Wall Street Journal'', July 24, 2015.</ref> The letter stated that none of the emails were marked as classified, but because they included classified information they should have been marked and handled as such, and transmitted securely.<ref name=WSJ3/>\n\nOn August 10, 2015, the IC inspector general said that two of the 40 emails in the sample were \"Top Secret/[[Sensitive Compartmented Information]]\" and subsequently given classified labels of \"TK\" (for \"Talent Keyhole,\" indicating material obtained by aerial or space-based imagery sources and [[NOFORN]]).<ref name=AP81415 /> One is a discussion of a news article about a [[Drone strikes in Pakistan|U.S. drone strike operation]].<ref name=AP81415/> The second, he said, either referred to classified material or else was \"parallel reporting\" of [[open-source intelligence]], which might still be classified by the government \"owning agency\" that sourced the information by secret means even though the same information was also available in the public domain.<ref name=AP81415/><ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|title=US State Department 'Top secret' emails on Clinton server discussed drone program, reference classified info.|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2015/08/14/top-secret-emails-on-clinton-server-discussed-drone-program-may-reference/?intcmp=ob_article_footer_text&intcmp=obinsite|accessdate=August 24, 2015|publisher=Fox News Channel|date=August 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/06/us/politics/agencies-battle-over-what-is-top-secret-in-hillary-clintons-emails.html|title=Agencies Battle Over What Is 'Top Secret' in Hillary Clinton's Emails|date=February 5, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=April 21, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Clinton's presidential campaign and the State Department disputed the letter, and questioned whether the emails had been over-classified by an arbitrary process. According to an unnamed source, a secondary review by the CIA and the [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]] endorsed the earlier inspectors general findings concluding that the emails (one of which concerned North Korea's nuclear weapons program) were \"Top Secret\" when received by Clinton through her private server in 2009 and 2011, a conclusion also disputed by the Clinton campaign.<ref>Schmidt, Michael S. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/08/us/politics/second-review-says-classified-information-was-in-hillary-clintons-email.html \"Second Review Says Classified Information Was in Hillary Clinton's Email\"] ''The New York Times'', September 7, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe IC inspector general issued another letter to Congress on January 14, 2016. In this letter he stated that an unnamed intelligence agency had made a sworn declaration that \"several dozen emails [had been] determined by the IC element to be at the CONFIDENTIAL, SECRET, and TOP SECRET/[[Special access program|SAP]] levels.\" Other intelligence officials added that the several dozen were not the two emails from the previous sample and that the clearance of the IC inspector general himself had to be upgraded before he could learn about the programs referenced by the emails.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Hillary Clinton Email Said to Include Material Exceeding 'Top Secret'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/20/us/politics/hillary-clinton-email-said-to-include-material-exceeding-top-secret.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=January 19, 2016|accessdate=January 20, 2016|issn=0362-4331|first=Mark|last=Mazzetti}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hillary Clinton Emails Held Info Beyond Top Secret: IG|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/hillary-clinton-emails-contained-info-above-top-secret-ig-n499886|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=January 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Intelligence community watchdog reconfirms that dozens of Clinton emails were classified|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/01/19/intelligence-community-watchdog-reconfirms-that-dozens-of-clinton-emails-were-classified|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=January 19, 2016|accessdate=January 20, 2016|issn=0190-8286|first=Rosalind S.|last=Helderman|first2=Tom|last2=Hamburger}}</ref> NBC News reported on January 20, 2016 that senior American officials described these emails as \"innocuous\" because\u2014although they discussed the CIA drone program that is technically classified TOP SECRET/[[Special access program|SAP]]\u2014the existence of the CIA drone program had been widely known and discussed in the public domain for years. These officials characterized the IC inspector general as unfair in how he had handled the issue.<ref name=\"nbcnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/officials-new-top-secret-clinton-emails-innocuous-n500586|title=Officials: New Top Secret Clinton Emails 'Innocuous'|publisher=|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, 2016, the State Department announced that 22 documents from Clinton's email server would not be released because they contained highly classified information that was too sensitive for public consumption. At the same time, the State Department announced that it was initiating its own investigation into whether the server contained information that was classified at the time it was sent or received.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Byron Tau|title=State Department: 22 of Hillary Clinton's Emails Considered Too Classified to Release|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-says-22-of-clintons-emails-contain-highly-classified-information-1454101286|accessdate=February 1, 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=January 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, State Department IG Linick addressed another report to Under Secretary of State Kennedy, stating his office had also found classified material in 10 emails in the personal email accounts of members of former Secretary [[Condoleezza Rice]]'s staff and in two emails in the personal email account of former Secretary of State [[Colin Powell]].<ref name=\"PowellRice\">{{cite news|authors=Jose Pagliery, Deirdre Walsh and Elise Labott|title=State Department: Colin Powell, Condoleezza Rice staffers received classified info via personal email|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/04/politics/hillary-clinton-email-classified-colin-powell-condoleezza-rice/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://i2.cdn.turner.com/cnn/2016/images/02/04/memo.pdf|title=Memorandum for Under Secretary Kennedy|date=February 3, 2016|last=Linick|first=Steve}}</ref> None of the emails were classified for intelligence reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/secretaries-handled-classified-material-private-email-state-dept/story?id=37404084|title=Other Secretaries Handled Classified Material on Private Email, State Dept. Concludes|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> PolitiFact found a year earlier that Powell was the only former secretary of state to use a personal email account.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fact-checking Chuck Schumer's defense of Hillary Clinton's private email|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2015/mar/08/charles-schumer/fact-checking-chuck-schumers-defense-hillary-clint|website=PolitiFact|accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref> In February 2016, Clinton's campaign chairman issued a statement claiming that her emails, like her predecessors,' were \"being inappropriately subjected to over-classification.\"<ref name=\"PowellRice\"/>\n\n===FBI investigation===\n====July 2015 \u2013 Security referral====\nThe State Department and [[United States Intelligence Community|Intelligence Community]] (IC) inspector generals' discovery of four emails containing classified information, out of a random sample of 40, prompted them to make a security referral to the FBI's counterintelligence office, to alert authorities that classified information was being kept on Clinton's server and by her lawyer on a [[USB flash drive|thumb drive]].<ref name=NYT72415 /><ref name=WSJ3/> As part of the FBI's '''Midyear investigation''',<ref name=OIGjune2018>{{cite web |title=A Review of Various Actions by the Federal Bureau of Investigation and Department of Justice in Advance of the 2016 Election |url=https://www.justice.gov/file/1071991/download |publisher=[[Office of the Inspector General]] |accessdate=May 19, 2019 |pages=328,330,397}}</ref> at the request of the IC [[inspector general]], Clinton agreed to turn over her email server to the [[U.S. Department of Justice]], as well as thumb drives containing copies of her work-related emails. Other emails were obtained by the [[United States House Select Committee on Benghazi]] from other sources, in connection with the committee's inquiry. Clinton's own emails are being made public in stages by the State Department on a gradual schedule.<ref>{{cite web|title=House GOP split over Clinton email probe|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/11/hillary-clinton-emails-republicans-server-congress-215498|publisher=Politico|accessdate=November 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/06/tracking-the-clinton-controversies-from-whitewater-to-benghazi/396182|title=From Whitewater to Benghazi: A Clinton-Scandal Primer|work=David A. Graham|date=June 10, 2016|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/personalities/hillary-clinton|title=Hillary Clinton's file|publisher=Politifact.com|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' ran a front-page story on July 24, 2015 with the headline \"Criminal Inquiry Sought In Clinton's Use of Email,\" with the lead sentence stating, \"Two inspectors general have asked the Justice Department to open a criminal investigation into whether Hillary Rodham Clinton mishandled sensitive government information on a private email account she used as secretary of state, senior government officials said Thursday.\"<ref name=\"mediamatters.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2015/07/25/ny-times-issues-second-major-correction-to-botc/204596|title=NY Times Issues Second Major Correction To Botched Report On Clinton's Emails|date=July 25, 2015|publisher=|accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref> Shortly after the publication of the story, the Inspectors General of the Intelligence Community and the\nDepartment of State issued a statement clarifying, \"An important distinction is that the IC IG did not make a [[criminal referral]] - it was a security referral made for counterintelligence purposes.\"<ref>https://www.stateoig.gov/system/files/statement_of_the_icig_and_oig_regarding_review_of_clintons_emails_july_24_2015_0.pdf</ref> The ''Times'' later made two corrections, first that Clinton was not a specific target of the referral, then later that the referral was not \"criminal\" in nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/24/us/politics/inquiry-is-sought-in-hillary-clinton-email-account.html|title=Inquiry Sought in Hillary Clinton's Use of Email|publisher=|accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/research/2015/07/24/ny-times-walks-back-flimsy-report-on-probe-into/204576|title=NY Times Walks Back Flimsy Report On Probe Into Clinton's Email|date=July 24, 2015|publisher=|accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"mediamatters.org\"/>\n\nClinton's IT contractors turned over her personal email server to the FBI on August 12, 2015,<ref name=\"server\"/> as well as thumb drives containing copies of her emails.<ref name=ABC0812>Justin Fishel & Mike Levine, [http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/hillary-clinton-emails-questions-answered/story?id=33037501 Hillary Clinton Emails: Your Questions Answered], ABC News, August 12, 2015.</ref><ref>Anita Kumar, Marisa Taylor & Greg Gordon, [http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article30714762.html \"Top Secret' emails Found as Clinton Probe Expands to Key Aides], McClatchy Washington Bureau, August 11, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn a letter describing the matter to Senator [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]], Chairman of the Senate Homeland Security Committee, Clinton's lawyer [[David E. Kendall]] said that emails, and all other data stored on the server, had earlier been erased prior to the device being turned over to the authorities, and that both he and another lawyer had been given security clearances by the State Department to handle thumb drives containing about 30,000 emails that Clinton subsequently also turned over to authorities. Kendall said the thumb drives had been stored in a safe provided to him in July by the State Department.<ref name=AP0819>{{cite news|last1=Sacks|first1=Mike|title=Clinton Lawyer Informs Congress About Security Clearance, Email Safeguards|url=http://www.nationallawjournal.com/id=1202735059877/Clinton-Lawyer-Informs-Congress-About-Security-Clearance-Email-Safeguards|accessdate=September 19, 2015|work=National Law Journal|date=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====August 2015 \u2013 Investigation continues; email recovery====\nOn August 20, 2015, U.S. District Judge [[Emmet G. Sullivan]] stated that Hillary Clinton's actions of maintaining a private email server were in direct conflict with U.S. government policy. \"We wouldn't be here today if this employee had followed government policy,\" he said, and ordered the State Department to work with the FBI to determine if any emails on the server during her tenure as Secretary of State could be recovered.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jason Donner|title=Judge orders State Dept. to work on recovering emails, suggests Clinton violated policy|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2015/08/20/judge-orders-state-to-work-with-fbi-on-clinton-email-investigation/?intcmp=ob_article_footer_text&intcmp=obnetwork|accessdate=August 27, 2015|publisher=Fox News Channel|date=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Schmidt>{{cite news|last1=Schmidt|first1=Michael|title=Judge Says Hillary Clinton Didn't Follow Government Email Policies|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/21/us/judge-says-hillary-clinton-didnt-follow-government-email-policies.html|accessdate=August 27, 2015|publisher=NYT|date=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Gerstein>{{cite news|last1=Gerstein|first1=Josh|title=Judge says Hillary Clinton's private emails violated policy|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/08/judge-says-hillary-clintons-private-emails-violated-policy-121568.html|accessdate=August 28, 2015|publisher=Politico|date=August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPlatte River Networks, the Denver-based firm that managed the Clinton server since 2013, said it had no knowledge of the server being wiped. \"Platte River has no knowledge of the server being wiped,\" company spokesman Andy Boian told the ''[[Washington Post]]''. \"All the information we have is that the server wasn't wiped.\"<ref name=WP0912>{{cite news|last1=Helderman|first1=Rosalind S.|last2=Hamburger|first2=Tom|last3=Leonnig|first3=Carol D.|title=Tech company: No indication that Clinton's e-mail server was 'wiped'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/tech-company-no-indication-that-clintons-e-mail-server-was-wiped/2015/09/12/10c8ce52-58c6-11e5-abe9-27d53f250b11_story.html|accessdate=September 13, 2015|work=Washington Post|date=September 12, 2015}}</ref> When asked by the ''Washington Post'', the Clinton campaign declined to comment.<ref name=WP0912/>\n\nIn September 2015, FBI investigators were engaged in sorting messages recovered from the server.<ref name=\"wilbur\">{{cite news|author1=Del Quentin Wilber|title=FBI Said to Recover Personal E-Mails From Hillary Clinton Server|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-09-22/fbi-said-to-recover-personal-e-mails-from-hillary-clinton-server|accessdate=September 23, 2015|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|date=September 22, 2015}}</ref> In November 2015, the FBI expanded its inquiry to examine whether Clinton or her aides jeopardized national security secrets, and if so, who should be held responsible.<ref name=Bade1110>Rachael Bade, [http://www.politico.com/story/2015/11/hillary-clinton-email-fbi-probe-215630 \"FBI steps up interviews in Clinton email probe; Questions focus on whether State officials improperly sent classified material\"], Politico.com, November 10, 2015. Retrieved November 14, 2016.</ref><ref name=HNGN1110>Taylor Tyler, [http://www.hngn.com/articles/148950/20151110/clinton-emails-fbi-expands-investigation-email-setup.htm \"Clinton Emails: FBI Expands Investigation Into Clinton Email Setup\"], ''Headlines & Global News'', November 10, 2015. Retrieved November 14, 2016.</ref>\n\n<!-- inclusion and lang per current consensus on Talk -->Conflicting media sources sized the FBI investigation from 12<ref name=\"msnbc-ari\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/fed-source-about-12-fbi-agents-working-clinton-email-inquiry-n548026|publisher=MSNBC|last=Melber|first=Ari|date=March 30, 2016|accessdate=April 29, 2016|title=Fed Source: About 12 FBI Agents Working on Clinton Email Inquiry}}</ref> to 30 agents<ref name=\"time\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4276988/jim-comey-hillary-clinton|work=Time|last=Calabresi|first=Massimo|date=March 31, 2016|accessdate=April 29, 2016|title=Inside the FBI Investigation of Hillary Clinton's E-Mail}}</ref> as of March 2016.<!-- end of current consensus lage per Talk -->\n\n====May\u2013July 2016 \u2013 Public statements====\nIn May 2016, FBI Director [[James Comey]] said he was \"not familiar with the term 'security inquiry'\" as the Clinton campaign was characterizing the probe, adding that the word ''investigation'' is \"in our name\" and \"We're conducting an investigation ... That's what we do. That's probably all I can say about it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/05/hillary-clinton-email-investigation-fbi-james-comey-223071|title=FBI's James Comey: I feel 'pressure' to quickly finish Clinton email probe|publisher=politico.com|date=May 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"fbi.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/pressrel/press-releases/director-comey-remarks-during-may-11-2018pen-and-pad2019-briefing-with-reporters|title=Director Comey Remarks During May 11 'Pen and Pad' Briefing with Reporters|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> Comey noted in his 2018 memoir that he did not publicly contradict Clinton's characterization of the investigation as a \"security inquiry\" while it was underway<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/13/us/politics/comey-book-clinton-emails.html|title=As Clinton Camp Denied Reports of Criminal Inquiry, F.B.I. Was Investigating, Comey Says|publisher=|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> despite being directly prompted by a reporter to do so in May 2016.<ref name=\"fbi.gov\"/> In April 2017 it became known that the FBI had, in fact, opened a criminal investigation on July 10, 2015, telling ''The New York Times'' they had received a \"criminal referral,\" although the following day they issued a public statement: \"The department has received a referral related to the potential compromise of classified information. It is not a criminal referral.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/22/us/politics/james-comey-election.html|title=Comey Tried to Shield the F.B.I. From Politics. Then He Shaped an Election.|publisher=|accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<!-- exact text per RfC on Talk -->\nIn late June 2016, it was reported that Bill Clinton met privately with Attorney General [[Loretta Lynch]] on her private plane on the tarmac at [[Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport]]. Officials indicated that the 30 minute meeting took place when Clinton became aware that Lynch's plane was on the same tarmac at the airport. When the meeting became public, Lynch stated that it was \"primarily social\" and \"there was no discussion of any matter pending for the department or any matter pending for any other body.\" Lynch was criticized for her involvement in the meeting and was called on by some critics to recuse herself from involvement in the FBI's investigation of the email case. In response, she stated \"The F.B.I. is investigating whether Mrs. Clinton, her aides or anyone else broke the law by setting up a private email server for her to use as secretary of state,\" but \"the case will be resolved by the same team that has been working on it from the beginning\" and \"I will be accepting their recommendations.\"<ref name=\"https\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/02/us/politics/loretta-lynch-hillary-clinton-email-server.html|title=Lynch to Accept F.B.I. Recommendations in Clinton Email Inquiry, Official Says |work=NYT|date=July 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/attorney-general-loretta-lynch-calls-perfectly-reasonable-question/story?id=40272091|title=Attorney General Loretta Lynch Calls It 'Perfectly Reasonable' to Question Bill Clinton Meeting|publisher=ABC News|date=July 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/06/30/loretta-lynch-bill-clinton-meeting/86555274/|title=Loretta Lynch, Bill Clinton meeting raises eyebrows|work=USA Today|date=June 30, 2016}}</ref>\n<!-- end of current consensus text per RfC on Talk -->\n\nOn July 1, 2016, the ''New York Times'' reported in the name of a \"Justice Department official\" that Attorney General Loretta Lynch will accept \"whatever recommendation career prosecutors and the F.B.I. director make about whether to bring charges related to Hillary Clinton's personal email server.\"<ref name=\"https\"/>\n\nClinton maintained she did not send or receive any confidential emails from her personal server. In a Democratic debate with [[Bernie Sanders]] on February 4, 2016, Clinton said, \"I never sent or received any classified material.\" In a Meet the Press interview on July 2, 2016, she stated: \"Let me repeat what I have repeated for many months now, I never received nor sent any material that was marked classified.\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-investigation-sheds-light-hillary-clintons-past-email/story?id=40350589|title=FBI Contradicts Clinton's Email Claims on Classified Info|date=July 5, 2016|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=\"politifact.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/jul/06/hillary-clinton/fbi-findings-tear-holes-hillary-clintons-email-def|title=FBI tears holes in Hillary Clinton's email defense|publisher=politifact.com}}</ref><ref name=\"washingtonpost.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2015/08/27/clintons-claims-about-receiving-or-sending-classified-material-on-her-private-email-system|title=Clinton's claims about receiving or sending 'classified material' on her private e-mail system|work=The Washington Post|date=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====July 2016 \u2013 Investigation concludes====\nOn July 5, 2016, FBI Director Comey announced in a statement he read to press and television reporters at FBI headquarters in Washington, DC, that the FBI had completed its investigation and was referring it to the State Department with the recommendation \"that no charges are appropriate in this case.\"<ref name=Comey>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/pressrel/press-releases/statement-by-fbi-director-james-b.-comey-on-the-investigation-of-secretary-hillary-clintons-use-of-a-personal-e-mail-system|title=Statement by FBI Director James B. Comey on the Investigation of Secretary Hillary Clinton's Use of a Personal E-Mail System|publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]|date=July 5, 2016|accessdate=July 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"News\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-completes-investigation-hillary-clintons-personal-email-server/story?id=40346712|title=FBI Recommends No Charges Over Clinton Email Use|first=A.B.C.|last=News|date=July 6, 2016|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=ZapHel>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-chief-plans-remarks-to-media-amid-heightened-focus-on-clinton-email-probe/2016/07/05/a53513c4-42b9-11e6-bc99-7d269f8719b1_story.html|last1=Zapotosky|first1=Matt|last2=Helderman|first2=Rosalind S.|title=FBI recommends no criminal charges in Clinton email probe|work=The Washington Post|date=July 5, 2016|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref> He added, \"Although there is evidence of potential violations of the statutes regarding the handling of classified information, our judgment is that no reasonable prosecutor would bring such a case.\"<ref name=\"Comey\"/><ref name=\"News\"/>\n\nWith regard to mishandling of classified information, Comey said, \"there is evidence that they [Clinton and her team] were extremely careless in their handling of very sensitive, highly classified information.\" The investigation found 110 emails that should have been regarded as classified at the time they were sent; another 2,000 emails were retroactively classified which means they were not classified at the time they were sent.<ref name=\"Comey\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/watch-live-fbi-director-speaks-at-11-a-m-edt|title=FBI director recommends 'no charges' over Clinton's emails|last=Epatko|first=Larisa|date=July 5, 2016|work=PBS|accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref> Comey said that \"any reasonable person in Secretary Clinton's position, or in the position of those government employees with whom she was corresponding ... should have known that an unclassified system was no place for that conversation.\"<ref name=\"FBI-Report\">{{cite web|url=https://vault.fbi.gov/hillary-r.-clinton|title=Clinton e-mail Investigation|publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]|date=July 2016|accessdate=October 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/07/05/politics/fbi-director-doesnt-recommend-charges-against-hillary-clinton/index.html|title=FBI: Clinton 'extremely careless' but no charges recommended|author1=Collinson, Stephen |author2=Tal Kopan|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nThe FBI learned that Clinton used her personal email extensively while outside the United States, both sending and receiving work-related emails in the territory of sophisticated adversaries. The FBI did not find \"direct evidence that Secretary Clinton's personal e-mail domain ... was successfully hacked;\" they assessed it \"possible that hostile actors gained access\" to it.<ref name=Comey/><ref name=ZapHel/> Investigators found that State Department employees often used private emails to conduct business. Comey noted, \"We also developed evidence that the security culture of the State Department in general, and with respect to use of unclassified e-mail systems in particular, was generally lacking in the kind of care for classified information found elsewhere in the government.\"<ref name=\"Graff\">{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/09/hillary-clinton-emails-2016-server-state-department-fbi-214307|title=What the FBI Files Reveal About Hillary Clinton's Email Server|last=Graff|first=Garrett M.|date=September 30, 2016|work=Politico|accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2016, Lynch confirmed that the investigation into Hillary Clinton's use of private email servers while secretary of state would be closed without criminal charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/justice-department-closes-clinton-email-probe-without-charges/2016/07/06/0ad8feda-43c2-11e6-88d0-6adee48be8bc_story.html|last=Zapotosky|first=Matt|title=Justice Department closes Clinton email probe without charges|work=The Washington Post|date=July 6, 2016|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====October 2016 \u2013 Additional investigation====\nIn early October 2016, FBI criminal investigators working on a case involving former Congressman [[Anthony Weiner]] allegedly [[Anthony Weiner sexting scandals|sending sexually explicit texts to a fifteen-year-old girl]] discovered emails from Weiner's estranged wife, [[Huma Abedin]], vice chair of Hillary Clinton's 2016 presidential campaign, that they considered potentially relevant to the Clinton server investigation. FBI officials reportedly decided to disclose the development despite its potential effect on the pending presidential election to preempt the possibility that it would be leaked in another way.<ref name=\"CNN Weiner\">{{cite web|last=Perez|first=Evan|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/30/politics/clinton-emails-fbi-abedin/index.html|title=FBI discovered Clinton-related emails weeks ago|date=October 30, 2016|publisher=CNN|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2016, Comey informed Congress that \"in connection with an unrelated case, the FBI has learned of the existence of emails that appear pertinent to the investigation.\" He said the FBI will take \"appropriate investigative steps designed to allow investigators to review these emails to determine whether they contain classified information, as well as to assess their importance to our investigation.\" He added that the FBI \"cannot yet assess whether or not this material may be significant.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/28/politics/fbi-reviewing-new-emails-in-clinton-probe-director-tells-senate-judiciary-committee/|title=Comey notified Congress of email probe despite DOJ concerns|last1=Perez|first1=Evan|last2=Brown|first2=Pamela|date=October 29, 2016|publisher=CNN|accessdate=October 29, 2016}}</ref> The FBI obtained a new search warrant to allow them to review Abedin's emails.<ref name=\"CNN Weiner\"/>\n\nComey informed Congress of this additional investigation despite having been advised by Justice Department officials that such an announcement would violate department policies and procedures, including a policy not to comment on investigations close to an election.<ref name=\"despite\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/28/politics/fbi-reviewing-new-emails-in-clinton-probe-director-tells-senate-judiciary-committee/|title=Comey notified Congress of email probe despite DOJ concerns|date=October 30, 2016|publisher=CNN|accessdate=November 5, 2016}}</ref> Comey later explained, in a letter to FBI employees, \"We don't ordinarily tell Congress about ongoing investigations, but here I feel an obligation to do so given that I testified repeatedly in recent months that our investigation was completed.\" Law enforcement sources added that he feared he would be accused of concealing relevant information if he did not disclose it.<ref name=\"despite\"/>\n\nNews of this renewed investigation being revealed shortly before the [[2016 United States presidential election|U.S. presidential election]] led to the announcement being described as an \"[[October surprise]],\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.voanews.com/a/furor-over-fbi-email-bombshell/3572062.html|title=Officials: FBI Knew About Possible New Clinton Emails Weeks Before Friday Announcement|last=Bowman|first=Michael|newspaper=VOA|access-date=October 31, 2016}}</ref> and prompted statements from both the Democratic and Republican campaigns. [[Donald Trump]] repeated his characterization that Hillary Clinton's email usage as secretary of state was \"worse than [[Watergate]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4534375/donald-trump-hillary-clinton-emails-watergate/|title=Donald Trump: Hillary Clinton Email Scandal 'Worse Than Watergate'|work=Time|date=October 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/fbi-clinton-new-probe-trump-hails-230460|title=Trump hails new Clinton FBI review as 'bigger than Watergate'|last=Schreckinger|first=Ben|date=October 28, 2016|work=Politico|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref> Clinton called for the FBI to immediately release all information about the newly discovered emails and said she was confident the FBI would not change its earlier conclusion that there is no basis for criminal prosecution.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/10/28/fbi-probe-newly-discovered-hillary-clinton-emails-and-reopen-inv|title=Hillary Clinton demands answers and Democrats call foul as FBI reopens investigation over files found on sexting congressman's computer|date=October 30, 2016|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref> Senator [[Dianne Feinstein]] (D-CA) said she was \"shocked\" by the letter, saying it \"played right into the political campaign of Donald Trump.\"<ref name=\"despite\"/>\n\nOn November 6, in another letter to Congress, Comey stated that, after working \"around the clock\" to review all of the newly discovered emails, the FBI had not changed the conclusion it reached in July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/fbi-completes-review-newly-revealed-hillary-clinton-emails-finds-no-n678701|title=FBI finds no criminality in review of newly discovered Clinton emails|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/07/us/politics/hilary-clinton-male-voters-donald-trump.html|title=Emails Warrant No New Action Against Hillary Clinton, F.B.I. Director Says|date=November 6, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-us-2016-37892138|title=No criminality in Clinton emails \u2013 FBI|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=November 6, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref> An unnamed government official added that the newly discovered emails turned out to be either personal or duplicates of emails previously reviewed, and that Comey's letter represents a conclusion of the investigation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/fbi-director-comey-says-agency-wont-recommend-charges-over-clinton-email/2016/11/06/f6276b18-a45e-11e6-ba59-a7d93165c6d4_story.html|title=FBI director says agency once again won't recommend charges over Clinton email|date=November 6, 2016|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref> The following day, stock and currency markets around the world surged in response.<ref name=Shell>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/markets/2016/11/07/asian-stocks-bounce-after-fbi-clears-clinton-over-emails/93412244|title=Dow surges 300 points as FBI clears Clinton on eve of election|work=[[USA Today]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016|author1=Shell, Adam  |author2=Jane Onyanga-Omara}}</ref><ref name=Imbert>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/07/us-markets.html|title=Dow soars 350 points higher on eve of US election; financials, health care lead|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016|author=Imbert, Fred}}</ref><ref name=Mikolajczak>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-global-markets-idUSKBN13115N|title=Stocks, dollar jump as FBI clears Clinton in email probe|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 16, 2016|author=Mikolajczak, Chuck}}</ref>\n\nOn November 12, during a conference call to top donors, Hillary Clinton attributed her [[2016 United States presidential election|presidential election]] loss to Comey's announcements, saying they stopped her momentum.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lawler |first=David |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/11/12/hillary-clinton-blames-election-loss-on-fbis-james-comey-in-call/ |title=US election: Hillary Clinton blames loss on FBI's James Comey in call with top donors |date=November 13, 2016 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref> In January 2017, the US Justice Department started an investigation of Comey's announcements.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ainsley |first1=Julia Edwards |last2=Harte |first2=Julia |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-clinton-idUSKBN14W2NT |title=FBI investigated over pre-election decisions on Clinton email |date=January 13, 2017 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref> A 2019 study found that Comey's letter substantially increased Trump's probability of winning the 2016 election.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halcoussis|first=Dennis|last2=Lowenberg|first2=Anton D.|last3=Phillips|first3=G. Michael|title=An Empirical Test of the Comey Effect on the 2016 Presidential Election|journal=Social Science Quarterly|language=en|volume=0|doi=10.1111/ssqu.12729|issn=1540-6237|year=2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Senate probes Loretta Lynch interference ===\nAccording to Comey's June 8, 2017, testimony to the Senate Intelligence Committee, then-Attorney General Loretta Lynch had asked him to downplay the investigation into Clinton's emails by calling it a \"matter\" rather than an investigation. He said the request \"confused and concerned\" him. He added that Lynch's tarmac meeting with [[Bill Clinton]] also influenced his decision to publicly announce the results of the FBI probe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/james-comey-loretta-lynch-told-me-not-to-call-clinton-email-probe-an-investigation/article/2625335|title=James Comey: Loretta Lynch told me not to call Clinton email probe an 'investigation'|last=Cohen|first=Kelly|work=Washington Examiner|access-date=July 5, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/senate-probes-loretta-lynchs-alleged-interference-clinton-email/story?id=48237960|title=Senate probes Loretta Lynch's alleged interference in Clinton investigation|last=News|first=A. B. C.|date=June 23, 2017|publisher=ABC News|access-date=July 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://time.com/4831849/loretta-lynch-hillary-clinton-fbi-senate/|title=Senate Investigating Loretta Lynch's Alleged Interference in Hillary Clinton Email Probe|access-date=July 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn June 23, 2017, several members of the Senate Judiciary Committee opened a bipartisan inquiry into whether former Attorney General Lynch interfered in the FBI's investigation into Hillary Clinton's use of a private email server.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/senate-investigates-loretta-lynch-clinton-email-investigation-2017-6|title=The Senate is investigating whether former Attorney General Loretta Lynch interfered in the Clinton email investigation|work=Business Insider|access-date=July 5, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/senate-probes-loretta-lynchs-alleged-interference-clinton-email/story?id=48237960|title=Senate probes Loretta Lynch's alleged interference in Clinton investigation|last=Parkinson|first=John|date=June 23, 2017|publisher=ABC News|access-date=July 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Internal State Department investigation===\nOn July 7, 2016, the internal State Department resumed its review of whether classified information had been mishandled. The review had been suspended until the completion of the Justice Department investigation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Labott|first1=Elise|last2=Lee|first2=MJ|title=Clinton reiterates email use was a 'mistake' as State Dept. reopens probe|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/07/07/politics/state-department-reopens-probe-into-clinton-emails|accessdate=November 5, 2016|work=Salon|date=July 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/news/election-us-2016-36742095|title=Hillary Clinton emails: US State Department restarts probe|publisher=BBC}}</ref> The [[United States Department of State]] finished its investigation in September 2019, citing 588 security violations. The review found that 38 current and former State Department officials \u2013 some of whom may be punished \u2013 were culpable of mishandling classified information, but in 497 cases the culpability could not be established. The material was considered classified then or later, but none of the violations involved information marked classified. The investigation found Clinton's use of personal email server increased the risk of compromising State Department information, but \"there was no persuasive evidence of systemic, deliberate mishandling of classified information\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Matthew |last2=Jalonick |first2=Mary Clare |title=38 people cited for violations in Clinton email probe |url=https://www.apnews.com/14b14afc5d8647858489a2cf5385c28d |work=The Associated Press |date=October 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/state-department-probe-of-clinton-emails-finds-no-deliberate-mishandling-of-classified-information/2019/10/18/83339446-f1dc-11e9-8693-f487e46784aa_story.html|title=State Department probe of Clinton emails finds no deliberate mishandling of classified information|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n=== Department of Justice Inspector General's report ===\n\n{{main|Inspector General report on FBI and DOJ actions in the 2016 election}}\n\nThe [[Inspector General of the Department of Justice]] (IG) launched an investigation into how the DOJ and FBI had handled the investigation into Clinton's email. On June 14, 2018, the IG issued a report that was highly critical of Comey's actions.<ref name = highlights/> Regarding his July press conference, in which he criticized Clinton even while announcing the investigation was over, the IG said it was \"extraordinary and insubordinate for Comey to conceal his intentions (about the press conference) from his superiors,\" and that \"we found none of his reasons to be a persuasive basis for deviating from well-established Department policies.\"<ref name = slams>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/doj-watchdog-slams-insubordinate-james-comey-over-clinton-email_us_5b22a82be4b0d4fc01fc61e6|title=DOJ Watchdog Slams 'Insubordinate' James Comey Over Clinton Email News Conference|last=Reilly|first=Ryan J.|date=June 14, 2018|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=June 16, 2018}}</ref> Comey's October decision to send a letter notifying Congress that the investigation had been re-opened one week before the election was described as \"[[ad-hoc]]\" and \"a serious error in judgment.\"<ref name = slams/> However, in June 2018 the IG concluded that the decision to not prosecute Clinton was not affected by bias and \"was consistent with the Department\u2019s historical approach in prior cases under different leadership, including in the 2008 decision not to prosecute former Attorney General Alberto Gonzales for mishandling classified documents.\"<ref name=cnn-comey14-6-18>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/14/politics/ig-report-clinton-email-investigation/index.html|title=Comey's actions 'extraordinary and insubordinate,' report says|date=June 14, 2018|work=CNN|accessdate=June 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>A Review of Various Actions by the Federal Bureau of Investigation and Department of Justice in Advance of the 2016 Election, Office of the Inspector General, p. vi: https://www.justice.gov/file/1071991/download</ref>\n\nThe IG report also commented on \"highly classified information\" in a purported Russian intelligence document obtained by the FBI that included an unconfirmed allegation that Attorney General [[Loretta Lynch]] assured a Clinton staffer that she would prevent the FBI investigation from digging too deeply into Clinton's affairs. The FBI long considered the document unreliable and a possible forgery, and Comey told IG investigators he knew the information was not true.<ref name=wapo-24-5-2017>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/how-a-dubious-russian-document-influenced-the-fbis-handling-of-the-clinton-probe/2017/05/24/f375c07c-3a95-11e7-9e48-c4f199710b69_story.html |title=How a dubious Russian document influenced the FBI's handling of the Clinton probe |date=May 24, 2017 |publisher= |access-date=January 22, 2018 |last1=Demirjian |first1=Karoun   |last2=Barrett |first2=Devlin }}</ref> The IG report stated: \"Comey said that he became concerned that the information about Lynch would taint the public's perception of the [Clinton] investigation if it leaked, particularly after DCLeaks and Guccifer 2.0 began releasing hacked emails in mid-June 2016,\" explaining why Comey chose to bypass Lynch and deputy AG [[Sally Yates]] to announce the FBI investigation findings himself.<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\">{{cite news |last1=EWING |first1=PHILIP |title=The Russia Investigations: What The Justice IG Report Revealed |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/06/16/620345643/the-russia-investigations-what-the-justice-ig-report-revealed |accessdate=January 11, 2019 |agency=NPR |date=June 16, 2018}}</ref> The ''[[Washington Post]]'' also stated that \"current and former officials\" told them that Comey relied on the questionable document in making his July decision to announce on his own without his superiors approval that the investigation was over.<ref name=wapo-24-5-2017/>\n\n===Opinions of journalists and experts===\nAccording to the ''New York Times'', if Clinton was a recipient of classified emails, \"it is not clear that she would have known that they contained government secrets, since they were not marked classified.\"<ref name=Allen0821>{{cite web|last1=Allen|first1= Jonathan|title=Exclusive: Dozens of Clinton emails were classified from the start, U.S. rules suggest|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/08/21/us-usa-election-clinton-emails-idUSKCN0QQ0BW20150821|agency=Reuters|accessdate=August 28, 2015|date=August 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=NYT72415/> The newspaper reported that \"most specialists believe the occasional appearance of classified information in the Clinton account was probably of marginal consequence\".<ref name=NYT8815/> Steven Aftergood, director of the Project on Government Secrecy at the [[Federation of American Scientists]], said that inadvertent \"spillage\" of classified information into an unclassified realm is a common occurrence.<ref name=\"NYT8815\"/>\n\n[[Reuters]]' August 2015 review of a set of released emails found \"at least 30 email threads from 2009, representing scores of individual emails,\" which include what the State Department identifies as \"foreign government information,\" defined by the U.S. government as \"any information, written or spoken, provided in confidence to U.S. officials by their foreign counterparts.\" Although unmarked, Reuters' examination appeared to suggest that these emails \"were classified from the start.\"<ref name=Allen0821/> [[J. William Leonard]], a former director of the NARA [[Information Security Oversight Office]], said that such information is \"born classified\" and that \"[I]f a foreign minister just told the secretary of state something in confidence, by U.S. rules that is classified at the moment it's in U.S. channels and U.S. possession.\"<ref name=Allen0821/> According to Reuters, the standard U.S. government [[nondisclosure agreement]] \"warns people authorized to handle classified information that it may not be marked that way and that it may come in oral form.\" The State Department \"disputed Reuters' analysis\" but declined to elaborate.<ref name=Allen0821/>\n\nThe [[Associated Press]] reported, \"Some officials said they believed the designations were a stretch\u2014a knee-jerk move in a bureaucracy rife with over-classification.\"<ref name=AP81415/> [[Jeffrey Toobin]], in an August 2015 ''[[The New Yorker|New Yorker]]'' article, wrote that the Clinton email affair is an illustration of overclassification, a problem written about by Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] in his book ''Secrecy: The American Experience''.<ref name=\"Toobin\">Jeffrey Toobin, [http://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/hillarys-problem-the-government-classifies-everything Hillary's Problem: The Government Classifies Everything], ''The New Yorker'', August 18, 2015.</ref> Toobin writes that \"government bureaucracies use classification rules to protect turf, to avoid embarrassment, to embarrass rivals\u2014in short, for a variety of motives that have little to do with national security.\"<ref name=\"Toobin\"/> Toobin wrote that \"It's not only the public who cannot know the extent or content of government secrecy. Realistically, government officials can't know either\u2014and this is Hillary Clinton's problem. Toobin noted that \"one of Clinton's potentially classified email exchanges is nothing more than a discussion of a newspaper story about [[Drone strikes in Pakistan|drones]]\" and wrote: \"That such a discussion could be classified underlines the absurdity of the current system. But that is the system that exists, and if and when the agencies determine that she sent or received classified information through her private server, Clinton will be accused of mishandling national-security secrets.\"<ref name=\"Toobin\"/>\n\nIn an analysis of the Clinton email controversy published by the [[Brookings Institution]], Richard Lempert wrote that \"security professionals have a reputation for erring in the direction of overclassification.\"<ref name=\"German\">German, Ben. [http://www.nationaljournal.com/twentysixteen/2015/08/19/other-top-secret-problem-hurting-hillary-clinton The Other 'Top Secret' Problem Hurting Hillary Clinton] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017184847/http://www.nationaljournal.com/twentysixteen/2015/08/19/other-top-secret-problem-hurting-hillary-clinton |date=October 17, 2015 }}, ''National Journal'', August 19, 2015.</ref> Elizabeth Goitein, co-director of the liberty and national security program at the [[Brennan Center for Justice]] at [[New York University School of Law]], says that \"The odds are good that any classified information in the Clinton emails should not have been classified,\" since an estimated 50 percent to 90 percent of classified documents could be made public without risking national security.<ref name=\"German\" /> Nate Jones, an expert with the [[National Security Archive]] at [[George Washington University]], said: \"Clinton's mistreatment of federal records and the intelligence community's desire to retroactively overclassify are two distinct troubling problems. No politician is giving the right message: Blame Clinton for poor records practices, but don't embrace overclassification while you do it.\"<ref name=\"German\" />\n\n====Russian intelligence and Comey's pronouncements====\nA number of journalists (Philip Ewing<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\"/> and [[Jane Mayer]]<ref name=\"mayer-1-10-18\">{{cite magazine |last1=Jane |first1=Mayer |title=How Russia Helped Swing the Election for Trump |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/10/01/how-russia-helped-to-swing-the-election-for-trump |accessdate=December 23, 2018 |magazine=New Yorker |date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> [[Karoun Demirjian]] and Devlin Barrett)<ref name=wapo-24-5-2017/> \nhave commented on the connection between the alleged Russian intelligence document given to the FBI that suggested Attorney General [[Loretta Lynch]] would prevent the FBI investigation from digging too deeply into Clinton's affairs (see above), and Comey's July announcement of the FBI investigation findings by himself without Lynch's permission,<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\"/><ref name=\"mayer-1-10-18\"/> which was later called \"extraordinary and insubordinate\" by the [[Inspector General report on FBI and DOJ actions in the 2016 election|Department of Justice Inspector General's report]].<ref name=cnn-comey14-6-18/> \u201cCurrent and former officials\u201d told Washington Post reporters Demirjian and Barrett that \u201cComey relied on the document in making his July decision to announce on his own,\u201d because he feared its contents would be leaked, tainting the public's perception of the FBI investigation.<ref name=wapo-24-5-2017/> This was despite the fact that Comey himself told investigators \u201che knew from the first moment\u201d that the document \u201cwasn't true\u201d<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\"/> and the FBI was later unable to corroborate the document.<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\"/>\n\nEwing and Mayer note the document's effect on the election. According to Ewing, \"to the degree\" that the document \"was intended to help disrupt the election, it worked\".<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\"/> Jane Mayer describes the work of political scientist [[Kathleen Hall Jamieson]] who argues that Comey\u2019s \"damaging public pronouncements\" on Clinton\u2019s handling of classified e-mails\" in July and later ten days before the election can \"plausibly be attributed to Russian disinformation\".<ref name=\"mayer-1-10-18\"/> While it is difficult to determine how many voters Clinton lost from the pronouncements, Mayer also quotes the Democratic ranking member of the House Intelligence Committee, [[Adam Schiff]], who states that if \"the fake intelligence\" motivated Comey, then the document was \"probably was the most measurable\u201d and \u201cthe most significant way in which the Russians may have impacted the outcome of the election.\u201d<ref name=\"mayer-1-10-18\"/>\n\n==House Oversight Committee hearing==\nOn July 7, 2016, Comey was questioned for 5 hours by the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]. Comey stated that there was \"evidence of mishandling\" of classified information and that he believed that Clinton was \"extremely careless; I think she was negligent.\" He defended the FBI's recommendation against bringing charges because it \"... would have been unfair and virtually unprecedented ...\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-james-comey-hillary-clinton-email-probe/story?id=41044927|title=What FBI Director Really Said About Clinton Email Probe|first=Mike|last=Levine|date=August 2, 2016|publisher=ABC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-director-set-to-appear-before-congressional-committee-to-answer-questions-on-clinton-investigation/2016/07/07/eb43ec7e-43c1-11e6-88d0-6adee48be8bc_story.html|last=Zapotosky|first=Matt|title=House Republicans grill FBI director Comey on Clinton emails|work=The Washington Post|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Responses and analysis==\n===Clinton's initial response===\n[[File:2015 03 10 Hillary Clinton by Voice of America (cropped to collar).jpg|thumb|left|Clinton addressing email controversy with the media at the [[Headquarters of the United Nations|UN Headquarters]] on March 10, 2015]]\nClinton's spokesman Nick Merrill defended Clinton's usage of her personal server and email accounts as being ''in compliance with the \"letter and spirit of the rules.\"''\n\nClinton herself stated she had done so as a matter of \"convenience.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/10/politics/hillary-clinton-email-scandal-press-conference|title=Hillary Clinton email scandal does damage control \u2013 CNN|author=Alexandra Jaffe and Dan Merica, CNN|date=March 10, 2015|publisher=CNN|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2015, while attending a conference at the [[headquarters of the United Nations|headquarters of the United Nation]]s in [[Manhattan]], Clinton spoke with reporters for about 20 minutes.<ref name=WashPost3>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/hillary-clinton-to-answer-questions-about-use-of-private-e-mail-server/2015/03/10/4c000d00-c735-11e4-a199-6cb5e63819d2_story.html|title=Clinton: It 'might have been smarter' to use a State Dept. e-mail account|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref> Clinton said she had used a private email for convenience, \"because I thought it would be easier to carry just one device for my work and for my personal emails instead of two.\"<ref name=\"cnn03312015\">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/03/31/politics/hillary-clinton-ipad-e-mail-devices|title=Source: Clinton used iPad for personal email at State|publisher=CNN|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=August 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2015/03/10/first-take-hillary-clinton-emails/24705871|title=First Take: Clinton's even tone edges into exasperation |  work=USA Today | date=March 11, 2015 | accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>\nIt was later determined that Clinton had used both an [[iPad]] and a [[BlackBerry]] while Secretary of State.<ref name=cnn03312015/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/64f85b3a72184bd1b4604d5e1870116d/clinton-also-used-ipad-email-mixed-personal-work-chats|title=State Department found 4 emails about drones sent by Clinton|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=August 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/hillary-clinton-actually-used-two-devices-while-secretary-of-state-records-show-10147082.html|title=Hillary Clinton actually used two devices while secretary of state, records show |work=The Independent| accessdate=August 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2015/03/31/hillary-clinton-also-used-an-ipad-for-e-mails-undercutting-her-single-device-defense|title=Hillary Clinton also used an iPad for e-mails, undercutting her single-device defense|work=The Washington Post| accessdate = August 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nClinton turned over copies of 30,000 State Department business-related emails from her private server that belonged in the public domain; she later explained that she instructed her lawyer to err on the side of disclosure, turning over any emails that ''might'' be work-related. Her aides subsequently deleted about 31,000 emails from the server dated during the same time period that Clinton regarded as personal and private.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-hillary-clinton-email-un-20150310-story.html#page=2|title=Hillary Clinton tries to end controversy over private email account |quote=she disclosed that her aides had deleted more than 30,000 emails that she deemed personal. ... Clinton said that when she and her staff reviewed the emails last year, she instructed her lawyer to err on the side of turning over anything that might be considered work-related.|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/10/hillary-clinton-spam-deleted-214351|title=Most Clinton Spam Messages Likely Deleted|publisher=Politico|date=October 1, 2015|authors=Josh Gerstein and Joseph Marks|quote=[A]ccording to little-noticed language in a statement Clinton's office issued earlier this year. ... 'After her work-related emails were identified and preserved, Secretary Clinton chose not to keep her private, personal messages. ... '}}</ref><ref name=\"SchmidtPrivateEmails\">Michael S. Schmidt, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/12/us/justice-dept-says-hillary-clinton-had-authority-to-delete-certain-emails.html?_r=0 Justice Dept. Says Hillary Clinton Had Authority to Delete Certain Emails], ''The New York Times'', September 11, 2015.</ref> State Department employees do have the right to delete personal emails.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hillary Clinton had right to delete personal emails, says US justice department|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/sep/12/hillary-clinton-had-right-to-delete-personal-emails-says-us-justice-department|accessdate=November 4, 2016|work=The Guardian|agency=Associated Press|date=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nClinton has used humor to try to shrug off the scandals.<ref>O'Harrow, Robert. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/how-clintons-email-scandal-took-root/2016/03/27/ee301168-e162-11e5-846c-10191d1fc4ec_story.html \"How Clinton's email scandal took root\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', March 27, 2016.</ref><ref>Vorhees, Josh. [http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2015/08/20/hillary_clinton_email_scandal_explained.html A Crystal-Clear Explanation of Hillary's Confusing Email Scandal], ''Slate'', August 20, 2015.</ref> In August 2015, when asked by a reporter whether she had \"wiped\" her server, Clinton laughed and said: \"What? Like with a cloth or something? I don't know how it works digitally at all.\"<ref>Struyk, Ryan & Liz Kreutz, [http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/hillary-clinton-jokes-wiping-email-server-cloth/story?id=33165517 Hillary Clinton Jokes About Wiping Email Server 'With A Cloth Or Something'], ABC News, August 18, 2015.</ref> In September 2015, Clinton was asked in an interview with [[Jimmy Fallon]] on ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' about the content of the emails. She laughed it off, saying there was nothing interesting and joking that she was offended people found her emails 'boring.'<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/jimmy-fallon-gives-hillary-a-pass-on-boring-emails|title=Jimmy Fallon Gives Hillary a Pass on 'Boring' Emails|author=Wilstein, Matt|accessdate=April 16, 2016|publisher=Mediaite}}</ref>\n\n====Later responses====\nClinton's responses to the question, made during her presidential campaign, evolved over time.<ref name=\"Toobin\"/><ref name=politics>{{cite news|author1=Leonnig, Carol D., Karen Tumulty & Rosalind S. Helderman|title=Clinton's team went from nonchalant to nervous over e-mail controversy|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/how-clintons-team-went-from-nonchalant-to-nervous-over-e-mail-controversy/2015/08/14/347f1066-405e-11e5-9561-4b3dc93e3b9a_story.html|accessdate=August 18, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=August 14, 2015|quote= ... it has become clear that a number of her statements defending her actions now appear to be false.}}</ref> Clinton initially said that there was no classified material on her server. Later, after a government review discovered some of her emails contained classified information, she said she never sent or received information that was ''marked'' classified.<ref name=\"Toobin\" /> Her campaign claimed other emails contained information that is now classified, but was ''retroactively'' classified by U.S. intelligence agencies after Clinton had received the material.<ref name=\"Campaign Classified\">Tau, Byron & Robert McMillan. [https://www.wsj.com/articles/hillary-clinton-says-classified-emails-were-on-server-1440030491 Hillary Clinton Campaign Says Classified Emails Were on Server], ''The Wall Street Journal'', August 19, 2015.</ref> See also the section above on the [[Hillary Clinton email controversy#May 2016 report from State Department's inspector general|May 2016 IG report]] for a number of Clinton statements that were contradicted by the report, and how she and her supporters responded afterward.\n\nCampaign spokesman Brian Fallon said: \"She was at worst a passive recipient of unwitting information that subsequently became deemed as classified.\"<ref name=\"Campaign Classified\"/> Clinton campaign spokeswoman [[Jennifer Palmieri]] has \"stressed that Clinton was permitted to use her own email account as a government employee and that the same process concerning classification reviews would still be taking place had she used the standard 'state.gov' email account used by most department employees.\"<ref name=AP81415>{{cite news|author1=Bradley Klapper  |author2=Ken Dilanian|title=Top secret Clinton emails include drone talk|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b54a250a40e9410baaaca5f9fb58ea94/ap-exclusive-top-secret-clinton-emails-include-drone-talk|accessdate=August 19, 2015|work=AP Big Story|agency=Associated Press|date=August 14, 2015|quote=part of a covert program that is widely known and discussed}}</ref><ref name=\"KesslerFactCheck\">Kessler, Glenn, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/fact-checker/wp/2015/07/09/hillary-clintons-claim-that-everything-i-did-on-emails-was-permitted \"Hillary Clinton's claim that everything I did on e-mails was permitted\"], ''The Washington Post'', July 9, 2015.</ref> Palmieri later stated: \"Look, this kind of nonsense comes with the territory of running for president. We know it, Hillary knows it, and we expect it to continue from now until Election Day.\"<ref name=AP0813>Eric Tucker, [http://www.aol.com/article/2015/08/13/clinton-aides-agree-to-preserve-emails-after-judges-order/21222558 \"Clinton Aides Agree to Preserve Emails after Judge's Order\"], Associated Press, August 13, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn her first national interview about the 2016 presidential race, on July 7, 2015, Clinton was asked by [[CNN]]'s [[Brianna Keilar]] about her use of private email accounts while serving as Secretary of State. She said:\n\n{{quote|Everything I did was permitted. There was no law. There was no regulation. There was nothing that did not give me the full authority to decide how I was going to communicate. Previous secretaries of state have said they did the same thing ... Everything I did was permitted by law and regulation. I had one device. When I mailed anybody in the government, it would go into the government system.<ref>[http://cnnpressroom.blogs.cnn.com/2015/07/07/cnn-exclusive-hillary-clintons-first-national-interview-of-2016-race \"Hillary Clinton's first national interview of 2016 Race\"], CNN, July 7, 2015.</ref>}}\n\nOn September 9, 2015, Clinton apologized during an ABC News interview for using the private server, saying she was \"sorry for that.\"<ref name=\"abcsorry\">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/hillary-clinton-private-email-mistake-im/story?id=33608970|title=Hillary Clinton on Private Email: 'That Was a Mistake. I'm Sorry'|last=Kreutz|first=Liz|date=September 8, 2015|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> Appearing on NBC's ''[[Meet the Press]]'' on September 27, 2015, Clinton defended her use of the private email server while she was secretary of state, comparing the investigations to Republican-led probes of her husband's presidential administration more than two decades ago, saying, \"It is like a drip, drip, drip. And that's why I said, there's only so much that I can control.\"<ref name=Lerer0927>Lisa Lerer,  [http://www.aol.com/article/2015/09/27/clinton-compares-email-attacks-to-white-house-controversies/21241424/ Clinton Compares email Attacks to White House Controversies], Associated Press, September 27, 2015.</ref>\n\nClinton and the State Department said the emails were not marked classified when sent. However, Clinton signed a [[non-disclosure agreement]] which stated that classified material may be \"marked or unmarked.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/07/27/opinions/cox-clinton-email-controversy|title=Hillary Clinton email controversy: How serious is it?|author=Douglas Cox|date=July 27, 2015|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2016/02/04/how-did-top-secret-emails-end-up-on-hillary-clintons-server|title=How did 'top secret' emails end up on Hillary Clinton's server?|author=Glenn Kessler|date=February 4, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/clinton-emails-held-indirect-references-undercover-cia-officers-n510741|title=Clinton Emails Held Indirect References to Undercover CIA Officers|author=Ken Dilanian|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> Additionally, the author of an email is legally required to properly mark it as classified if it contains classified material, and to avoid sending classified material on a personal device, such as the ones used exclusively by Clinton.<ref>Gearan, Anne.  [https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/new-batch-of-clinton-e-mails-due-monday-minus-150-deemed-classified/2015/08/31/dcbdcbbc-501e-11e5-8c19-0b6825aa4a3a_story.html \"Big batch of Clinton e-mails released; some have redactions\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', August 31, 2015: \"Under the law, it is the responsibility of the author of e-mails to properly mark them as classified and to make sure they avoid discussing classified material over a nongovernment or personal device. Because the State Department deals in so many sensitive secrets, many employees use two computer networks for their daily communications: a non-classified system called the \"low side\" and a more secure classified system called the \"high side.\" But Clinton had no official State Department e-mail address and exclusively used a personal domain and personal server set up in her home for electronic correspondence.\"</ref>\n\nClinton maintained that she did not send or receive any confidential emails from her personal server. In a Democratic debate with [[Bernie Sanders]] on February 4, 2016, Clinton said, \"I never sent or received any classified material.\" In a Meet the Press interview on July 2, 2016, Clinton stated: \"Let me repeat what I have repeated for many months now, I never received nor sent any material that was marked classified.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"politifact.com\"/><ref name=\"washingtonpost.com1\"/>\n\nIn an interview with Fox News in late July 2016, Clinton stated \"Director Comey said my answers were truthful, and what I've said is consistent with what I have told the American people, that there were decisions discussed and made to classify retroactively certain of the emails.\" The Washington Post awarded Clinton four \"Pinocchios\", its worst rating, for her statement saying \"While Comey did say there was no evidence she lied to the FBI, that is not the same as saying she told the truth to the American public.\"<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2016/07/31/clintons-claim-that-the-fbi-director-said-her-email-answers-were-truthful \"Clinton\u2019s claim that the [[FBI]] director at the time, James Comey, said that Clinton's email answers were ''truthful''\"], ''The Washington Post'', July 31, 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/01/politics/washington-post-clinton-four-pinnochios-comey-emails/index.html][[Washington Post]]<span> hits Clinton with four 'Pinnochios' on emails</span>, CNN (August 1, 2016).</ref><ref>[http://nation.foxnews.com/2016/08/01/wapo-gives-hillary-four-pinocchios-claiming-comey-called-her-truthful-about-her-emails \"WaPo Gives Hillary Four Pinocchios For Claiming Comey Called Her ''Truthful'' About Her Emails\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819034501/http://nation.foxnews.com/2016/08/01/wapo-gives-hillary-four-pinocchios-claiming-comey-called-her-truthful-about-her-emails# |date=August 19, 2016 }}, Fox News Channel, August 1, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn her 2017 book ''What Happened?'', Clinton argued that the email controversy and FBI Director James Comey's actions contributed to her loss. A 2019 study in the journal ''Perspectives on Politics'' found little evidence to support the hypothesis.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Quinlan|first=Stephen|last2=Lewis-Beck|first2=Michael S.|date=2019|title=The Hillary Hypotheses: Testing Candidate Views of Loss|journal=Perspectives on Politics|language=en|volume=17|issue=3|pages=646\u2013665|doi=10.1017/S153759271800347X|issn=1537-5927|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Venice]] at the \u201cHillary: The Hillary Clinton Emails,\u201d a work on display in a balcony jutting out over a supermarket at the Despar Teatro Italia during the [[58th Venice Biennale|58th Biennale of Visual Arts]], Clinton made a surprise visit on Tuesday September 10, 2019, to this work of political theater and performance art. The exhibition created by the American poet and artist [[Kenneth Goldsmith]] is displayed from May 9, 2019, until November 24, 2019, during the Francesco Urbano Ragazzi's Biennale. During her appearance, she said that the attention given to her emails was one of the \u201cstrangest\u201d and most \u201cabsurd\u201d events in U.S. political history, adding, \u201cAnyone can go in and look at them. There is nothing there. There is nothing that should have been so controversial.\u201d<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/09/12/breaking-news/hillary-clinton-reads-her-emails-at-venice-art-show/| title=Hillary Clinton reads her emails at Venice art show| newspaper=[[Star-Advertiser]]| location=[[Honolulu]]| via=[[New York Times]]| date=September 12, 2019| access-date=September 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic response===\nIn August 2015, the ''New York Times'' reported on \"interviews with more than 75 Democratic governors, lawmakers, candidates and party members\" on the email issue.<ref name=\"FrustratesDems\">Patrick Healy, Jonathan Martin & Maggie Haberman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/28/us/politics/hillary-clintons-handling-of-email-issue-frustrates-democratic-leaders.html Hillary Clinton\u2019s Handling of Email Issue Frustrates Democratic Leaders], ''The New York Times'', August 27, 2015.</ref> The ''Times'' reported, \"None of the Democrats interviewed went so far as to suggest that the email issue raised concerns about Mrs. Clinton's ability to serve as president, and many expressed a belief that it had been [[manufactured controversy|manufactured]] by Republicans in Congress and other adversaries.\"<ref name=\"FrustratesDems\"/> At the same time, many Democratic leaders showed increasing frustration among party leaders of Clinton's handling of the email issue. For example, [[Edward G. Rendell]], former [[governor of Pennsylvania]], a Clinton supporter, said that a failure of the Clinton campaign to get ahead of the issue early on meant that the campaign was \"left just playing defense.\"<ref name=\"FrustratesDems\"/> Other prominent Democrats, such as Governor [[Dannel P. Malloy]] of [[Connecticut]], were less concerned, noting the campaign was at an early stage and that attacks on Clinton were to be expected.<ref name=\"FrustratesDems\"/>\n\nAt the October 2015 primary debate, Clinton's chief rival for the Democratic presidential nomination, Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] of [[Vermont]], defended Clinton, saying: \"Let me say this. Let me say something that may not be great politics. But I think the secretary is right. And that is that the American people are sick and tired of hearing about your damn emails!\"<ref name=\"DamnEmailsRoy\">Roy, Jessica. [http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pol-prez-bernie-sanders-damn-emails-20151013-htmlstory.html \"Watch Bernie Sanders slay the room with 'damn emails' line\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', October 13, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"Terkel\">Terkel, Amanda. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/bernie-sanders-hillary-clinton-emails_5623adaee4b02f6a900ca3b9 \"Bernie Sanders: No Regrets Defending Hillary Clinton on Emails\"], ''HuffPost'', October 19, 2015.</ref> Sanders later clarified that he thought Clinton's emails were a \"very serious issue,\"<ref name=\"Foley\">Foley, Elise. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/bernie-sanders-hillary-clinton-emails_us_56ae254be4b077d4fe8e7023 Bernie Sanders Calls Hillary Clinton\u2019s Emails \u2018A Very Serious Issue\u2019], Huffington Post (January 31, 2016).</ref> but Americans want a discussion on issues that are \"real\" to them, such as paid [[Family leave|family]] and [[medical leave]], [[College tuition in the United States|college affordability]], and [[campaign finance reform]].<ref name=\"Terkel\"/>\n\n\"But her emails!\" became a meme during and following the 2016 election, often used in a joking or mocking way.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brandwatch.com/blog/react-but-her-emails/|title=\"But Her Emails!\" Unpicking the Social Media Phenomenon That Is Hillary Clinton's Emails|last=Joyce|first=Gemma|date=October 12, 2017|work=Brandwatch|accessdate=August 3, 2018}}</ref> Clinton herself echoed the phrase in June 2018, when the Justice Department's Inspector General issued a [[Inspector General report on FBI and DOJ actions in the 2016 election|report]] on how the investigation of her use of email was conducted. It revealed that FBI Director Comey had used a personal email account to conduct FBI business; Clinton's response was a Twitter comment, \"But my emails!\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2018/06/14/hillary-clinton-justice-report-fbi/703886002/|title='But my emails': Hillary Clinton claps back after report reveals Comey used Gmail|last=Cummings|first=William|date=June 14, 2018|work=USA Today|accessdate=August 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Republican response===\n[[Chairman of the Republican National Committee|Republican National Committee chairman]] [[Reince Priebus]] said, in a statement regarding the June 30, 2015 email releases, \"These emails ... are just the tip of the iceberg, and we will never get full disclosure until Hillary Clinton releases her secret server for an independent investigation.\"<ref name=LATimes2/> [[Trey Gowdy]] said on June 29, 2015, that he would press the State Department for a fuller accounting of Clinton's emails, after the Benghazi panel retrieved 15 additional emails to Sidney Blumenthal that the department had not provided to the Committee.<ref name=Memoli1>Memoli, Michael A. [http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-hillary-clinton-state-emails-20150629-story.html Next batch of Hillary Clinton's emails will be released], ''Los Angeles Times'', June 30, 2015.</ref>\n\nOn September 12, 2015, Republican Senators [[Charles Grassley]] and [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]], chairmen of the Senate [[Senate Judiciary Committee|Judiciary]] and [[Senate Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs Committee|Homeland Security]] committees, respectively, said they would seek an independent review of the deleted emails, if they were recovered from Clinton's server, to determine if there were any government related items among those deleted.<ref name=WP0912/>\n\n===Comparisons and media coverage===\nAnalyses by Columbia Journalism Review, the [[Berkman Klein Center for Internet & Society|Berkman Klein Center]] for Internet and Society at Harvard University, and the [[Shorenstein Center on Media, Politics and Public Policy|Shorenstein Center]] at the Harvard Kennedy School show that the Clinton email controversy received more coverage in mainstream media outlets than any other topic during the 2016 presidential election.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> The ''New York Times'' coverage of the email controversy was notoriously extensive; according to a Columbia Journalism Review analysis, \"''in just six days, ''The New York Times'' ran as many cover stories about Hillary Clinton's emails as they did about all policy issues combined in the 69 days leading up to the election'' (and that does not include the three additional articles on October 18, and November 6 and 7, or the two articles on the emails taken from John Podesta).\"<ref name=\":4\" /> In attempting to explain the lopsided coverage, the Columbia Journalism Review speculates, \"In retrospect, it seems clear that the press in general made the mistake of assuming a Clinton victory was inevitable, and were setting themselves as credible critics of the next administration.\"<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n[[Pundit|Media commentators]] drew comparisons of Clinton's email usage to past political controversies. ''Pacific Standard Magazine'' published an article in May 2015, comparing email controversy and her response to it with the [[Whitewater controversy|Whitewater]] investigation 20 years earlier.<ref name=\"PS031615\">{{cite news|last1=Gerth|first1=Jeff|title=Hillary Clinton's Email Scandal Looks a Lot Like the Whitewater Investigation of 20 Years Ago|url=https://psmag.com/news/hillary-clintons-email-scandal-looks-a-lot-like-the-whitewater-investigation-of-20-years-ago|accessdate=October 13, 2015|work=Pacific Standard|date=March 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, ''Washington Post'' associate editor and [[investigative journalist]] [[Bob Woodward]], when asked about Clinton's handling of her emails, said they remind him of the [[Nixon White House tapes|Nixon tapes]] from the [[Watergate scandal]].<ref>[http://www.msnbc.com/morning-joe/watch/security-questions-linger-in-clinton-emails-508380739552 Security questions linger in Clinton emails], ''[[Morning Joe]]'', August 19, 2015.</ref> On March 9, 2015, liberal columnist and Clinton supporter [[Dana Milbank]] wrote that the email affair was \"a needless, self-inflicted wound\" brought about by \"debilitating caution\" in \"trying to make sure an embarrassing e-mail or two didn't become public,\" which led to \"obsessive secrecy.\" Milbank pointed out that Clinton herself had justifiably criticized the George W. Bush administration in 2007 for its \"secret\" White House email accounts.<ref name=CT3915>{{cite news|last1=Milbank|first1=Dana|title=Hillary Clinton, too cautious for her own good|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/hillary-clintons-debilitating-caution/2015/03/06/e3225638-c411-11e4-9ec2-b418f57a4a99_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=GWBSalon>{{cite news|last1=Boehlert|first1=Eric|title=The George W. Bush email scandal the media has conveniently forgotten|url=http://www.salon.com/2015/03/12/the_george_w_bush_email_scandal_the_media_has_conveniently_forgotten_partner/|work=Salon|date=March 12, 2015|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn ''[[Fox News Sunday]]'', [[political analyst]] [[Juan Williams]] contrasted the [[media coverage]] of Clinton's emails to the coverage of the 2007 [[Bush White House email controversy]] which he claimed received \"just about zero press coverage.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/punditfact/statements/2015/mar/15/juan-williams/media-reaction-george-w-bushs-email-controversy|title=The media reaction to George W. Bush's email controversy|publisher=[[PolitiFact]]|date=March 15, 2015|accessdate=October 13, 2015|last=Carroll|first=Lauren}}</ref> PolitiFact found Williams' assertion to be \"mostly false,\" concluding \"We found hundreds of articles and television transcripts referencing the issue. Still, Williams has something of a point that compared to the extensive recent coverage of Clinton's use of private email, media coverage of the 2007 Bush White House email controversy was thin.\"<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'' published an editorial opining that \"the only believable reason for the private server in her basement was to keep her emails out of the public eye by willfully avoiding freedom of information laws. No president, no secretary of state, no public official at any level is above the law. She chose to ignore it, and must face the consequences.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/opinion/clintons-absymal-record-on-open-government-b99696012z1-374014501.html|title=Clinton's abysmal record on open government|publisher=jsonline.com|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/2016-dem-primary-live-updates-and-results/2016/03/milwaukee-journal-sentinel-criticizes-hillary-clinton-221390|title=Wisconsin's largest paper blasts Clinton on transparency|work=POLITICO}}</ref> Pascal-Emmanuel Gobry wrote in ''[[The Week]]'' that \"Clinton set up a personal email server, in defiance or at least circumvention of rules, with the probable motive of evading federal records and transparency requirements, and did it with subpar security.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/articles/615382/hillary-clintons-litany-scandal|title=Hillary Clinton's litany of scandal|work=The Week|accessdate=March 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2, 2016, [[Fox News]] anchor [[Bret Baier]] reported that according to Fox's anonymous sources the FBI had discovered that Clinton's private server had been hacked by \"five foreign intelligence agencies.\"<ref name=Cummings>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2016/11/04/fox-news-apologizes-clinton-report/93300254|last1=Cummings|first1=William|title=Fox News anchor apologizes for false report of 'likely' Clinton indictment|work=USA Today|date=November 4, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Farhi>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-chief-plans-remarks-to-media-amid-heightened-focus-on-clinton-email-probe/2016/07/05/a53513c4-42b9-11e6-bc99-7d269f8719b1_story.html|last1=Farhi|first1=Paul|title=Fox News apologizes for falsely reporting that Clinton faces indictment|work=The Washington Post|date=November 4, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/11/tracking-the-fbi-stories-about-clinton/506642/|title=The Anatomy of a Leak: How Did a Mistaken Clinton Story Happen?|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=Nov 4, 2016|author=David Graham}}</ref> Baier further reported that according to an anonymous source an FBI investigation of the Clinton Foundation was \"likely\" to lead to an indictment of Hillary Clinton.<ref name=Cummings/><ref name=Farhi/> On November 4, 2016, he acknowledged that his assertions were a mistake, saying, \"indictment obviously is a very loaded word,\" and that he was sorry.<ref name=Snopes>{{cite web|url=http://www.snopes.com/homeland-security-indicts-hillary|last1=Emery|first1=David|title= Premature Litigation|website=Snopes.com|date=November 4, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Cummings/><ref name=Farhi/>\n\n==House Select Committee on Benghazi==\n{{main|United States House Select Committee on Benghazi}}\n\nOn March 27, 2015, Republican Congressman [[Trey Gowdy]], Chairman of the Select Committee on Benghazi, asserted that some time after October 2014, Clinton \"unilaterally decided to wipe her server clean\" and \"summarily decided to delete all emails.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://benghazi.house.gov/news/press-releases/statement-regarding-subpoena-compliance-and-server-determination-by-former|title=Statement Regarding Subpoena Compliance and Server Determination by Former Secretary of State Hillary Clinton &#124; Select Committee on Benghazi|publisher=Benghazi.house.gov|date=October 28, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402175403/http://benghazi.house.gov/news/press-releases/statement-regarding-subpoena-compliance-and-server-determination-by-former|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Perry|first=Mark|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/03/gowdy-clinton-wiped-her-server-clean-116472.html|title=Trey Gowdy: Hillary Clinton wiped email server clean|publisher=Politico.com|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref> Clinton's attorney, [[David E. Kendall]], said that day that an examination showed that no copies of any of Clinton's emails remained on the server. Kendall said the server was reconfigured to only retain emails for 60 days after Clinton lawyers had decided which emails needed to be turned over.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/28/us/politics/no-copies-of-hillary-clinton-emails-on-server-lawyer-says.html|title=No Copies of Hillary Clinton Emails on Server Lawyer Says|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2015, the Benghazi panel released emails between Clinton and [[Sidney Blumenthal]], who had been recently deposed by the committee. Committee chairman Gowdy issued a press release criticizing Clinton for not providing the emails to the State Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://benghazi.house.gov/news/press-releases/select-committee-adds-to-secretary-clinton-s-public-email-record|title=Select Committee Adds to Secretary Clinton's Public Email Record|work=Select Committee on Benghazi|accessdate=August 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901071429/http://benghazi.house.gov/news/press-releases/select-committee-adds-to-secretary-clinton-s-public-email-record|archive-date=September 1, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Clinton had said she provided all work-related emails to the State Department, and that only emails of a personal nature on her private server were destroyed. The State Department confirmed that 10 emails and parts of five others from Sidney Blumenthal regarding Benghazi, which the Committee had made public on June 22, could not be located in the Department's records, but that the 46 other, previously unreleased Libya-related Blumenthal emails published by the Committee, were in the Department's records. In response, Clinton campaign spokesman Nick Merrill, when asked about the discrepancy said: \"She has turned over 55,000 pages of materials to the State Department, including all emails in her possession from Mr. Blumenthal.\"<ref name=KlapperLee>Bradley Klapper & Matthew Lee, [http://www.aol.com/article/2015/06/25/state-dept-15-emails-missing-from-clinton-cache/21201434/ State Dept.: 15 emails missing from Clinton cache], Associated Press (June 25, 2015).</ref> Republican Committee members were encouraged about their probe, having found emails that Clinton failed to produce.<ref name=KlapperLee/><ref name=NJ1>{{cite news|author=Ben German|title=GOP's Benghazi Probe Ups Pressure on John Kerry as Team Clinton Returns Fire: Republican Rep. Trey Gowdy said he may call the secretary of State to testify about a lack of document production|work=National Journal|date=June 28, 2015|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/2016-elections/gop-s-benghazi-probe-ups-pressure-on-john-kerry-as-team-clinton-returns-fire-20150628|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150629135647/http://www.nationaljournal.com/2016-elections/gop-s-benghazi-probe-ups-pressure-on-john-kerry-as-team-clinton-returns-fire-20150628|archivedate=June 29, 2015}}</ref> Clinton campaign staff accused Gowdy and Republicans of \"clinging to their invented scandal.\"<ref name=NJ1/>\n\nIn response to comments that House Republican Majority Leader [[Kevin McCarthy (California politician)|Kevin McCarthy]] made on September 29, 2015, about damaging Clinton's poll numbers,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/kevin-mccarthys-truthful-gaffe/2015/09/30/f12a9fac-67a8-11e5-8325-a42b5a459b1e_story.html|title=Kevin McCarthy's truthful gaffe on Benghazi|first=E.J.|last=Dionne|authorlink=E.J. Dionne|date=September 30, 2015|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> Minority Leader [[Nancy Pelosi]] threatened to end the Democrats' participation in the committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/255625-pelosi-threatens-to-end-dem-participation-in-benghazi-probe|title=Pelosi threatens to end Dem participation in Benghazi probe|work=The Hill|first=Mike|last=Lillis|date=October 1, 2015|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2015/10/05/house-democrats-to-release-benghazi-interview-transcript|title=House Democrats to Release Benghazi Interview Transcript|author=Byron Tau|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2015/10/06/democrats-work-to-keep-heat-on-gowdy-mccarthy-ahead-of-clinton-benghazi-hearing|title=Democrats work to keep heat on Gowdy, McCarthy ahead of Clinton Benghazi hearing|author=Elise Viebeck|date=October 6, 2015|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> Representative [[Louise Slaughter]] (D-NY) introduced an amendment to disband the committee, which was defeated in a party-line vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/10/06/politics/benghazi-committee-democrats-threat/index.html?eref=rss_latest|title=Democrats go on offense after McCarthy's Benghazi gaffe|author1=Kopan, Tal  |author2=Deirdre Walsh|date=October 7, 2015|publisher=CNN|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> On October 7, the [[editorial board]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called for the end of the committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/07/opinion/shut-down-the-benghazi-committee.html|title=Shut Down the Benghazi Committee|work=The New York Times|date=October 7, 2015|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> Representative [[Alan Grayson]] (D-FL) took step towards filing an ethics complaint, calling the committee \"the new McCarthyism\", alleging it was violating both House rules and federal law by using official funds for political purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.rollcall.com/218/grayson-file-benghazi-ethics-complaint-mccarthy-gowdy|title=Grayson to File Benghazi Ethics Complaint Over Benghazi|work=Roll Call|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> [[Richard L. Hanna]], (R-NY),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/10/clinton_campaign_gop_rep_richard_hanna_admits_benghazi_probe_is_political_sham.html|title=GOP Rep. Richard Hanna suggests Benghazi probe targeted Hillary Clinton|publisher=syracuse.com|accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref> and conservative [[pundit]] [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]] acknowledged the partisan nature of the committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/10/bill-oreilly-benghazi-investigation-political-214620|title=Bill O'Reilly on Benghazi probe: 'Of course it's political'|work=Politico|accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:House Select Committee on Benghazi.png|thumb|Hillary Clinton's public hearing before the House Select Committee on Benghazi]]\nOn October 22, 2015, Clinton testified before the Committee and answered members' questions for eleven hours before the Committee in a public hearing.<ref name=\"ShearSchmidt\">Michael D. Shear & Michael S. Schmidt, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/23/us/politics/hillary-clinton-benghazi-committee.html Benghazi Panel Engages Clinton in Tense Session], ''The New York Times'', October 22, 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=David A.|last1=Fahrenthold|first2=Elise|last2=Viebeck|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/clintons-benghazi-testimony-today-has-high-political-stakes-for-both-sides/2015/10/22/beff40d2-7838-11e5-bc80-9091021aeb69_story.html|title=GOP lands no solid punches while sparring with Clinton over Benghazi|work=The Washington Post|date=October 22, 2015|accessdate=October 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2015/10/22/transcript-clinton-testifies-before-house-committee-on-benghazi|title=Full Text of Hearing: \"Clinton testifies before House committee on Benghazi\"|work=The Washington Post|date=October 22, 2015|accessdate=October 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' reported that \"the long day of often-testy exchanges between committee members and their prominent witness revealed little new information about an episode that has been the subject of seven previous investigations ... Perhaps stung by recent admissions that the pursuit of Mrs. Clinton's emails was politically motivated, Republican lawmakers on the panel for the most part avoided any mention of her use of a private email server.\"<ref name=\"ShearSchmidt\"/> The email issue did arise shortly before lunch, in \"a shouting match\" between Republican committee chair [[Trey Gowdy]] and two Democrats, [[Adam Schiff]] and [[Elijah Cummings]].<ref name=\"ShearSchmidt\"/> Late in the hearing, Republican Representative [[Jim Jordan (U.S. politician)|Jim Jordan]] of Ohio accused Clinton of changing her accounts of the email service, leading to a \"heated exchange\" in which Clinton said that she had erred in making a private email account, but denied having dealt with anything marked classified, instead seeking \"to be transparent by publicly releasing her emails.\"<ref name=\"ShearSchmidt\"/>\n\n==Freedom of Information lawsuits==\n===''Judicial Watch v. U.S. Department of State''===\n[[File:Huma Abedin handing Hillary Clinton notes and a pen.jpg|thumb|Huma Abedin and Hillary Clinton]]\n\n[[Judicial Watch]], a conservative activist group, filed a complaint against the Department of State in the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]] on September 10, 2013, seeking records under the [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|federal Freedom of Information Act]] relating to Clinton aide [[Huma Abedin]] (a former deputy chief of staff and former senior advisor at the State Department).<ref name=\"JW March 12, 2015\">Judicial Watch, [http://www.judicialwatch.org/press-room/press-releases/citing-misconduct-and-misrepresentation-by-hillary-clinton-and-state-department-judicial-watch-asks-federal-court-to-reopen-lawsuit-seeking-information-on-top-clinton-aide-huma-abedin/ Citing Misconduct and Misrepresentation by Hillary Clinton and State Department, Judicial Watch Asks Federal Court to Reopen Lawsuit Seeking Information on Top Clinton Aide Huma Abedin] (March 12, 2015).</ref><ref name=\"JW September 2013 Complaint\">Judicial Watch, [http://www.judicialwatch.org/document-archive/huma-employment/ Huma Outside Employment Complaint] (September 10, 2013)</ref> Judicial Watch was particularly interested in Abedin's role as a \"special government employee\" (SGE), a consulting position which allowed her to represent outside clients while also serving at the State Department. After corresponding with the State Department, Judicial Watch agreed to dismiss its lawsuit on March 14, 2014.<ref name=\"JW March 12, 2015\"/> On March 12, 2015, in response to the uncovering of Clinton's private email account, it filed a motion to reopen the suit, alleging that the State Department had misrepresented its search and had not properly preserved and maintained records under the act.<ref name=\"JW March 12, 2015\"/> U.S. District Judge [[Emmet G. Sullivan]] granted the motion to reopen the case on June 19, 2015.<ref>[http://www.judicialwatch.org/document-archive/court-order-state-department-01363-2/ Court order reopening case] (June 19, 2015).</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/19/idUSnMKWv47gXa+1c2+MKW20150619 Judicial Watch Statement in Response to Federal Court Reopening Lawsuit Seeking Information on Top Clinton Aide Huma Abedin] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924220619/http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/19/idUSnMKWv47gXa+1c2+MKW20150619 |date=September 24, 2015 }}, Judicial Watch (June 19, 2015).</ref>\n\nOn July 21, 2015, Judge Sullivan issued supplemental discovery orders, including one that Clinton, Abedin, and former Deputy Secretary of State [[Cheryl Mills]] disclose any required information they had not disclosed already, and promise under oath that they had done so, including a description of the extent Abedin and Mills had used Clinton's email server for official government business.<ref name=politico1>{{cite news|last1=Gerstein|first1=Josh|title=Judge wants Clinton certification on emails|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/08/judge-wants-clinton-to-certify-shes-turned-over-some-211652.html|accessdate=August 5, 2015|publisher=Politico|date=August 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=CBS>{{cite news|last1=Flores|first1=Reena|title=Judge wants Clinton confirmation on State Department emails|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/judge-wants-clinton-confirmation-on-state-department-emails/|accessdate=August 5, 2015|publisher=CBS News|date=August 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2015, Clinton filed her declaration, stating \"I have directed that all my emails on clintonemail.com in my custody that were or potentially were federal records be provided to the Department of State,\" and that as a result of this directive, 55,000 pages of emails were produced to the Department on December 5, 2014.<ref name=\"Clinton Declaration\"/><ref name=NYT81015>{{cite news|author1=Michael S. Schmidt|title=All Emails Were Provided, Hillary Clinton Says in Statement|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/us/politics/all-emails-were-provided-hillary-clinton-says-in-statement.html|accessdate=August 11, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=August 10, 2015|quote=I have directed that all my emails on clintonemail.com in my custody that were or potentially were federal records be provided to the Department of State, and on information and belief, this has been done}}</ref><ref name=\"HeldermanConfirmation\"/> She said in her statement that Abedin did have an email account through clintonemail.com that \"was used at times for government business,\" but that Mills did not.<ref name=\"Clinton Declaration\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/r/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2015/08/10/National-Politics/Graphics/HRC%208-10.pdf Clinton Declaration] (filed August 10, 2015).</ref><ref name=NYT81015/><ref name=\"HeldermanConfirmation\">Rosalind S. Helderman, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/hillary-clinton-swears-i-turned-over-all-my-required-e-mails/2015/08/10/36084f6a-3f8c-11e5-bfe3-ff1d8549bfd2_story.html Hillary Clinton swears: I turned over all my required e-mails], ''The Washington Post'', August 10, 2015.</ref> The statement was filed as Clinton faced questions over fifteen emails in exchanges with Blumenthal that were not among the emails she gave to the department the previous year. She did not address the matter of those emails in the statement.<ref name=NYT81015/> On September 25, 2015, several additional emails from her private server<ref name=CNN10252015>{{cite news|last1=Labott|first1=Elise|last2=Levitt|first2=Ross|title=New Hillary Clinton email chain discovered|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/09/25/politics/hillary-clinton-emails-david-petraeus-benghazi|accessdate=September 28, 2015|publisher=CNN|date=September 25, 2015}}</ref> surfaced which she had not provided to the State Department.<ref name=CNN10252015/><ref name=AP10252015>{{cite news|last1=Klapper|first1=Bradley|title=Officials: More work emails from Clinton's private account|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/f80adbe482e14366ad1cec38f597db86/officials-more-work-emails-clintons-private-account|accessdate=September 28, 2015|agency=Associated Press|date=September 25, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Guardian10252015>{{cite news|last1=Woolf|first1=Nicky|title=Officials uncover two chains of emails Hillary Clinton didn't turn over|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/sep/25/hillary-clinton-email-chain-discovered-david-petraeus|accessdate=September 28, 2015|work=The Guardian|date=September 25, 2015}}</ref> These emails between Clinton and General [[David Petraeus]], discussing personnel matters, were part of an email chain that started on a different email account before her tenure as Secretary of State,<ref name=CNN10252015/><ref name=AP10252015/><ref name=Guardian10252015/> but continued onto her private server in late January 2009 after she had taken office.<ref name=CNN10252015/><ref name=AP10252015/><ref name=Guardian10252015/> The existence of these emails also called into question Clinton's previous statement that she did not use the server before March 18, 2009.<ref name=NYT10252015>{{cite news|last1=Schmidt|first1=Michael|title=String of Emails Raises Questions About When Hillary Clinton Began Using Personal Account|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/26/us/politics/string-of-emails-raises-questions-about-when-hillary-clinton-began-using-personal-account.html|accessdate=September 28, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=September 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Judge Sullivan issued a discovery order in the case, ruling that [[Deposition (law)|depositions]] of State Department officials and top Clinton aides were to proceed.<ref>Hsu, Spenser S. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/us-judge-weighs-deeper-probe-into-clintons-private-email-system/2016/02/23/9c27412a-d997-11e5-81ae-7491b9b9e7df_story.html?tid=pm_pop_b U.S. judge orders discovery to go forward over Clinton\u2019s private email system], ''The Washington Post'', February 23, 2016.</ref> On May 26, 2016, Judicial Watch released the transcript of the deposition of Lewis Lukens,<ref>[http://www.judicialwatch.org/document-archive/jw-v-state-lukens-testimony-01363/ JW v. State Lukens Testimony 01363] (May 26, 2016).</ref> on May 31, 2016, the transcript of Cheryl Mills,<ref>[http://www.judicialwatch.org/document-archive/jw-v-state-mills-deposition-01363/ JW v State Mills deposition 01363].</ref> on June 7, 2016, the transcript of Ambassador Stephen Mull,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.judicialwatch.org/press-room/press-releases/clinton-email-update-judicial-watch-releases-clinton-email-deposition-testimony-amb-stephen-mull-former-executive-secretary-state-department|title=Clinton Email Update: Judicial Watch Releases Clinton Email Deposition Testimony of Amb. Stephen Mull, Former Executive Secretary for State Department \u2013 Judicial Watch|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> and on June 9, 2016, Karin Lang, Director of Executive Secretariat Staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.judicialwatch.org/press-room/press-releases/clinton-email-update-judicial-watch-releases-clinton-email-deposition-testimony-karen-lang-director-executive-secretariat-staff/|title=Clinton Email Update: Judicial Watch Releases Clinton Email Deposition Testimony of Karin Lang, Director, Executive Secretariat Staff \u2013 Judicial Watch|publisher=judicialwatch.org|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe testimony of Clarence Finney, who worked in the department responsible for [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|FOIA]] searches, said that he first became curious about Clinton's email setup after seeing the [[Texts from Hillary]] meme on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2016/06/hillary-clinton-emails-probe-blackberry-224154|title=Clinton BlackBerry photo led to State official's query about email account|work=Politico|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=June 11, 2016|first=Josh|last=Gerstein}}</ref>\n\n===''Jason Leopold v. U.S. Department of State''===\nIn November 2014, [[Jason Leopold]] of ''[[Vice News]]'' made a Freedom of Information Act request for Clinton's State Department records,<ref name=\"Brennan on Leopold\"/><ref name=\"Gerstein on Leopold\"/> and, on January 25, 2015, filed a lawsuit in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia seeking to compel production of responsive documents.<ref name=\"Brennan on Leopold\">Brennan, Margaret & Paula Reid, [http://www.cbsnews.com/news/state-dept-to-comply-with-court-order-on-hillary-clintons-emails/ State Dept. to comply with court order on Hillary Clinton's emails], CBS News, May 19, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"Gerstein on Leopold\">Gerstein, Josh. [http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/03/feds-fight-hillary-clintonfocused-email-lawsuit-204672.html Feds fight Hillary Clinton-focused email lawsuit], Politico.com, March 28, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://images.politico.com/global/2015/03/28/leopoldstatestatrep150327.pdf Joint Status Report Regarding Schedule] (filed March 27, 2015) (\"Plaintiff Jason Leopold initiated this Freedom of Information Act ('FOIA') lawsuit against Defendant U.S. Department of State on January 25, 2015. (ECF No. 1). The Department of State answered the complaint on March 2, 2015 (ECF No. 7)\").</ref> After some dispute between Leopold and the State Department over the request, U.S. District Judge [[Rudolph Contreras]] ordered rolling production and release of the emails on a schedule set by the State Department.<ref name=\"Brennan & Reid\">Margaret Brennan & Paula Reid, [http://www.cbsnews.com/news/state-dept-to-comply-with-court-order-on-hillary-clintons-emails \"State Dept. to comply with court order on Hillary Clinton's emails\"], [[CBS News]], May 19, 2015.</ref><ref>Andrew Zajac & Billy House, [https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2015/05/19/judge-orders-rolling-release-clinton-state-department-mail/WxUyky3HdtJJFBob9VG82O/story.html Judge orders rolling release of Clinton's State Department e-mail], Bloomberg News, May 20, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"Leopold May 19\">Jason Leopold, [https://news.vice.com/article/judge-orders-state-department-to-release-clinton-emails-on-rolling-basis \"Judge Orders State Department to Release Clinton Emails on Rolling Basis\"], ''Vice News'', May 19, 2015.</ref>\n\nOver the next several months, the State Department completed production of 30,068 emails, which were released in 14 batches, with the final batch released on February 29, 2016.<ref>Myers, Steven Lee & Julie Hirschfeld Davis. [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/01/us/politics/last-batch-of-hillary-clintons-emails-is-released.html?_r=0 Last Batch of Hillary Clinton\u2019s Emails Is Released], ''The New York Times'', February 29, 2016.</ref> Both the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' and [[WikiLeaks]] independently set up search engines for anyone who would like to search through the Clinton emails released by the State Department.<ref>[http://graphics.wsj.com/hillary-clinton-email-documents/ \"Search Hillary Clinton\u2019s Emails\"], ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''. Retrieved April 17, 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/wikileaks-publishes-searchable-archive-of-clinton-emails/article/2586017 \"WikiLeaks publishes searchable archive of Clinton emails\"], ''[[Washington Examiner]]''. Retrieved May 9, 2016.</ref>\n\nIt was revealed in October 2017 that during the 2016 US Presidential election, Cambridge Analytica funder and GOP mega-donor [[Rebekah Mercer]] had proposed creating a searchable data base for Hillary Clinton emails in the public domain and then forwarded this suggestion to several people, including Cambridge Analytica CEO [[Alexander Nix]], who personally emailed a request to Julian Assange for Clinton's emails.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/10/27/politics/rebekah-mercer-cambridge-analytica-clinton-emails/index.html|title=GOP megadonor requested Trump's data firm organize hacked Clinton emails|author=Dana Bash and Marshall Cohen|publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> Assange responded to the report by saying he denied Nix's request.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/25/us/julian-assange-wikileaks-trump.html|title=Assange Says WikiLeaks Rejected Request by Data Firm Tied to Trump|first=Nicholas|last=Confessore|date=October 25, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2018|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n\nThe emails showed that Blumenthal communicated with Clinton while Secretary on a variety of issues including Benghazi.<ref name=LATimes2>Halper, Evan and Michael A. Memoli, [http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-hillary-clinton-state-emails-20150629-story.html \"More of Hillary Clinton's emails say little about State Department tenure\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', June 30, 2015.</ref><ref name=NYT2>Baker, Peter & Steve Ederjune, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/01/us/politics/new-trove-of-hillary-clintons-emails-highlight-workaday-tasks-at-the-state-department.htm New Trove of Hillary Clinton's Emails Highlights Workaday Tasks at the State Department], ''The New York Times'', June 30, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"NJ 3d Batch\">Schultheis, Emily & Lauren Fox, [http://www.nationaljournal.com/2016-elections/state-dept-releases-more-hillary-clinton-emails-20150731 State Department Releases More Hillary Clinton Emails] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821141056/http://www.nationaljournal.com/2016-elections/state-dept-releases-more-hillary-clinton-emails-20150731 |date=August 21, 2015}}, ''National Journal'', July 31, 2015.</ref><ref>Kumar, Anita & Greg Gordon & Marisa Taylor, [http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/election/presidential-election/article31345289.html Investigators now examining 305 Clinton emails for classified information], McClatchy Washington Bureau (August 17, 2015).</ref><!-- preserve some refs\n<ref name=\"UPI First Batch\">Danielle Haynes, [http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2015/05/22/First-batch-of-Hillary-Clinton-emails-on-Benghazi-released/7431432313084/ First batch of Hillary Clinton emails on Benghazi released], UPI.com, May 22, 2015.</ref><ref name=BBC32853708>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-32853708|title=First set of Hillary Clinton emails published online|work=BBC News|date=May 22, 2015|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref><ref name=WP3>Gearan, Anne & Colby Itkowitz, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/a-glimpse-at-hillary-clintons-e-mails-from-celebrities-to-politicians/2015/06/30/ae0b96de-1f52-11e5-aeb9-a411a84c9d55_story.html \"A glimpse at Hillary Clinton's e-mails, from celebrities to politicians\"], ''The Washington Post'', July 1, 2015.</ref><ref name=NYT2 /><ref name=NJ2>Geman, Ben, [http://www.nationaljournal.com/2016-elections/here-are-the-3-000-pages-of-hillary-clinton-s-emails-just-released-by-the-state-department-20150630 Here Are the 3,000 Pages of Hillary Clinton\u2019s Emails Just Released by the State Department], ''National Journal'', June 30, 2015.</ref>-->\n\n===''Associated Press v. U.S. Department of State''===\nOn March 11, 2015, the day after Clinton acknowledged her private email account, the Associated Press (AP) filed suit against the State Department regarding multiple FOIA requests over the past five years. The requests were for various emails and other documents from Clinton's time as secretary of state and were still unfulfilled at the time.<ref name=\"APSuitFiled\">Associated Press, [http://www.cbsnews.com/news/associated-press-sues-state-department-for-hillary-clinton-emails/ Associated Press sues State Department for Hillary Clinton emails], CBS News, March 11, 2015.</ref><ref>[https://cryptome.org/2015/03/ap-001.pdf Complaint], ''Associated Press v. U.S. Department of State'' (filed March 11, 2015).</ref><ref name=\"Leon Schedule\">Eric Tucker, [http://bigstory.ap.org/article/17bb3935546b422ba4246e934e00d8d7/clinton-records-judge-sets-schedule-release-ap Clinton records: Judge sets schedule for release to AP] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811004955/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/17bb3935546b422ba4246e934e00d8d7/clinton-records-judge-sets-schedule-release-ap |date=August 11, 2015 }}, Associated Press, August 7, 2015.</ref> The State Department said that a high volume of FOIA requests and a large backlog had caused the delay.<ref name=\"APSuitFiled\"/><ref name=\"Gerstein July 20 Hearing\">Josh Gerstein, [http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/07/judge-slams-state-department-over-hillary-clintonrelated-210878.html Judge slams State Department over Hillary Clinton-related records], Politico.com, July 20, 2015.</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2015, U.S. District Judge [[Richard J. Leon]] reacted angrily to what he said was \"the State Department for four years dragging their feet.\"<ref name=\"Gerstein July 20 Hearing\"/> Leon said that \"even the least ambitious bureaucrat\" could process the request faster than the State Department was doing.<ref>David Francis, [https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/07/30/judge-the-least-ambitious-bureaucrat-could-process-clintons-personal-emails-faster \"Judge: The 'Least Ambitious' Bureaucrat Could Process Clinton's Personal Emails Faster\"], ''Foreign Policy'', July 30, 2015.</ref>\n\nOn August 7, 2015, Leon issued an order setting a stringent schedule for the State Department to provide the AP with the requested documents over the next eight months.<ref name=\"Leon Schedule\"/> The order issued by Leon did not include the 55,000 pages of Clinton emails the State Department scheduled to be released in the Leopold case, or take into account 20 boxes given to the State Department by [[Philippe Reines]], a former Clinton senior adviser.<ref name=\"Leon Schedule\"/>\n\n===Other suits and coordination of email cases===\nIn September 2015, the State Department filed a motion in court seeking to consolidate and coordinate the large number of Freedom of Information Act lawsuits relating to Clinton and Clinton-related emails. There were at the time at least three dozen lawsuits pending, before 17 different judges.<ref>Josh Gerstein, [http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/09/feds-move-to-consolidate-lawsuits-over-hillary-clinton-emails-213228 Feds move to consolidate lawsuits over Hillary Clinton emails], ''Politico'', September 1, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"TauCoordination\">Tau, Byron, [https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2015/10/08/court-declines-to-consolidate-clinton-emails-lawsuits/ Court Declines to Consolidate Clinton Emails Lawsuits], ''The Wall Street Journal'', October 8, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn a [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]] order issued on October 8, 2015, Chief U.S. District Judge [[Richard W. Roberts]] wrote that the cases did not meet the usual criteria for consolidation but: \"The judges who have been randomly assigned to these cases have been and continue to be committed to informal coordination so as to avoid unnecessary inefficiencies and confusion, and the parties are also urged to meet and confer to assist in coordination.\"<ref name=\"TauCoordination\"/>\n\nIn 2015, Judicial Watch and the Cause of Action Institute filed two lawsuits seeking a court order to compel the Department of State and the [[National Archives and Records Administration]] to recover emails from Clinton's server. In January 2016, these two suits (which were consolidated because they involved the same issues) were dismissed as [[Mootness|moot]] by U.S. District Judge [[James Boasberg]], because the government was already working to recover and preserve these emails.<ref>[http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b219d2da39454b799b653187d6ab2831/judge-dismisses-pair-lawsuits-arising-clinton-emails Judge dismisses pair of lawsuits arising from Clinton emails] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404032537/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b219d2da39454b799b653187d6ab2831/judge-dismisses-pair-lawsuits-arising-clinton-emails |date=April 4, 2016 }}, Associated Press, January 11, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the [[Republican National Committee]] filed four new [[complaint (law)|complaints]] in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia stemming from Freedom of Information Act requests it had filed the previous year. These new filings brought the total number of civil suits over access to Clinton's records pending in federal court to at least 38.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2016-03-15/gop-files-more-lawsuits-seeking-hillary-clinton-records|title=GOP files a flurry of new lawsuits seeking reams of government documents related to Clinton's tenure as secretary of state|date=March 15, 2016|work=[[U.S. News and World Report]]|first1=Michael|last1=Biesecker|agency=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, in response to the Republican National Committee's complaints filed in March 2016, the State Department estimates it will take 75 years to complete the review of documents which are responsive to the complaints.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2016/06/07/estimate-of-75-years-to-process-clinton-aides-email-not-an-outlandish-estimation|title=Estimate of 75 Years to Release Clinton Aides' Email 'Not an Outlandish Estimation'|last=Tau|first=Byron|website=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref> It has been observed that a delay of this nature would cause the documents to remain out of public view longer than the vast majority of classified documents which must be declassified after 25 years.<ref name=\"NYT20061221\">{{cite news|author=Scott Shane|title=U.S. to Declassify Secrets at Age 25|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/21/washington/21declassify.html|work=[[New York Times]]|date=December 21, 2006|accessdate=September 16, 2018|quote=Secret documents 25 years old or older will lose their classified status without so much as the stroke of a pen, unless agencies have sought exemptions on the ground that the material remains secret.}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2016 Democratic National Committee email leak]]\n* [[Clinton Foundation\u2013State Department controversy]]\n* [[White House FBI files controversy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hillary Rodham Clinton email use as United States Secretary of State}}\n\n* [https://www.archives.gov/press/press-releases/2016/nr16-29.html Press release] by the [[National Archives and Records Administration]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160505102708/http://thompsontimeline.com/The_Clinton_Email_Scandal_Timeline The Clinton Email Scandal Timeline] created by the author of [[The Terror Timeline]]\n* [https://foia.state.gov/Search/Results.aspx?collection=Clinton_Email Secretary Clinton Emails at the United States Department of State website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160311140652/https://www.hillaryclinton.com/briefing/factsheets/2015/07/13/email-facts/ The Facts About Hillary Clinton\u2019s Emails] at the Hillary Clinton campaign website\n* [https://vault.fbi.gov/hillary-r.-clinton Clinton E-Mail Investigation] by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]\n{{Hillary Clinton}}\n[[Category:2015 controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:2015 in American politics]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Classified information in the United States]]\n[[Category:Computing-related controversies and disputes]]\n[[Category:Controversies of the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic correspondence]]\n[[Category:Email]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation operations]]\n[[Category:Hillary Clinton controversies|Email]]\n[[Category:Obama administration controversies]]\n[[Category:Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American political controversy surrounding Hillary Clinton's conduct while Secretary of State}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Hillary Clinton series}}\nDuring [[Hillary Clinton's tenure as Secretary of State|her tenure as United States Secretary of State]], [[Hillary Clinton]] drew controversy by using a private [[email server]] for official public communications rather than using official [[United States Department of State|State Department]] email accounts maintained on secure federal servers. An [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] examination of Clinton's server found over 100 emails containing classified information, including 65 emails deemed \"Secret\" and 22 deemed \"Top Secret\". An additional 2,093 emails not marked classified were retroactively classified by the State Department. \n\nSome experts, officials, and members of [[United States Congress|Congress]] contended that Clinton's use of a private [[Message transfer agent|messaging system]] and a private server violated federal law, specifically 18 U.S. Code \u00a7\u202f1924, regarding the unauthorized removal and retention of classified documents or materials, as well as State Department protocols and procedures, and regulations governing [[recordkeeping]]. Clinton responded that her use complied with federal laws and State Department regulations, and that former secretaries of state had also maintained personal email accounts. News reports by NBC and CNN indicated that the emails discussed \"innocuous\" matters already available in the public domain. For example, the [[Drone strikes in Pakistan|CIA drone program]] has been widely discussed in the public domain since the early 2000s; however, the very existence of the program is technically classified, so sharing a newspaper article that mentions it would constitute a security breach according to the CIA.<ref>\"Secrecy defines Obama\u2019s drone war,\" ''Washington Post'', December 19, 2011: https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/secrecy-defines-obamas-drone-war/2011/10/28/gIQAPKNR5O_story.html</ref><ref>\"DoD Warns Employees of Classified Info in Public Domain,\" Federation of American Scientists, June 11, 2013: https://fas.org/blogs/secrecy/2013/06/dod-classified/</ref>  \n\nThe controversy was a major point of discussion and contention during the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]], in which Clinton was the Democratic nominee. In May, the [[Office of the Inspector General of the Department of State|State Department's Office of the Inspector General]] released a report about the State Department's email practices, including Clinton's. In July, FBI director [[James Comey]] announced that the FBI investigation had concluded that Clinton had been \"extremely careless\" but recommended that no charges be filed. Clinton's opponent, then presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]], used the nickname \"Crooked Hillary\" to criticize Clinton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/01/05/trumps-nicknames-for-rivals-from-rocket-man-to-pocahontas.html|title=Trump's nicknames for rivals, from 'Rocket Man' to 'Pocahontas'|first=Kaitlyn|last=Schallhorn|date=April 17, 2018|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2016, days before the election, Comey notified Congress that the FBI had started looking into newly discovered emails. On November 6, Comey notified Congress that the FBI had not changed its original conclusion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/2016/11/06/fbi-not-recommending-charges-over-new-clinton-emails/93395808/|work=USA Today|title=FBI declares it is finally done investigating Hillary Clinton's email|authors=Schouten, Fredreka, Kevin Johnson & Heidi Przybyla|date=November 6, 2016}}</ref> Comey's timing was contentious, with critics saying that he had violated Department of Justice guidelines and precedent, and prejudiced the public against Clinton.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/11/james-comey-fbi-clinton-230851|title=Will Comey survive the Clinton email flap?|work=Politico|access-date=April 18, 2018}}</ref> The controversy received more media coverage than any other topic during the presidential campaign.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cjr.org/analysis/fake-news-media-election-trump.php|title=Don't blame the election on fake news. Blame it on the media.|work=Columbia Journalism Review|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://shorensteincenter.org/news-coverage-2016-national-conventions/|title=News Coverage of the 2016 National Conventions: Negative News, Lacking Context|date=September 21, 2016|work=Shorenstein Center|access-date=December 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://cyber.harvard.edu/publications/2017/08/mediacloud|title=Partisanship, Propaganda, and Disinformation: Online Media and the 2016 U.S. Presidential Election {{!}} Berkman Klein Center|website=cyber.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=December 7, 2017}}</ref> Clinton and other observers argue that the reopening of the investigation contributed to her loss in the election. In April 2018, Comey said in his new book \"A Higher Loyalty\" that, in hindsight, he wondered about whether his decision was unconsciously influenced by the fact that he thought it extremely likely that Clinton would become the next President.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/13/james-comey-clinton-investigation-poll-numbers-522958|title=Fact-check: Comey didn't say he reopened Clinton investigation because of poll numbers|work=Politico|access-date=April 18, 2018}}</ref> On June 14, 2018, the Department of Justice's Office of the Inspector General released [[Inspector General report on FBI and DOJ actions in the 2016 election|its report]] on the FBI's and DOJ's handling of Clinton's investigation, finding no evidence of political bias and lending support for the decision to not prosecute Clinton.<ref name=\"highlights\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/live-news/inspector-general-report-clinton-email-investigation-2018-06-14-live-updates/|title=Highlights of DOJ inspector general report on handling of Clinton email probe|date=June 14, 2018|work=CBS News|access-date=June 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|4}}\n\n==Background==\n===Clinton's use of BlackBerrys===\n[[File:U.S. Air Force Col. Peggy Poore, commander, 65th Air Base Wing, greets Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton during a stop at Lajes Field, Azores, Portugal, June 3, 2009 090603-F-MK264-040.jpg|thumb|Clinton holding a Blackberry phone in 2009]]\nPrior to her appointment as Secretary of State in 2009, Clinton and her circle of friends and colleagues communicated via [[BlackBerry]] phones.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/how-clintons-email-scandal-took-root/2016/03/27/ee301168-e162-11e5-846c-10191d1fc4ec_story.html|title=How Clinton's email scandal took root|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> State Department security personnel suggested this would pose a security risk during her tenure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/26/us/politics/state-department-hillary-clinton-emails.html|title=Hillary Clinton Is Criticized for Private Emails in State Dept. Review|date=May 26, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> The email account used on Clinton's BlackBerry was then hosted on a private server in the basement of her home in [[Chappaqua, New York]], but that information was not disclosed to State Department security personnel or senior State Department personnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/may/31/hillary-clinton/fact-checking-hillary-clintons-claim-her-email-pra|title=Not 'allowed': Clinton's email talk misses the mark|publisher=politifact.com|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSetting up a secure desktop computer in her office was suggested, but Clinton was unfamiliar with their use<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/27/us/politics/hillary-clinton-state-department-email-inquiry.html|title=Hillary Clinton Wasn't Adept at Using a Desktop for Email, Inquiry Is Told|date=May 27, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> and opted for the convenience of her BlackBerry,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-31819843|title=Hillary Clinton: Private email set up for 'convenience'|publisher=BBC|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> not the State Department, government protocol of a secured desktop computer. Efforts to find a secure solution were abandoned by Clinton,<ref name=\"lawnewz.com\">{{cite web|url=http://lawnewz.com/high-profile/we-now-know-more-about-why-clinton-set-up-private-server-and-its-sketchyy/|title=NSA Refused Clinton a Secure Phone, She Set Up Private Server Instead|publisher=lawnewz.com|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> and she was warned by State Department security personnel about the vulnerability of an unsecured BlackBerry to hacking.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2015/3/3/govt-cybersecurity-source-clintons-office-warned-private-email-use.html|title=Revealed: Clinton's office was warned over private email use|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> She affirmed her knowledge of the danger, and was reportedly told that the [[Bureau of Diplomatic Security]] had obtained intelligence about her vulnerability while she was on a trip to Asia, but continued to use her BlackBerry outside her office.<ref name=\"WP032716\">{{cite news|author1=Robert O'Harrow Jr.|title=How Clinton's email scandal took root|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/how-clintons-email-scandal-took-root/2016/03/27/ee301168-e162-11e5-846c-10191d1fc4ec_story.html|accessdate=March 28, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=March 27, 2016|quote=\"The issue here is one of personal comfort\", one of the participants in that meeting, Donald Reid, the department's senior coordinator for security infrastructure, wrote afterward in an email that described Clinton's inner circle of advisers as \"dedicated [BlackBerry] addicts\". ... \"Her attention was drawn to the sentence that indicates (Diplomatic Security) have intelligence concerning this vulnerability during her recent trip to Asia. ... \"}}</ref>\n\n===Domain names and email server===\n[[File:Clintonemail.com Outlook Web App.png|thumb|A screenshot of the default Outlook Web App login page that is displayed when navigating to [https://mail.clintonemail.com/owa Clinton's email service]]]\nAt the time of Senate confirmation hearings on Hillary Clinton's nomination as Secretary of State, the [[domain name]]s clintonemail.com, wjcoffice.com, and presidentclinton.com were [[Domain registration|registered]] to Eric Hoteham,<ref name=\"ABCNews.Hoteham\">{{cite web|title=Hillary Clinton Email Mystery Man: What We Know About Eric Hoteham|author=Meghan Keneally|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/hillary-clinton-email-mystery-man-eric-hoteham/story?id=29413827|date=March 5, 2015|publisher=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=March 19, 2015}} (The name Eric Hoteham is similar to that of Eric Hothem, a former Clinton aide.)</ref> with the home of Clinton and her husband in Chappaqua, New York, as the contact address.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://washington.cbslocal.com/2015/03/04/clinton-private-server-listed-under-mysterious-untraceable-name|title=Who Is Eric Hoteham? Clinton Private Server Listed Under Mysterious, Untraceable Name|publisher=Washington.cbslocal.com|date=March 4, 2015|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sick|first=Gary|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/03/hillary-clinton-email-5-questions-115876.html|title=5 questions: The Clinton email|publisher=Politico.com|date=March 9, 2015|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref> The domains were pointed to a private email server that Clinton (who never had a state.gov email account) used to send and receive email, and which was purchased and installed in the Clintons' home for [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2008|her 2008 presidential campaign]].<ref name=NYT8815>{{cite news|author1=Scott Shane  |author2=Michael S. Schmidt|title=Hillary Clinton Emails Take Long Path to Controversy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/09/us/hillary-clinton-emails-take-long-path-to-controversy.html|accessdate=August 8, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=August 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe email server was located in the Clintons' home in Chappaqua, New York, from January 2009 until 2013, when it was sent to a [[data center]] in New Jersey before being handed over to Platte River Networks, a Denver-based [[information technology]] firm that Clinton hired to manage her email system.<ref name=AP0813 /><ref>Natasha Bertrand, [http://www.businessinsider.com/platte-river-hillary-clinton-private-server-2015-8 \"VP of Cybersecurity Firm Hired by Hillary Clinton: 'We would never have taken it on' if we knew of the ensuing chaos\"], ''Business Insider'', August 19, 2015.</ref><ref name=WP81215>{{cite news|author1=Tom Hamburger  |author2=Karen Tumulty|title=Hillary Clinton's e-mail server turned over to FBI|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/clintons-e-mail-server-turned-over-to-fbi/2015/08/12/aba5feea-4160-11e5-8ab4-c73967a143d3_story.html|accessdate=August 14, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=August 12, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Clintonserver>{{cite news|last1=Labott|first1=Elise|title=Hillary Clinton to turn over private email server to Justice Department|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/11/politics/hillary-clinton-email-server-justice-department/index.html|accessdate=August 12, 2015|publisher=CNN|date=August 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=server>{{cite news|last1=Dilanian|first1=Ken|title=Clinton relents, gives up possession of private email server|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/40f1d5d9d6cc411a83e8466253e6ef3e/us-official-fbi-has-hillary-clinton-emails-home-server|agency=Associated Press|date=August 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe server itself runs a [[Microsoft Exchange Server|Microsoft Exchange 2010]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2015/03/clintons-email-hosted-on-exchange-2010-server-now-not-in-chappaqua|title=Update: Clinton's e-mail is on a hosted Exchange 2010 server, not in Chappaqua|access-date=July 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mail.clintonemail.com/owa|title=Outlook Web App|website=mail.clintonemail.com|access-date=July 6, 2016}}</ref> server with access to emails over the internet being delivered by [[Outlook Web App]]. The web page is secured with a [[TLS/SSL|TLS certificate]] to allow information to be transmitted securely when using the website. However, for the first two months of its use \u2013 January 2009 through March 29, 2009 \u2013 the web page was reportedly not secured with a TLS certificate, meaning that information transmitted using the service was unencrypted and may have been liable to interception.<ref name=\"WP032716\"/>\n\n===Initial awareness===\nAs early as 2009, officials with the [[National Archives and Records Administration]] (NARA) expressed concerns over possible violations of normal federal government record-keeping procedures at the State Department under then-Secretary Clinton.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gerstein|first=Josh|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/03/state-department-email-rule-hillary-clinton-115804.html?hp=t4_r|title=Clinton private email violated 'clear-cut' State Dept. rules|publisher=Politico.com|date=March 6, 2015|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, near the end of Clinton's tenure as Secretary of State, a nonprofit group called [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]], or CREW, filed a [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|FOIA]] request seeking records about her email. CREW received a response in May 2013: \"no records responsive to your request were located.\"<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">O'Harrow Jr., Robert.  [https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/how-clintons-email-scandal-took-root/2016/03/27/ee301168-e162-11e5-846c-10191d1fc4ec_story.html \"How Clinton's email scandal took root\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'''', March 27, 2016.</ref> Emails sent to Clinton's private clintonemail.com address were first discovered in March 2013, when a hacker named \"[[Guccifer]]\" widely distributed emails sent to Clinton from [[Sidney Blumenthal]], which Guccifer obtained by illegally accessing Blumenthal's email account.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=Hacker Begins Distributing Confidential Memos Sent To Hillary Clinton On Libya, Benghazi Attack|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/buster/sidney-blumenthal/hacker-distributes-memos-784091|website=The Smoking Gun|accessdate=September 30, 2015|date = March 18, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title=Hacked Emails Show Hillary Clinton Was Receiving Advice at a Private Email Account From Banned, Obama-Hating Former Staffer |url=http://gawker.com/5991563/hacked-emails-show-hillary-clinton-was-receiving-advice-at-a-private-email-account-from-banned-obama-hating-former-staffer |accessdate=September 30, 2015 |first=John |last=Cook |website=Gawker |date=March 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001023951/http://gawker.com/5991563/hacked-emails-show-hillary-clinton-was-receiving-advice-at-a-private-email-account-from-banned-obama-hating-former-staffer |archivedate=October 1, 2015  }}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|title='Guccifer' hacks Hillary Clinton's e-emails via aide's account|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2013/03/19/guccifer-hacker-hillary-clinton-sidney-blumenthal-george-hw-bush/2001429/|accessdate=September 30, 2015|website=USA Today|date=March 22, 2013|last=Acohido|first=Byron}}</ref> The emails dealt with the [[2012 Benghazi attack]] and other issues in [[Libya]] and revealed the existence of her clintonemail.com address.<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\":2\"/>\n\nBlumenthal did not have a security clearance when he received material from Clinton that has since been characterized as classified by the State Department.<ref>Gerstein, Josh. [http://www.politico.com/story/2015/10/hillary-clinton-sidney-blumenthal-emails-benghazi-hearings-215083 \"Clinton's emails from Blumenthal spark tension\"], [[Politico]] (October 22, 2015): \"At least one [email] has been deemed classified by State, including information Clinton sent to Blumenthal, who had no security clearance.\"</ref><ref>Morrison, Micah.  [https://nypost.com/2015/10/31/hillary-clintons-rogue-agenda-why-sid-blumenthal-matters/ \"Hillary Clinton's rogue agenda: Why Sid Blumenthal matters\"], ''[[New York Post]]'', October 31, 2015; \"The November 2009 e-mail was sent by Wilson to Blumenthal, who passed it on to Clinton. Most of Clinton's reply to Blumenthal is redacted as classified.\"</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2014, lawyers from the State Department noticed a number of emails from Clinton's personal account, while reviewing documents requested by the House Select Committee on Benghazi. A request by the State Department for additional emails led to negotiations with her lawyers and advisors. In October, the State Department sent letters to Clinton and all previous Secretaries of State back to [[Madeleine Albright]] requesting emails and documents related to their work while in office. On December 5, 2014, Clinton lawyers delivered 12 file boxes filled with printed paper containing more than 30,000 emails. Clinton withheld almost 32,000 emails deemed to be of a personal nature.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\"/> Datto, Inc., which provided [[data backup]] service for Clinton's email, agreed to give the FBI the hardware that stored the backups.<ref name=WP10715>{{cite news|author1=Tom Hamburger  |author2=Rosalind S. Helderman|title=FBI probe of Clinton e-mail expands to second data company|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/fbi-probe-of-clinton-e-mail-expands-to-second-data-company/2015/10/06/3d94ba46-6c48-11e5-b31c-d80d62b53e28_story.html|accessdate=October 7, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of May 2016, no answer had been provided to the public as to whether 31,000 emails deleted by Hillary Clinton as personal have been or could be recovered.<ref>Emery, Eugene.  [http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/apr/03/hillary-clinton/hillary-clinton-i-have-now-put-out-all-my-emails/ \"Hillary Clinton spins on \u2018Meet the Press,\u2019 says she put out all her emails\"], ''[[Politifact]]'' (April 3, 2016).</ref>\n\nA March 2, 2015 ''[[New York Times]]'' article broke the story that the Benghazi panel had discovered that Clinton exclusively used her own private email server rather than a government-issued one throughout her time as Secretary of State, and that her aides took no action to preserve emails sent or received from her personal accounts as required by law.<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\" /><ref name=\"nytimes.com\">Michael S. Schmidt, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/03/us/politics/hillary-clintons-use-of-private-email-at-state-department-raises-flags.html Hillary Clinton Used Personal Email Account at State Dept., Possibly Breaking Rules], ''The New York Times'', March 2, 2015.</ref><ref>Jack Gillum - \"H [https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/ap-finds-hillary-clinton-used-private-server-official-email/ illary Clinton used private server for official email\"], Associated Press, March 4, 2015. Retrieved November 14, 2016.</ref> At that point, Clinton announced that she had asked the State Department to release her emails.<ref name=NYT0315>{{cite news|author1=Schmidt, Michael S.|title=Hillary Clinton Asks State Department to Vet Emails for Release|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/06/us/politics/hillary-clinton-asks-state-dept-to-review-emails-for-public-release.html?ref=politics&_r=1|accessdate=November 5, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=March 5, 2015}}</ref> Some in the media labeled the controversy \"emailgate.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Anthony |last=Zurcher |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-31806907 |title=Hillary Clinton's 'emailgate' diced and sliced |work=BBC News |date=March 11, 2015 |archivedate=March 12, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312173705/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-31806907 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Kurt |last=Eichenwald |url=http://www.newsweek.com/hillary-clinton-emailgate-312784 |title=Why Hillary Clinton's 'Emailgate' Is a Fake Scandal |work=Newsweek |date=March 3, 2015 |archive-date=March 10, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150310235140/http://www.newsweek.com/hillary-clinton-emailgate-312784 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Margaret |last=Hartmann |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2015/08/hillary-clinton-legal-emailgate.html |title=Could Hillary Clinton Face Criminal Charges Over Emailgate? |work=New York |date=August 21, 2015 |archive-date=November 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20161103202304/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2015/08/hillary-clinton-legal-emailgate.html |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n==Use of private server for government business==\nAccording to Clinton's spokesperson Nick Merrill, a number of government officials have used private email accounts for official business, including secretaries of state before Clinton.<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-hillary-clinton-emails-20150303-story.html|title=Hillary Clinton's use of private email not unusual, but still raises questions|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 3, 2015|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nState Department spokesperson [[Marie Harf]] said that: \"For some historical context, Secretary [[John Kerry|Kerry]] is the first secretary of state to rely primarily on a state.gov email account.\"<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\">Domenico Montanaro, [https://www.npr.org/sections/itsallpolitics/2015/04/02/396823014/fact-check-hillary-clinton-those-emails-and-the-law Fact Check: Hillary Clinton, Those Emails and the Law], NPR (April 2, 2015).</ref> John Wonderlich, a transparency advocate with the [[Sunlight Foundation]], observed while many government officials used private email accounts, their use of private email servers was much rarer.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|title = Howard Dean: 'Tremendous' number of public officials have done what Hillary Clinton did with email|url = http://www.politifact.com/punditfact/statements/2015/aug/18/howard-dean/howard-dean-tremendous-number-public-officials-hav/|website = @politifact|access-date = February 9, 2016}}</ref> A [[Bush White House email controversy|notable exception]] was during the [[George W. Bush|Bush administration]], when dozens of senior White House officials conducted government business via approximately 22 million emails using accounts they had on a server owned by the Republican National Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/2016/09/23/george-w-bush-white-house-lost-22-million-emails-497373.html|title=George W. Bush's White House \"lost\" 22 million emails|first=Nina Burleigh On 9/12/16 at 7:31|last=AM|date=September 12, 2016|website=Newsweek}}</ref>\n\nDan Metcalfe, a former head of the Justice Department's Office of Information and Privacy, said this gave her even tighter control over her emails by not involving a third party such as Google and helped prevent their disclosure by Congressional subpoena. He added: \"She managed successfully to insulate her official emails, categorically, from the FOIA, both during her tenure at State and long after her departure from it\u2014perhaps forever,\" making it \"a blatant circumvention of the [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|FOIA]] by someone who unquestionably knows better.\"<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\" /><ref>{{cite web|title = Hillary's Email Defense Is Laughable|url = http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/03/hillary-clinton-email-scandal-defense-laughable-foia-116116|website = Politico.com|access-date = February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Harf, use by government officials of personal email for government business is permissible under the [[Federal Records Act]], so long as relevant official communications, including all work-related emails, are preserved by the agency. The Act (which was [[Presidential and Federal Records Act Amendments of 2014|amended in late 2014]] after Clinton left office to require that personal emails be transferred to government servers within 20 days) requires agencies to retain all official communications, including all work-related emails, and stipulates that government employees cannot destroy or remove relevant records.<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\"/> NARA regulations dictate how records should be created and maintained, require that they must be maintained \"by the agency\" and \"readily found,\" and that the records must \"make possible a proper scrutiny by the Congress.\"<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\"/> Section 1924 of [[Title 18 of the United States Code]] addresses the deletion and retention of classified documents, under which \"knowingly\" removing or housing classified information at an \"unauthorized location\" is subject to a fine, or up to a year in prison.<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\"/>\n\nExperts such as Metcalfe agree that these practices are allowed by federal law assuming that the material is not supposed to be classified,<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\"/><ref>{{cite web|author1=Bob Cusack  |author2=Molly K. Hooper|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/237012-the-backer-who-could-hurt-hillary|title=The Hillary backer who will pose problems for her 2016 bid|newspaper=The Hill|date=March 26, 2015}}</ref> or at least these practices are allowed in case of emergencies,<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> but they discourage these practices, believing that official email accounts should be used.<ref name=\"MontanaroFactCheck\"/>\n\nJason R. Baron, the former head of [[litigation]] at NARA, described the practice as \"highly unusual\" but not a violation of the law. In a separate interview, he said, \"It is very difficult to conceive of a scenario\u2014short of nuclear winter\u2014where an agency would be justified in allowing its cabinet-level head officer to solely use a private email communications channel for the conduct of government business.\"<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/><ref>Merica, Dan.[https://twitter.com/danmericaCNN/status/572842630855430145 Report via CNN Tweet (March 3, 2015), \"Jason Baron, former head of litigation at the NARA, says Clinton didn't 'violate' the law. 'The Federal Records Act is amorphous enough.'\"]</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Seitz-Wald|first=Alex|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/hillary-clinton-email-problem-not-going-away|title=Hillary Clinton's email problem is not going away|publisher=[[MSNBC]]|date=March 4, 2015|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref> Baron told the Senate Judiciary Committee in May 2015 that \"any employee's decision to conduct all email correspondence through a private email network, using a non-''.gov'' address, is inconsistent with long-established policies and practices under the Federal Records Act and NARA regulations governing all federal agencies.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Eugene Kiely|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2015/09/more-spin-on-clinton-emails|title=More Spin on Clinton Emails|publisher=FactCheck.org|date=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== May 2016 report from State Department's inspector general ===\nIn May 2016, [[Office of the Inspector General of the Department of State|the Department's Office]] of the [[Inspector General of the Department of State|Inspector General]] [[Steve A. Linick]] released an 83-page report about the State Department's email practices.<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\" /><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/apps/g/page/politics/state-department-report-on-clintons-email-practices/2039/?tid=a_inl Office of the Secretary: Evaluation of Email Records Management and Cybersecurity Requirements], Office of the Inspector General of the U.S. Department of State and Broadcasting Board of Governors (May 2016) (republished by ''The Washington Post'').</ref><ref>Morello, Carol and Yang, Jia. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2016/05/25/here-are-the-most-critical-parts-of-the-state-dept-inspector-general-report-on-clintons-email-use/?tid=a_inl Here are the most critical parts of the State Department inspector general report on Clinton\u2019s email use], ''The Washington Post'', May 25, 2016.</ref> The Inspector General was unable to find evidence that Clinton had ever sought approval from the State Department staff for her use of a private email server, determining that if Clinton had sought approval, Department staff would have declined her setup because of the \"security risks in doing so.\"<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\"/> Aside from security risks, the report stated that \"she did not comply with the Department's policies that were implemented in accordance with the Federal Records Act.\"<ref>Dilanian, Ken. [https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/clinton-broke-federal-rules-email-server-audit-finds-n580131 \"Clinton Broke Federal Rules With Email Server, Audit Finds\"], [[NBC News]], May 25, 2016.</ref> Each of these findings contradicted what Clinton and her aides had been saying up to that point.<ref>Lerer, Lisa; Lucey, Catherine. \"[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/ap-fact-check-some-clinton-email-misstatements/ AP Fact Check: Some Clinton email misstatements]\". Associated Press. Public Broadcasting System. May 31, 2016.</ref><ref>Carroll, Lauren. [http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/may/31/hillary-clinton/fact-checking-hillary-clintons-claim-her-email-pra \"Fact-checking Hillary Clinton's claim that her email practices were 'allowed'\"], Polifact, May 31, 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2016/05/ig-report-on-clintons-emails/|title=IG Report on Clinton's Emails| publisher=factcheck.org|author=Kieley, Eugene|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=November 21, 2018}}</ref> The report also stated that Clinton and her senior aides declined to speak with the investigators, while the previous four Secretaries of State did so.<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\"/>\n\nThe report also reviewed the practices of several previous Secretaries of State and concluded that the Department's record keeping practices were subpar for many years.<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\"/> The Inspector General criticized Clinton's use of private email for Department business, concluding that it was \"not an appropriate method\" of document preservation and did not follow Department policies that aim to comply with federal record laws. The report also criticized Colin Powell, who used a personal email account for business, saying that this violated some of the same Department policies.<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\"/> State Department spokesman Mark Toner said the report emphasized the need for federal agencies to adapt \"decades-old record-keeping practices to the email-dominated modern era\" and said that the Department's record-retention practices had been improved under the current Secretary of State [[John F. Kerry]], Clinton's successor.<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\"/> The report also notes that the rules for preserving work-related emails were updated in 2009.<ref>Browne, Ryan and Evan Perez. [http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/25/politics/state-department-report-faults-clinton-over-email-use/ \u201cState Department report slams Clinton email use\u201d], [[CNN]], May 25, 2016: \"while the report acknowledges personal email use by previous secretaries, it also notes that the rules for preserving work emails sent from a personal email account were updated in 2009, the year Clinton took office\".</ref>\n\nInspector General Linick wrote that he \"found no evidence that staff in the Office of the Legal Adviser reviewed or approved Secretary Clinton's personal system,\" and also found that multiple State employees who raised concerns regarding Clinton's server were told that the Office of the Legal Adviser had approved it, and were further told to \"never speak of the Secretary's personal email system again.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/5/25/11771850/hillary-clinton-emails-inspector-general-report|title=What the new inspector general report on Hillary Clinton's emails actually says|author=Andrew Prokop|date=May 25, 2016|work=Vox}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/26/opinions/clinton-email-server-ig-report-opinion-cox/|title=Hillary Clinton's shrinking email defense|author=Douglas Cox|date=May 26, 2016|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2016/05/state-department-hillary-clinton-violated-record-keeping-rules|title=State Department Inspector General Finds Hillary Clinton Violated Recordkeeping Rules|work=Mother Jones}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/26/us/politics/state-department-hillary-clinton-emails.html|title=Hillary Clinton Is Criticized for Private Emails in State Dept. Review|date=May 26, 2016|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nClinton campaign spokesman [[Brian Fallon (press secretary)|Brian Fallon]] issued a statement saying: \"The report shows that problems with the State Department's electronic record-keeping systems were long-standing\" and that Clinton \"took steps that went much further than others to appropriately preserve and release her records.\"<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\" /> However, the Associated Press said, \"The audit did note that former Secretary of State Colin Powell had also exclusively used a private email account. ... But the failings of Clinton were singled out in the audit as being more serious than her predecessor.\"<ref name=\"APMay26Report\">{{cite web|authors=Michael Biesecker & Bradley Klapper|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/e9cf125b8af1417a8cdd0b3526a1ce9e/apnewsbreak-state-dept-audit-faults-clinton-emails|title=Clinton email use broke federal rules: inspector's report|agency=Associated Press|date=May 26, 2016}}</ref> The report stated that \"By Secretary Clinton's tenure, the department's guidance was considerably more detailed and more sophisticated, Secretary Clinton's cybersecurity practices accordingly must be evaluated in light of these more comprehensive directives.\"<ref name=\"APMay26Report\" />\n\n== Server security and hacking attempts ==\n\n===Encryption and security===\nIn 2008, before Hillary Clinton became Secretary of State, [[Justin Cooper (aide)|Justin Cooper]], a longtime aide to Clinton's husband, former President [[Bill Clinton]], managed the system. Cooper had no security clearance or expertise in computer security.<ref name=WP0804>Carol D. Leonnig, Rosalind S. Helderman & Tom Hamburger, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/fbi-looks-into-security-of-clintons-private-e-mail-setup/2015/08/04/2bdd85ec-3aae-11e5-8e98-115a3cf7d7ae_story.html FBI Looking into the Security of Hillary Clinton's Private e-mail Setup], ''The Washington Post'', August 4, 2015.</ref> Later, Bryan Pagliano, the former IT director for Clinton's 2008 presidential campaign, was hired to maintain their private email server while Clinton was Secretary of State.<ref name=WP0901>Helderman, Rosalind S. & Carol D. Leonnig, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/clintons-personally-paid-state-department-staffer-to-maintain-server/2015/09/04/b13ab23e-530c-11e5-9812-92d5948a40f8_story.html \"Clintons personally paid State Department staffer to maintain server\"], ''The Washington Post'', September 5, 2015.</ref><ref name=Joseph0901>Joseph, Cameron.[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/hillary-clinton-won-apologize-private-email-server-article-1.2348855 Hillary Clinton 'takes responsibility' for email controversy, but won't apologize for using private server], ''Daily News'' (New York), September 5, 2015.</ref> Pagliano had invoked the [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] during congressional questioning about Clinton's server. In early 2016, he was granted immunity by the Department of Justice in exchange for cooperation with prosecutors.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perez|first1=Evan|title=DOJ grants immunity to ex-Clinton staffer who set up email server|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/02/politics/hillary-clinton-email-server-justice-department/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 2, 2016|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref> A Clinton spokesman said her campaign was \"pleased\" Pagliano was now cooperating with prosecutors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-clinton-email-investigation-justice-department-grants-immunity-to-former-state-department-staffer/2016/03/02/e421e39e-e0a0-11e5-9c36-e1902f6b6571_story.html|title=Justice Dept. grants immunity to staffer who set up Clinton email server|last=Goldman|first=Adam|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 2, 2016|accessdate=March 3, 2016}}</ref> As of May 2016, the State Department remained unable to locate most of Pagliano's work-related emails from the period when he was employed by that department under Secretary Clinton.<ref>Fishel, Justin.  [http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/emails-found-hillary-clintons-senior-staffer-state-department/story?id=38989504 \"Emails From Hillary Clinton\u2019s IT Director at State Department Appear to Be Missing\"], ''[[ABC News]]'', May 9, 2016.</ref>\n\nSecurity experts such as [[Chris Soghoian]] believe that emails to and from Clinton may have been at risk of [[Hacker (computer security)|hacking]] and [[Computer and network surveillance|foreign surveillance]].<ref name=\"Greenberg\"/> [[Marc Maiffret]], a cybersecurity expert, said that the server had \"amateur hour\" vulnerabilities.<ref name=AP1013/> For the first two months after Clinton was appointed Secretary of State and began accessing mail on the server through her BlackBerry, transmissions to and from the server were apparently not encrypted. On March 29, 2009, a [[Public key certificate|digital certificate]] was obtained which would have permitted encryption.<ref name=\"WP032716\"/>\n\nFormer [[Director of the Defense Intelligence Agency]] [[Michael T. Flynn]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://video.foxnews.com/v/4157397774001/michael-flynn-weighs-in-on-hillary-clinton-email-controversy/?#sp=show-clips/primetime|title=Michael Flynn weighs in on Hillary Clinton email controversy|publisher=Fox News Channel|date=April 6, 2015}}</ref> former [[United States Secretary of Defense]] [[Robert Gates]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/266674-former-defense-secretary-says-clinton-server-may-have-been-compromised|title=Ex-Pentagon chief: Iran, China or Russia may have gotten to Clinton server|work=TheHill}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/600728/did-russia-read-hillary-clintons-emails-robert-gates-says-odds-are-pretty-high|title=Did Russia read Hillary Clinton's emails? Robert Gates says the odds are 'pretty high'|publisher=theweek.com}}</ref> and former deputy director of the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] [[Michael Morell]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/05/michael-morrell-foreign-governments-have-hillarys-email-118007|title=Hillary Clinton emails: Former CIA head says foreign governments have access|newspaper=Politico}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/politics-ideas/hillary-clinton-email-scandal-victim|title=Hillary's Tell-Tale Server|author=Noah Rothman|magazine=Commentary Magazine}}</ref> have said that it is likely that foreign governments were able to access the information on Clinton's server. [[Michael Hayden (general)|Michael Hayden]], former [[Director of the National Security Agency]], Principal Deputy [[Director of National Intelligence]], and [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]] said \"I would lose all respect for a whole bunch of foreign intelligence agencies if they weren't sitting back, paging through the emails.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2016/02/21/ex-nsa-chief-backs-apple-iphone-back-doors/80660024/|title=Ex-NSA chief backs Apple on iPhone 'back doors'|date=February 21, 2016|newspaper=USA Today}}</ref>\n\n===Hacking attempts===\nClinton's server was configured to allow users to connect openly from the Internet and control it remotely using Microsoft's [[Remote Desktop Services]].<ref name=AP1013>{{cite news|author1=Jack Gillum  |author2=Stephen Braun|title=Exclusive: Clinton server's software had hacking risk|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/467ff78858bf4dde8db21677deeff101/only-ap-clinton-server-ran-software-risked-hacking|accessdate=October 13, 2015|agency=Associated Press|date=October 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt is known that hackers were aware of Clinton's non-public email address as early as 2011.<ref>[http://www.cbsnews.com/news/russian-hackers-tried-to-infiltrate-hillary-clintons-emails/ \"Hackers linked to Russia tried to infiltrate Hillary Clinton's emails\"], [[CBS News]] (September 30, 2015): \"these messages show hackers had Clinton's email address, which was not public. ... \"</ref> Secretary Clinton and her staff were aware of hacking attempts in 2011, and were reportedly worried about them.<ref>Gerstein, Josh.  [http://www.politico.com/story/2016/05/clinton-email-problems-223573 \"Why Clinton\u2019s email problems are here to stay\"], ''[[Politico]]'', May 25, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, according to server records, a hacker in [[Serbia]] scanned Clinton's Chappaqua server at least twice, in August and in December 2012. It was unclear whether the hacker knew the server belonged to Clinton, although it did identify itself as providing email services for clintonemail.com.<ref name=AP1013/> During 2014, Clinton's server was the target of repeated intrusions originating in Germany, China, and South Korea. Threat monitoring software on the server blocked at least five such attempts. The software was installed in October 2013, and for three months prior to that, no such software had been installed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2015/10/08/clinton-server-hack-attempts-came-from-china-korea-germany/ADRRitdZev3O1FhIFQT1SP/story.html|title=Sources of attempts to hack Clinton's e-mail server ID'd|accessdate=February 21, 2016|author1=Ken Dilanian  |author2=Jack Gillum}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5ad0f6bb57eb487f84e98fe9a74a08b1/clinton-subject-hack-attempts-china-korea-germany|title=Clinton subject to hack attempts from China, Korea, Germany|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Pagliano, security logs of Clinton's email server showed no evidence of successful hacking.<ref name=\"nyt-apuzzo\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/04/us/politics/security-logs-of-hillary-clintons-email-server-are-said-to-show-no-evidence-of-hacking.html | title=Security Logs of Hillary Clinton's Email Server Are Said to Show No Evidence of Hacking | last=Apuzzo|first=Matt|newspaper=The New York Times| date=March 3, 2016 | accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> The ''New York Times'' reported that \"forensic experts can sometimes spot sophisticated hacking that is not apparent in the logs, but computer security experts view logs as key documents when detecting hackers,\" adding the logs \"bolster Mrs. Clinton's assertion that her use of a personal email account ... did not put American secrets into the hands of hackers or foreign governments.\"<ref name=\"Greenberg\">Andy Greenberg, [https://www.wired.com/2015/03/clintons-email-server-vulnerable Why Clinton's Private Email Server Was Such a Security Failure], ''Wired'', March 4, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"nyt-apuzzo\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/live-from-boulder/2015/10/2016-presidential-debate-hillary-clinton-emails-215291|title=Debate fact check: No evidence Clinton's server was hacked|last=Marks|first=Joseph|newspaper='[[Politico]]|date=October 28, 2015|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Romanian people|Romanian]] hacker Marcel Lehel Laz\u0103r (aka \"[[Guccifer]]\") distributed private memos from [[Sidney Blumenthal]] to Clinton on [[Libyan Civil War (2011)|events in Libya]] that he had acquired by hacking Blumenthal's email account.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/buster/sidney-blumenthal/hacker-distributes-memos-784091|title=Hacker Begins Distributing Confidential Memos Sent To Hillary Clinton On Libya, Benghazi Attack|date=March 18, 2013|website=The Smoking Gun|accessdate=March 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/private-emails-reveal-ex-clinton-aides-secret-spy-network|title=Private Emails Reveal Ex-Clinton Aide's Secret Spy Network|date=March 27, 2015|publisher=ProPublica|accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref> In 2016, Laz\u0103r was extradited from Romania to the U.S. to face unrelated federal charges related to his hacking into the accounts of a number of high-profile U.S. figures,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-guccifer-idUSKCN0WY5MK|title=Hacker 'Guccifer' extradited from Romania, appears in U.S. court|date=April 1, 2016|accessdate=June 11, 2016|agency=Reuters}}</ref> pleading guilty to these charges.<ref>Catherine Herridge & Pamela K. Browne. [http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/05/25/hacker-who-claims-breached-clinton-server-pleads-guilty-strikes-deal-with-feds.html Hacker who claims he breached Clinton server pleads guilty, strikes deal with feds], Fox News (May 25, 2016).</ref><ref>Hosenball, Mark. [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-clinton-emails-hacker-idUSKCN0YF2KZ \"Hacker who exposed Hillary Clinton's email server expected to plead guilty\"], Reuters.com, May 24, 2016.</ref> While detained pending trial, Laz\u0103r claimed to the media that he had successfully hacked Clinton's server, but provided no proof of this claim.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/05/04/us/politics/ap-us-clinton-email.html|title=US Judge: Clinton May Be Ordered to Testify in Records Case|date=May 4, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Officials associated with the investigation told the media that they found no evidence supporting Laz\u0103r's assertion,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/federal-prosecutors-in-virginia-assisting-in-clinton-email-probe/2016/05/05/f0277faa-12f0-11e6-81b4-581a5c4c42df_story.html|title=Officials: Scant evidence that Clinton had malicious intent in handling of emails|date=May 5, 2016|accessdate=May 6, 2016|work=The Washington Post|last=Zapotosky|first=Matt}}</ref> and Clinton press secretary [[Brian Fallon (press secretary)|Brian Fallon]] said \"There is absolutely no basis to believe the claims made by this criminal from his prison cell.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/hacker-guccifer-i-got-inside-hillary-clinton-s-server-n568206|title=Hacker 'Guccifer': I Got Inside Hillary Clinton's Server|author=Cynthia McFadden|publisher=NBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/05/04/romanian-hacker-guccifer-breached-clinton-server-it-was-easy.html?intcmp=hpbt1|title=Romanian hacker Guccifer: I breached Clinton server, 'it was easy'|author=Catherine Herridge, Pamela K. Browne|publisher=Fox News Channel}}</ref> FBI Director James Comey later stated in a congressional hearing that Guccifer admitted his claim was a lie.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-director-set-to-appear-before-congressional-committee-to-answer-questions-on-clinton-investigation/2016/07/07/eb43ec7e-43c1-11e6-88d0-6adee48be8bc_story.html?tid=sm_fb|last=Zapotosky|first=Matt|title=House Republicans grill FBI director Comey on Clinton emails|work=The Washington Post|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to security researchers at [[Secureworks]] the email leak was caused by Threat Group-4127, later attributed to [[Fancy Bear]], a unit that targets governments, military, and international non-governmental organizations. The researchers report moderate confidence that the unit gathers intelligence on behalf of the Russian government.<ref name=\"secureworks.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.secureworks.com/research/threat-group-4127-targets-hillary-clinton-presidential-campaign|title=Hillary Clinton Email Targeted by Threat Group-4127|publisher=secureworks.com|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720175418/https://www.secureworks.com/research/threat-group-4127-targets-hillary-clinton-presidential-campaign#|archive-date=July 20, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Deletion of emails==\n\nIn 2014, months prior to public knowledge of the server's existence, Clinton chief of staff [[Cheryl Mills]] and two attorneys worked to identify work-related emails on the server to be archived and preserved for the State Department. Upon completion of this task in December 2014, Mills instructed Clinton's computer services provider, Platte River Networks (PRN), to change the server's [[retention period]] to 60 days, allowing 31,830 older personal emails to be automatically deleted from the server, as Clinton had decided she no longer needed them. However, the PRN technician assigned for this task failed to carry it out at that time.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2016/09/the-fbi-files-on-clintons-emails/|title=The FBI Files on Clinton's Emails - FactCheck.org|date=September 7, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the existence of the server became publicly known on March 2, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/03/us/politics/hillary-clintons-use-of-private-email-at-state-department-raises-flags.html|title=Hillary Clinton Used Personal Email Account at State Dept., Possibly Breaking Rules|publisher=|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> the [[Select Committee on Benghazi]] issued a subpoena for Benghazi-related emails two days later. Mills sent an email to PRN on March 9 mentioning the Committee's retention request.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\"/> The PRN technician then had what he described to the FBI as an \"oh shit moment,\" realizing he had not set the personal emails to be deleted as instructed months earlier. The technician then erased the emails using a free utility, [[BleachBit]], sometime between March 25 and 31.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/03/us/politics/hillary-clinton-fbi.html|title=F.B.I. Papers Offer Closer Look at Hillary Clinton Email Inquiry|publisher=|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> ''Bloomberg News'' reported in September 2015 that the FBI had recovered some of the deleted emails.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2015/09/23/442797133/fbi-investigators-recover-clinton-emails-thought-to-have-been-deleted|title=FBI Investigators Recover Clinton Emails Thought To Have Been Lost|website=NPR.org}}</ref>\n\nSince this episode, Clinton critics have accused her or her aides of deleting emails that were under subpoena, alleging the server had been \"bleached\" or \"acid-washed\" by a \"very expensive\" process<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2016/09/trump-pence-acid-wash-facts/|title=Trump, Pence 'Acid Wash' Facts - FactCheck.org|date=September 8, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> in an effort to destroy evidence, with candidate Donald Trump stating the day before the 2016 election that \"Hillary Clinton erased more than 30,000 emails as part of a cover-up.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factba.se/search#30,000+emails|title=Donald Trump Complete - Search Tweets, Speeches, Policies - Factbase|last=Factbase|website=Factbase|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> Trump reiterated his position as late as August 2018, asking \"Look at the crimes that Clinton did with the emails and she deletes 33,000 emails after she gets a subpoena from Congress, and this Justice Department does nothing about it?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factba.se/search#emails|title=Donald Trump Complete - Search Tweets, Speeches, Policies - Factbase|last=Factbase|website=Factbase|accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Classified information in emails==\nIn various interviews, Clinton has said that \"I did not send classified material, and I did not receive any material that was marked or designated classified.\"<ref name=Allen0821 /> However, in June and July 2016, a number of news outlets reported that Clinton's emails did include messages with some paragraphs marked with a \"(c)\" for \"Confidential.\"<ref name=\"BBC20160705\">{{cite news|author=Staff|title=FBI recommends no charges against Hillary Clinton over emails|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-36711711|work=[[BBC News]]|date=July 5, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016|quote=But investigators found that a number of messages that were marked classified at the time were sent from her account.}}</ref><ref name=\"FoxNews2016-06-11\">{{cite news|last1=Herridge|first1=Catherine|last2=Browne|first2=Pamela K.|date=June 11, 2016|title=Despite Clinton claims, 2012 email had classified marking|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/06/11/despite-clinton-claims-2012-email-had-classified-marking.html|publisher=[[Fox News Channel]]|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\nThe FBI investigation found that 110 messages contained information that was classified at the time it was sent. Sixty-five of those emails were found to contain information classified as \"Secret;\" more than 20 contained \"Top-Secret\" information.<ref name=\"PolitiFact2016-07-06\">{{cite news|last=Carroll|first=Lauren|date=July 5, 2016|title=FBI investigation undermines Clinton email defense|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2016/jul/05/fbi-investigation-undermines-clinton-email-defense|newspaper=[[PolitiFact]]|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Wapo-2016-07-05\">{{cite news|last=Cillizza|first=Chris|date=July 5, 2016|title=Hillary Clinton's email problems might be even worse than we thought|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/07/05/hillary-clintons-email-problems-might-be-even-worse-than-we-thought|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref> Three emails, out of 30,000, were found to be marked as classified, although they lacked classified headers and were only marked with a small \"c\" in parentheses, described as \"portion markings\" by Comey. He added it was possible Clinton was not \"technically sophisticated\" enough to understand what the three classified markings meant<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-james-comey-hillary-clinton-email-probe/story?id=41044927|title=What FBI Director James Comey Really Said About Hillary Clinton Email Probe|publisher=ABC News|date=August 2, 2016|accessdate=September 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.cnbc.com/gallery/?video=3000548237|title=Clinton not technically sophisticated: FBI interview|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=September 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Kiely\">{{cite web|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2016/07/revisiting-clinton-and-classified-information|title=Revisiting Clinton and Classified Information|last=Kiely|first=Eugene|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016|publisher=Factcheck.org}}</ref> which is consistent with Clinton's claim that she wasn't aware of the meaning of such markings.<ref name=\"BusinessInsider20160902\">{{cite web|author=Pamela Engel|title=Hillary Clinton said she didn't know what the 'C' markings in emails stood for|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/hillary-clinton-fbi-report-classified-markings-2016-9|website=[[Business Insider]]|date=September 2, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2018|quote=Hillary Clinton told investigators that she wasn't aware that a \"C\" marking in emails she received on her private server indicated that the information was classified }}</ref>\n\nClinton personally wrote 104 of the 2,093 emails that were retroactively<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/clinton-on-her-private-server-wrote-104-emails-the-government-says-are-classified/2016/03/05/11e2ee06-dbd6-11e5-81ae-7491b9b9e7df_story.html|title=Clinton, on her private server, wrote 104 emails the government says are classified|first1=Rosalind S.|last1=Helderman|first2=Tom|last2=Hamburger|date=March 5, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=April 21, 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/jul/06/hillary-clinton/fbi-findings-tear-holes-hillary-clintons-email-def/|title=FBI tears holes in Hillary Clinton's email defense|publisher=|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2016/jul/19/politifact-sheet-hillary-clintons-email-controvers/|title=The GOP's opening over Hillary Clinton's email|publisher=|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> found to contain information classified as \"confidential.\"<ref name=\"IGReportPractices\">Helderman, Rosalind and Hamburger, Tom. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/state-dept-inspector-general-report-sharply-criticizes-clintons-email-practices/2016/05/25/fc6f8ebc-2275-11e6-aa84-42391ba52c91_story.html State Dept. inspector general report sharply criticizes Clinton's email practices], ''The Washington Post'', May 25, 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/clinton-on-her-private-server-wrote-104-emails-the-government-says-are-classified/2016/03/05/11e2ee06-dbd6-11e5-81ae-7491b9b9e7df_story.html|title=Clinton, on her private server, wrote 104 emails the government says are classified|author=Rosalind S. Helderman|date=March 5, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> Of the remaining emails that were classified after they were sent, Clinton aide [[Jake Sullivan]] wrote the most, at 215.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nAccording to the State Department, there were 2,093 email chains on the server that were retroactively marked as classified by the State Department as \"Confidential,\" 65 as \"Secret,\" and 22 as \"Top Secret.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/01/us/politics/last-batch-of-hillary-clintons-emails-is-released.html|title=Last Batch of Hillary Clinton's Emails Is Released|date=March 1, 2016|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2016-02-29/state-dept-wins-dispute-over-clinton-email-on-north-korea|title=State Dept completes Clinton email release, more than 52k out including 2,100 with info now deemed classified|last=Klapper|first=Bradley|date=February 29, 2016|newspaper=U.S. News and World Report|accessdate=March 1, 2016|last2=Lee|first2=Matthew}}</ref>\n\nAn interagency dispute arose during the investigation about what constitutes \u201cclassified\u201d status when information acquired and considered \u201cowned\u201d by intelligence agencies is also independently and publicly available through \u201cparallel reporting\u201d by the press or others. In one reported instance, an email chain deemed by the intelligence community to contain classified information included a discussion of a ''New York Times'' article that reported on a CIA drone strike in Pakistan; despite wide public knowledge of the drone program, the CIA \u2014 as the \"owning agency\" \u2014 considers the very existence of its drone program to be classified in its entirety. [[Assistant Secretary of State for Legislative Affairs]] [[Julia Frifield]] noted, \"When policy officials obtain information from open sources, \u2018think tanks,\u2019 experts, foreign government officials, or others, the fact that some of the information may also have been available through intelligence channels does not mean that the information is necessarily classified.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/06/us/politics/agencies-battle-over-what-is-top-secret-in-hillary-clintons-emails.html|title=Agencies Battle Over What Is 'Top Secret' in Hillary Clinton's Emails|first1=Steven Lee|last1=Myers|first2=Mark|last2=Mazzetti|date=February 5, 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/secrecy-defines-obamas-drone-war/2011/10/28/gIQAPKNR5O_story.html|title=Secrecy defines Obama's drone war|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n===State Department inspector general reports and statements===\nA June 29, 2015, memorandum from the Inspector General of the State Department, Steve A. Linick, said that a review of the 55,000-page email release found \"hundreds of potentially classified emails.\"<ref name=CNN3>Labott, Elise.[http://www.cnn.com/2015/07/24/politics/hillary-clinton-email-justice-department \"Clinton emails Included Classified Information\"], CNN, July 24, 2015.</ref> A July 17, 2015, follow-up memo, sent jointly by Linick and the [[United States Intelligence Community|Intelligence Community]] (IC) inspector general, I. Charles McCullough III, to [[Under Secretary of State for Management]] [[Patrick F. Kennedy]], stated that they had confirmed that several of the emails contained classified information that was not marked as classified, at least one of which was publicly released.<ref name=CNN3/>\n\nOn July 24, 2015, Linick and McCullough said they had discovered classified information on Clinton's email account,<ref name=NYT72415>{{cite news|author1=Michael S. Schmidt  |author2=Matt Apuzzo|title=Hillary Clinton Emails Said to Contain Classified Data|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/25/us/politics/hillary-clinton-email-classified-information-inspector-general-intelligence-community.html|accessdate=July 25, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=July 24, 2015}}</ref> but did not say whether Clinton sent or received the emails.<ref name=NYT72415/> Investigators from their office, searching a randomly chosen sample of 40 emails, found four that contained classified information that originated from U.S. intelligence agencies, including the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and the National Security Agency (NSA).<ref name=NYT72415/> Their statement said that the information they found was classified when sent, remained so as of their inspection, and \"never should have been transmitted via an unclassified personal system.\"<ref name=NYT72415/>\n\nIn a separate statement in the form of a letter to Congress, McCullough said that he had made a request to the State Department for access to the entire set of emails turned over by Clinton, but that the Department rejected his request.<ref name=NYT72415/><ref name=WSJ3>Byron Tau, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/investigation-sought-into-hillary-clintons-emails-1437714369 Hillary Clinton Sent Classified Information Over Email While at State Department], ''The Wall Street Journal'', July 24, 2015.</ref> The letter stated that none of the emails were marked as classified, but because they included classified information they should have been marked and handled as such, and transmitted securely.<ref name=WSJ3/>\n\nOn August 10, 2015, the IC inspector general said that two of the 40 emails in the sample were \"Top Secret/[[Sensitive Compartmented Information]]\" and subsequently given classified labels of \"TK\" (for \"Talent Keyhole,\" indicating material obtained by aerial or space-based imagery sources and [[NOFORN]]).<ref name=AP81415 /> One is a discussion of a news article about a [[Drone strikes in Pakistan|U.S. drone strike operation]].<ref name=AP81415/> The second, he said, either referred to classified material or else was \"parallel reporting\" of [[open-source intelligence]], which might still be classified by the government \"owning agency\" that sourced the information by secret means even though the same information was also available in the public domain.<ref name=AP81415/><ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|title=US State Department 'Top secret' emails on Clinton server discussed drone program, reference classified info.|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2015/08/14/top-secret-emails-on-clinton-server-discussed-drone-program-may-reference/?intcmp=ob_article_footer_text&intcmp=obinsite|accessdate=August 24, 2015|publisher=Fox News Channel|date=August 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/06/us/politics/agencies-battle-over-what-is-top-secret-in-hillary-clintons-emails.html|title=Agencies Battle Over What Is 'Top Secret' in Hillary Clinton's Emails|date=February 5, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=April 21, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Clinton's presidential campaign and the State Department disputed the letter, and questioned whether the emails had been over-classified by an arbitrary process. According to an unnamed source, a secondary review by the CIA and the [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]] endorsed the earlier inspectors general findings concluding that the emails (one of which concerned North Korea's nuclear weapons program) were \"Top Secret\" when received by Clinton through her private server in 2009 and 2011, a conclusion also disputed by the Clinton campaign.<ref>Schmidt, Michael S. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/08/us/politics/second-review-says-classified-information-was-in-hillary-clintons-email.html \"Second Review Says Classified Information Was in Hillary Clinton's Email\"] ''The New York Times'', September 7, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe IC inspector general issued another letter to Congress on January 14, 2016. In this letter he stated that an unnamed intelligence agency had made a sworn declaration that \"several dozen emails [had been] determined by the IC element to be at the CONFIDENTIAL, SECRET, and TOP SECRET/[[Special access program|SAP]] levels.\" Other intelligence officials added that the several dozen were not the two emails from the previous sample and that the clearance of the IC inspector general himself had to be upgraded before he could learn about the programs referenced by the emails.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Hillary Clinton Email Said to Include Material Exceeding 'Top Secret'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/20/us/politics/hillary-clinton-email-said-to-include-material-exceeding-top-secret.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=January 19, 2016|accessdate=January 20, 2016|issn=0362-4331|first=Mark|last=Mazzetti}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hillary Clinton Emails Held Info Beyond Top Secret: IG|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/hillary-clinton-emails-contained-info-above-top-secret-ig-n499886|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=January 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Intelligence community watchdog reconfirms that dozens of Clinton emails were classified|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/01/19/intelligence-community-watchdog-reconfirms-that-dozens-of-clinton-emails-were-classified|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=January 19, 2016|accessdate=January 20, 2016|issn=0190-8286|first=Rosalind S.|last=Helderman|first2=Tom|last2=Hamburger}}</ref> NBC News reported on January 20, 2016 that senior American officials described these emails as \"innocuous\" because\u2014although they discussed the CIA drone program that is technically classified TOP SECRET/[[Special access program|SAP]]\u2014the existence of the CIA drone program had been widely known and discussed in the public domain for years. These officials characterized the IC inspector general as unfair in how he had handled the issue.<ref name=\"nbcnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/officials-new-top-secret-clinton-emails-innocuous-n500586|title=Officials: New Top Secret Clinton Emails 'Innocuous'|publisher=|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, 2016, the State Department announced that 22 documents from Clinton's email server would not be released because they contained highly classified information that was too sensitive for public consumption. At the same time, the State Department announced that it was initiating its own investigation into whether the server contained information that was classified at the time it was sent or received.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Byron Tau|title=State Department: 22 of Hillary Clinton's Emails Considered Too Classified to Release|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-says-22-of-clintons-emails-contain-highly-classified-information-1454101286|accessdate=February 1, 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=January 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, State Department IG Linick addressed another report to Under Secretary of State Kennedy, stating his office had also found classified material in 10 emails in the personal email accounts of members of former Secretary [[Condoleezza Rice]]'s staff and in two emails in the personal email account of former Secretary of State [[Colin Powell]].<ref name=\"PowellRice\">{{cite news|authors=Jose Pagliery, Deirdre Walsh and Elise Labott|title=State Department: Colin Powell, Condoleezza Rice staffers received classified info via personal email|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/04/politics/hillary-clinton-email-classified-colin-powell-condoleezza-rice/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://i2.cdn.turner.com/cnn/2016/images/02/04/memo.pdf|title=Memorandum for Under Secretary Kennedy|date=February 3, 2016|last=Linick|first=Steve}}</ref> None of the emails were classified for intelligence reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/secretaries-handled-classified-material-private-email-state-dept/story?id=37404084|title=Other Secretaries Handled Classified Material on Private Email, State Dept. Concludes|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> PolitiFact found a year earlier that Powell was the only former secretary of state to use a personal email account.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fact-checking Chuck Schumer's defense of Hillary Clinton's private email|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2015/mar/08/charles-schumer/fact-checking-chuck-schumers-defense-hillary-clint|website=PolitiFact|accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref> In February 2016, Clinton's campaign chairman issued a statement claiming that her emails, like her predecessors,' were \"being inappropriately subjected to over-classification.\"<ref name=\"PowellRice\"/>\n\n===FBI investigation===\n====July 2015 \u2013 Security referral====\nThe State Department and [[United States Intelligence Community|Intelligence Community]] (IC) inspector generals' discovery of four emails containing classified information, out of a random sample of 40, prompted them to make a security referral to the FBI's counterintelligence office, to alert authorities that classified information was being kept on Clinton's server and by her lawyer on a [[USB flash drive|thumb drive]].<ref name=NYT72415 /><ref name=WSJ3/> As part of the FBI's '''Midyear investigation''',<ref name=OIGjune2018>{{cite web |title=A Review of Various Actions by the Federal Bureau of Investigation and Department of Justice in Advance of the 2016 Election |url=https://www.justice.gov/file/1071991/download |publisher=[[Office of the Inspector General]] |accessdate=May 19, 2019 |pages=328,330,397}}</ref> at the request of the IC [[inspector general]], Clinton agreed to turn over her email server to the [[U.S. Department of Justice]], as well as thumb drives containing copies of her work-related emails. Other emails were obtained by the [[United States House Select Committee on Benghazi]] from other sources, in connection with the committee's inquiry. Clinton's own emails are being made public in stages by the State Department on a gradual schedule.<ref>{{cite web|title=House GOP split over Clinton email probe|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/11/hillary-clinton-emails-republicans-server-congress-215498|publisher=Politico|accessdate=November 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/06/tracking-the-clinton-controversies-from-whitewater-to-benghazi/396182|title=From Whitewater to Benghazi: A Clinton-Scandal Primer|work=David A. Graham|date=June 10, 2016|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/personalities/hillary-clinton|title=Hillary Clinton's file|publisher=Politifact.com|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' ran a front-page story on July 24, 2015 with the headline \"Criminal Inquiry Sought In Clinton's Use of Email,\" with the lead sentence stating, \"Two inspectors general have asked the Justice Department to open a criminal investigation into whether Hillary Rodham Clinton mishandled sensitive government information on a private email account she used as secretary of state, senior government officials said Thursday.\"<ref name=\"mediamatters.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2015/07/25/ny-times-issues-second-major-correction-to-botc/204596|title=NY Times Issues Second Major Correction To Botched Report On Clinton's Emails|date=July 25, 2015|publisher=|accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref> Shortly after the publication of the story, the Inspectors General of the Intelligence Community and the\nDepartment of State issued a statement clarifying, \"An important distinction is that the IC IG did not make a [[criminal referral]] - it was a security referral made for counterintelligence purposes.\"<ref>https://www.stateoig.gov/system/files/statement_of_the_icig_and_oig_regarding_review_of_clintons_emails_july_24_2015_0.pdf</ref> The ''Times'' later made two corrections, first that Clinton was not a specific target of the referral, then later that the referral was not \"criminal\" in nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/24/us/politics/inquiry-is-sought-in-hillary-clinton-email-account.html|title=Inquiry Sought in Hillary Clinton's Use of Email|publisher=|accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/research/2015/07/24/ny-times-walks-back-flimsy-report-on-probe-into/204576|title=NY Times Walks Back Flimsy Report On Probe Into Clinton's Email|date=July 24, 2015|publisher=|accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"mediamatters.org\"/>\n\nClinton's IT contractors turned over her personal email server to the FBI on August 12, 2015,<ref name=\"server\"/> as well as thumb drives containing copies of her emails.<ref name=ABC0812>Justin Fishel & Mike Levine, [http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/hillary-clinton-emails-questions-answered/story?id=33037501 Hillary Clinton Emails: Your Questions Answered], ABC News, August 12, 2015.</ref><ref>Anita Kumar, Marisa Taylor & Greg Gordon, [http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article30714762.html \"Top Secret' emails Found as Clinton Probe Expands to Key Aides], McClatchy Washington Bureau, August 11, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn a letter describing the matter to Senator [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]], Chairman of the Senate Homeland Security Committee, Clinton's lawyer [[David E. Kendall]] said that emails, and all other data stored on the server, had earlier been erased prior to the device being turned over to the authorities, and that both he and another lawyer had been given security clearances by the State Department to handle thumb drives containing about 30,000 emails that Clinton subsequently also turned over to authorities. Kendall said the thumb drives had been stored in a safe provided to him in July by the State Department.<ref name=AP0819>{{cite news|last1=Sacks|first1=Mike|title=Clinton Lawyer Informs Congress About Security Clearance, Email Safeguards|url=http://www.nationallawjournal.com/id=1202735059877/Clinton-Lawyer-Informs-Congress-About-Security-Clearance-Email-Safeguards|accessdate=September 19, 2015|work=National Law Journal|date=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====August 2015 \u2013 Investigation continues; email recovery====\nOn August 20, 2015, U.S. District Judge [[Emmet G. Sullivan]] stated that Hillary Clinton's actions of maintaining a private email server were in direct conflict with U.S. government policy. \"We wouldn't be here today if this employee had followed government policy,\" he said, and ordered the State Department to work with the FBI to determine if any emails on the server during her tenure as Secretary of State could be recovered.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jason Donner|title=Judge orders State Dept. to work on recovering emails, suggests Clinton violated policy|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2015/08/20/judge-orders-state-to-work-with-fbi-on-clinton-email-investigation/?intcmp=ob_article_footer_text&intcmp=obnetwork|accessdate=August 27, 2015|publisher=Fox News Channel|date=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Schmidt>{{cite news|last1=Schmidt|first1=Michael|title=Judge Says Hillary Clinton Didn't Follow Government Email Policies|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/21/us/judge-says-hillary-clinton-didnt-follow-government-email-policies.html|accessdate=August 27, 2015|publisher=NYT|date=August 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Gerstein>{{cite news|last1=Gerstein|first1=Josh|title=Judge says Hillary Clinton's private emails violated policy|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/08/judge-says-hillary-clintons-private-emails-violated-policy-121568.html|accessdate=August 28, 2015|publisher=Politico|date=August 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPlatte River Networks, the Denver-based firm that managed the Clinton server since 2013, said it had no knowledge of the server being wiped. \"Platte River has no knowledge of the server being wiped,\" company spokesman Andy Boian told the ''[[Washington Post]]''. \"All the information we have is that the server wasn't wiped.\"<ref name=WP0912>{{cite news|last1=Helderman|first1=Rosalind S.|last2=Hamburger|first2=Tom|last3=Leonnig|first3=Carol D.|title=Tech company: No indication that Clinton's e-mail server was 'wiped'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/tech-company-no-indication-that-clintons-e-mail-server-was-wiped/2015/09/12/10c8ce52-58c6-11e5-abe9-27d53f250b11_story.html|accessdate=September 13, 2015|work=Washington Post|date=September 12, 2015}}</ref> When asked by the ''Washington Post'', the Clinton campaign declined to comment.<ref name=WP0912/>\n\nIn September 2015, FBI investigators were engaged in sorting messages recovered from the server.<ref name=\"wilbur\">{{cite news|author1=Del Quentin Wilber|title=FBI Said to Recover Personal E-Mails From Hillary Clinton Server|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-09-22/fbi-said-to-recover-personal-e-mails-from-hillary-clinton-server|accessdate=September 23, 2015|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|date=September 22, 2015}}</ref> In November 2015, the FBI expanded its inquiry to examine whether Clinton or her aides jeopardized national security secrets, and if so, who should be held responsible.<ref name=Bade1110>Rachael Bade, [http://www.politico.com/story/2015/11/hillary-clinton-email-fbi-probe-215630 \"FBI steps up interviews in Clinton email probe; Questions focus on whether State officials improperly sent classified material\"], Politico.com, November 10, 2015. Retrieved November 14, 2016.</ref><ref name=HNGN1110>Taylor Tyler, [http://www.hngn.com/articles/148950/20151110/clinton-emails-fbi-expands-investigation-email-setup.htm \"Clinton Emails: FBI Expands Investigation Into Clinton Email Setup\"], ''Headlines & Global News'', November 10, 2015. Retrieved November 14, 2016.</ref>\n\n<!-- inclusion and lang per current consensus on Talk -->Conflicting media sources sized the FBI investigation from 12<ref name=\"msnbc-ari\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/fed-source-about-12-fbi-agents-working-clinton-email-inquiry-n548026|publisher=MSNBC|last=Melber|first=Ari|date=March 30, 2016|accessdate=April 29, 2016|title=Fed Source: About 12 FBI Agents Working on Clinton Email Inquiry}}</ref> to 30 agents<ref name=\"time\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4276988/jim-comey-hillary-clinton|work=Time|last=Calabresi|first=Massimo|date=March 31, 2016|accessdate=April 29, 2016|title=Inside the FBI Investigation of Hillary Clinton's E-Mail}}</ref> as of March 2016.<!-- end of current consensus lage per Talk -->\n\n====May\u2013July 2016 \u2013 Public statements====\nIn May 2016, FBI Director [[James Comey]] said he was \"not familiar with the term 'security inquiry'\" as the Clinton campaign was characterizing the probe, adding that the word ''investigation'' is \"in our name\" and \"We're conducting an investigation ... That's what we do. That's probably all I can say about it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/05/hillary-clinton-email-investigation-fbi-james-comey-223071|title=FBI's James Comey: I feel 'pressure' to quickly finish Clinton email probe|publisher=politico.com|date=May 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"fbi.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/pressrel/press-releases/director-comey-remarks-during-may-11-2018pen-and-pad2019-briefing-with-reporters|title=Director Comey Remarks During May 11 'Pen and Pad' Briefing with Reporters|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> Comey noted in his 2018 memoir that he did not publicly contradict Clinton's characterization of the investigation as a \"security inquiry\" while it was underway<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/13/us/politics/comey-book-clinton-emails.html|title=As Clinton Camp Denied Reports of Criminal Inquiry, F.B.I. Was Investigating, Comey Says|publisher=|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> despite being directly prompted by a reporter to do so in May 2016.<ref name=\"fbi.gov\"/> In April 2017 it became known that the FBI had, in fact, opened a criminal investigation on July 10, 2015, telling ''The New York Times'' they had received a \"criminal referral,\" although the following day they issued a public statement: \"The department has received a referral related to the potential compromise of classified information. It is not a criminal referral.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/22/us/politics/james-comey-election.html|title=Comey Tried to Shield the F.B.I. From Politics. Then He Shaped an Election.|publisher=|accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<!-- exact text per RfC on Talk -->\nIn late June 2016, it was reported that Bill Clinton met privately with Attorney General [[Loretta Lynch]] on her private plane on the tarmac at [[Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport]]. Officials indicated that the 30 minute meeting took place when Clinton became aware that Lynch's plane was on the same tarmac at the airport. When the meeting became public, Lynch stated that it was \"primarily social\" and \"there was no discussion of any matter pending for the department or any matter pending for any other body.\" Lynch was criticized for her involvement in the meeting and was called on by some critics to recuse herself from involvement in the FBI's investigation of the email case. In response, she stated \"The F.B.I. is investigating whether Mrs. Clinton, her aides or anyone else broke the law by setting up a private email server for her to use as secretary of state,\" but \"the case will be resolved by the same team that has been working on it from the beginning\" and \"I will be accepting their recommendations.\"<ref name=\"https\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/02/us/politics/loretta-lynch-hillary-clinton-email-server.html|title=Lynch to Accept F.B.I. Recommendations in Clinton Email Inquiry, Official Says |work=NYT|date=July 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/attorney-general-loretta-lynch-calls-perfectly-reasonable-question/story?id=40272091|title=Attorney General Loretta Lynch Calls It 'Perfectly Reasonable' to Question Bill Clinton Meeting|publisher=ABC News|date=July 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/06/30/loretta-lynch-bill-clinton-meeting/86555274/|title=Loretta Lynch, Bill Clinton meeting raises eyebrows|work=USA Today|date=June 30, 2016}}</ref>\n<!-- end of current consensus text per RfC on Talk -->\n\nOn July 1, 2016, the ''New York Times'' reported in the name of a \"Justice Department official\" that Attorney General Loretta Lynch will accept \"whatever recommendation career prosecutors and the F.B.I. director make about whether to bring charges related to Hillary Clinton's personal email server.\"<ref name=\"https\"/>\n\nClinton maintained she did not send or receive any confidential emails from her personal server. In a Democratic debate with [[Bernie Sanders]] on February 4, 2016, Clinton said, \"I never sent or received any classified material.\" In a Meet the Press interview on July 2, 2016, she stated: \"Let me repeat what I have repeated for many months now, I never received nor sent any material that was marked classified.\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-investigation-sheds-light-hillary-clintons-past-email/story?id=40350589|title=FBI Contradicts Clinton's Email Claims on Classified Info|date=July 5, 2016|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=\"politifact.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2016/jul/06/hillary-clinton/fbi-findings-tear-holes-hillary-clintons-email-def|title=FBI tears holes in Hillary Clinton's email defense|publisher=politifact.com}}</ref><ref name=\"washingtonpost.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2015/08/27/clintons-claims-about-receiving-or-sending-classified-material-on-her-private-email-system|title=Clinton's claims about receiving or sending 'classified material' on her private e-mail system|work=The Washington Post|date=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====July 2016 \u2013 Investigation concludes====\nOn July 5, 2016, FBI Director Comey announced in a statement he read to press and television reporters at FBI headquarters in Washington, DC, that the FBI had completed its investigation and was referring it to the State Department with the recommendation \"that no charges are appropriate in this case.\"<ref name=Comey>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/pressrel/press-releases/statement-by-fbi-director-james-b.-comey-on-the-investigation-of-secretary-hillary-clintons-use-of-a-personal-e-mail-system|title=Statement by FBI Director James B. Comey on the Investigation of Secretary Hillary Clinton's Use of a Personal E-Mail System|publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]|date=July 5, 2016|accessdate=July 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"News\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-completes-investigation-hillary-clintons-personal-email-server/story?id=40346712|title=FBI Recommends No Charges Over Clinton Email Use|first=A.B.C.|last=News|date=July 6, 2016|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=ZapHel>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-chief-plans-remarks-to-media-amid-heightened-focus-on-clinton-email-probe/2016/07/05/a53513c4-42b9-11e6-bc99-7d269f8719b1_story.html|last1=Zapotosky|first1=Matt|last2=Helderman|first2=Rosalind S.|title=FBI recommends no criminal charges in Clinton email probe|work=The Washington Post|date=July 5, 2016|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref> He added, \"Although there is evidence of potential violations of the statutes regarding the handling of classified information, our judgment is that no reasonable prosecutor would bring such a case.\"<ref name=\"Comey\"/><ref name=\"News\"/>\n\nWith regard to mishandling of classified information, Comey said, \"there is evidence that they [Clinton and her team] were extremely careless in their handling of very sensitive, highly classified information.\" The investigation found 110 emails that should have been regarded as classified at the time they were sent; another 2,000 emails were retroactively classified which means they were not classified at the time they were sent.<ref name=\"Comey\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/watch-live-fbi-director-speaks-at-11-a-m-edt|title=FBI director recommends 'no charges' over Clinton's emails|last=Epatko|first=Larisa|date=July 5, 2016|work=PBS|accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref> Comey said that \"any reasonable person in Secretary Clinton's position, or in the position of those government employees with whom she was corresponding ... should have known that an unclassified system was no place for that conversation.\"<ref name=\"FBI-Report\">{{cite web|url=https://vault.fbi.gov/hillary-r.-clinton|title=Clinton e-mail Investigation|publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]|date=July 2016|accessdate=October 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/07/05/politics/fbi-director-doesnt-recommend-charges-against-hillary-clinton/index.html|title=FBI: Clinton 'extremely careless' but no charges recommended|author1=Collinson, Stephen |author2=Tal Kopan|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nThe FBI learned that Clinton used her personal email extensively while outside the United States, both sending and receiving work-related emails in the territory of sophisticated adversaries. The FBI did not find \"direct evidence that Secretary Clinton's personal e-mail domain ... was successfully hacked;\" they assessed it \"possible that hostile actors gained access\" to it.<ref name=Comey/><ref name=ZapHel/> Investigators found that State Department employees often used private emails to conduct business. Comey noted, \"We also developed evidence that the security culture of the State Department in general, and with respect to use of unclassified e-mail systems in particular, was generally lacking in the kind of care for classified information found elsewhere in the government.\"<ref name=\"Graff\">{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/09/hillary-clinton-emails-2016-server-state-department-fbi-214307|title=What the FBI Files Reveal About Hillary Clinton's Email Server|last=Graff|first=Garrett M.|date=September 30, 2016|work=Politico|accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2016, Lynch confirmed that the investigation into Hillary Clinton's use of private email servers while secretary of state would be closed without criminal charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/justice-department-closes-clinton-email-probe-without-charges/2016/07/06/0ad8feda-43c2-11e6-88d0-6adee48be8bc_story.html|last=Zapotosky|first=Matt|title=Justice Department closes Clinton email probe without charges|work=The Washington Post|date=July 6, 2016|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====October 2016 \u2013 Additional investigation====\nIn early October 2016, FBI criminal investigators working on a case involving former Congressman [[Anthony Weiner]] allegedly [[Anthony Weiner sexting scandals|sending sexually explicit texts to a fifteen-year-old girl]] discovered emails from Weiner's estranged wife, [[Huma Abedin]], vice chair of Hillary Clinton's 2016 presidential campaign, that they considered potentially relevant to the Clinton server investigation. FBI officials reportedly decided to disclose the development despite its potential effect on the pending presidential election to preempt the possibility that it would be leaked in another way.<ref name=\"CNN Weiner\">{{cite web|last=Perez|first=Evan|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/30/politics/clinton-emails-fbi-abedin/index.html|title=FBI discovered Clinton-related emails weeks ago|date=October 30, 2016|publisher=CNN|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2016, Comey informed Congress that \"in connection with an unrelated case, the FBI has learned of the existence of emails that appear pertinent to the investigation.\" He said the FBI will take \"appropriate investigative steps designed to allow investigators to review these emails to determine whether they contain classified information, as well as to assess their importance to our investigation.\" He added that the FBI \"cannot yet assess whether or not this material may be significant.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/28/politics/fbi-reviewing-new-emails-in-clinton-probe-director-tells-senate-judiciary-committee/|title=Comey notified Congress of email probe despite DOJ concerns|last1=Perez|first1=Evan|last2=Brown|first2=Pamela|date=October 29, 2016|publisher=CNN|accessdate=October 29, 2016}}</ref> The FBI obtained a new search warrant to allow them to review Abedin's emails.<ref name=\"CNN Weiner\"/>\n\nComey informed Congress of this additional investigation despite having been advised by Justice Department officials that such an announcement would violate department policies and procedures, including a policy not to comment on investigations close to an election.<ref name=\"despite\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/28/politics/fbi-reviewing-new-emails-in-clinton-probe-director-tells-senate-judiciary-committee/|title=Comey notified Congress of email probe despite DOJ concerns|date=October 30, 2016|publisher=CNN|accessdate=November 5, 2016}}</ref> Comey later explained, in a letter to FBI employees, \"We don't ordinarily tell Congress about ongoing investigations, but here I feel an obligation to do so given that I testified repeatedly in recent months that our investigation was completed.\" Law enforcement sources added that he feared he would be accused of concealing relevant information if he did not disclose it.<ref name=\"despite\"/>\n\nNews of this renewed investigation being revealed shortly before the [[2016 United States presidential election|U.S. presidential election]] led to the announcement being described as an \"[[October surprise]],\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.voanews.com/a/furor-over-fbi-email-bombshell/3572062.html|title=Officials: FBI Knew About Possible New Clinton Emails Weeks Before Friday Announcement|last=Bowman|first=Michael|newspaper=VOA|access-date=October 31, 2016}}</ref> and prompted statements from both the Democratic and Republican campaigns. [[Donald Trump]] repeated his characterization that Hillary Clinton's email usage as secretary of state was \"worse than [[Watergate]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4534375/donald-trump-hillary-clinton-emails-watergate/|title=Donald Trump: Hillary Clinton Email Scandal 'Worse Than Watergate'|work=Time|date=October 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/fbi-clinton-new-probe-trump-hails-230460|title=Trump hails new Clinton FBI review as 'bigger than Watergate'|last=Schreckinger|first=Ben|date=October 28, 2016|work=Politico|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref> Clinton called for the FBI to immediately release all information about the newly discovered emails and said she was confident the FBI would not change its earlier conclusion that there is no basis for criminal prosecution.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/10/28/fbi-probe-newly-discovered-hillary-clinton-emails-and-reopen-inv|title=Hillary Clinton demands answers and Democrats call foul as FBI reopens investigation over files found on sexting congressman's computer|date=October 30, 2016|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref> Senator [[Dianne Feinstein]] (D-CA) said she was \"shocked\" by the letter, saying it \"played right into the political campaign of Donald Trump.\"<ref name=\"despite\"/>\n\nOn November 6, in another letter to Congress, Comey stated that, after working \"around the clock\" to review all of the newly discovered emails, the FBI had not changed the conclusion it reached in July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/fbi-completes-review-newly-revealed-hillary-clinton-emails-finds-no-n678701|title=FBI finds no criminality in review of newly discovered Clinton emails|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/07/us/politics/hilary-clinton-male-voters-donald-trump.html|title=Emails Warrant No New Action Against Hillary Clinton, F.B.I. Director Says|date=November 6, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-us-2016-37892138|title=No criminality in Clinton emails \u2013 FBI|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=November 6, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref> An unnamed government official added that the newly discovered emails turned out to be either personal or duplicates of emails previously reviewed, and that Comey's letter represents a conclusion of the investigation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/fbi-director-comey-says-agency-wont-recommend-charges-over-clinton-email/2016/11/06/f6276b18-a45e-11e6-ba59-a7d93165c6d4_story.html|title=FBI director says agency once again won't recommend charges over Clinton email|date=November 6, 2016|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref> The following day, stock and currency markets around the world surged in response.<ref name=Shell>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/markets/2016/11/07/asian-stocks-bounce-after-fbi-clears-clinton-over-emails/93412244|title=Dow surges 300 points as FBI clears Clinton on eve of election|work=[[USA Today]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016|author1=Shell, Adam  |author2=Jane Onyanga-Omara}}</ref><ref name=Imbert>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/07/us-markets.html|title=Dow soars 350 points higher on eve of US election; financials, health care lead|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016|author=Imbert, Fred}}</ref><ref name=Mikolajczak>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-global-markets-idUSKBN13115N|title=Stocks, dollar jump as FBI clears Clinton in email probe|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 16, 2016|author=Mikolajczak, Chuck}}</ref>\n\nOn November 12, during a conference call to top donors, Hillary Clinton attributed her [[2016 United States presidential election|presidential election]] loss to Comey's announcements, saying they stopped her momentum.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lawler |first=David |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/11/12/hillary-clinton-blames-election-loss-on-fbis-james-comey-in-call/ |title=US election: Hillary Clinton blames loss on FBI's James Comey in call with top donors |date=November 13, 2016 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref> In January 2017, the US Justice Department started an investigation of Comey's announcements.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ainsley |first1=Julia Edwards |last2=Harte |first2=Julia |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-clinton-idUSKBN14W2NT |title=FBI investigated over pre-election decisions on Clinton email |date=January 13, 2017 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref> A 2019 study found that Comey's letter substantially increased Trump's probability of winning the 2016 election.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halcoussis|first=Dennis|last2=Lowenberg|first2=Anton D.|last3=Phillips|first3=G. Michael|title=An Empirical Test of the Comey Effect on the 2016 Presidential Election|journal=Social Science Quarterly|language=en|volume=0|doi=10.1111/ssqu.12729|issn=1540-6237|year=2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Senate probes Loretta Lynch interference ===\nAccording to Comey's June 8, 2017, testimony to the Senate Intelligence Committee, then-Attorney General Loretta Lynch had asked him to downplay the investigation into Clinton's emails by calling it a \"matter\" rather than an investigation. He said the request \"confused and concerned\" him. He added that Lynch's tarmac meeting with [[Bill Clinton]] also influenced his decision to publicly announce the results of the FBI probe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/james-comey-loretta-lynch-told-me-not-to-call-clinton-email-probe-an-investigation/article/2625335|title=James Comey: Loretta Lynch told me not to call Clinton email probe an 'investigation'|last=Cohen|first=Kelly|work=Washington Examiner|access-date=July 5, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/senate-probes-loretta-lynchs-alleged-interference-clinton-email/story?id=48237960|title=Senate probes Loretta Lynch's alleged interference in Clinton investigation|last=News|first=A. B. C.|date=June 23, 2017|publisher=ABC News|access-date=July 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://time.com/4831849/loretta-lynch-hillary-clinton-fbi-senate/|title=Senate Investigating Loretta Lynch's Alleged Interference in Hillary Clinton Email Probe|access-date=July 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn June 23, 2017, several members of the Senate Judiciary Committee opened a bipartisan inquiry into whether former Attorney General Lynch interfered in the FBI's investigation into Hillary Clinton's use of a private email server.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/senate-investigates-loretta-lynch-clinton-email-investigation-2017-6|title=The Senate is investigating whether former Attorney General Loretta Lynch interfered in the Clinton email investigation|work=Business Insider|access-date=July 5, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/senate-probes-loretta-lynchs-alleged-interference-clinton-email/story?id=48237960|title=Senate probes Loretta Lynch's alleged interference in Clinton investigation|last=Parkinson|first=John|date=June 23, 2017|publisher=ABC News|access-date=July 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Internal State Department investigation===\nOn July 7, 2016, the internal State Department resumed its review of whether classified information had been mishandled. The review had been suspended until the completion of the Justice Department investigation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Labott|first1=Elise|last2=Lee|first2=MJ|title=Clinton reiterates email use was a 'mistake' as State Dept. reopens probe|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/07/07/politics/state-department-reopens-probe-into-clinton-emails|accessdate=November 5, 2016|work=Salon|date=July 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/news/election-us-2016-36742095|title=Hillary Clinton emails: US State Department restarts probe|publisher=BBC}}</ref> The [[United States Department of State]] finished its investigation in September 2019, citing 588 security violations. The review found that 38 current and former State Department officials \u2013 some of whom may be punished \u2013 were culpable of mishandling classified information, but in 497 cases the culpability could not be established. The material was considered classified then or later, but none of the violations involved information marked classified. The investigation found Clinton's use of personal email server increased the risk of compromising State Department information, but \"there was no persuasive evidence of systemic, deliberate mishandling of classified information\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Matthew |last2=Jalonick |first2=Mary Clare |title=38 people cited for violations in Clinton email probe |url=https://www.apnews.com/14b14afc5d8647858489a2cf5385c28d |work=The Associated Press |date=October 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/state-department-probe-of-clinton-emails-finds-no-deliberate-mishandling-of-classified-information/2019/10/18/83339446-f1dc-11e9-8693-f487e46784aa_story.html|title=State Department probe of Clinton emails finds no deliberate mishandling of classified information|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n=== Department of Justice Inspector General's report ===\n\n{{main|Inspector General report on FBI and DOJ actions in the 2016 election}}\n\nThe [[Inspector General of the Department of Justice]] (IG) launched an investigation into how the DOJ and FBI had handled the investigation into Clinton's email. On June 14, 2018, the IG issued a report that was highly critical of Comey's actions.<ref name = highlights/> Regarding his July press conference, in which he criticized Clinton even while announcing the investigation was over, the IG said it was \"extraordinary and insubordinate for Comey to conceal his intentions (about the press conference) from his superiors,\" and that \"we found none of his reasons to be a persuasive basis for deviating from well-established Department policies.\"<ref name = slams>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/doj-watchdog-slams-insubordinate-james-comey-over-clinton-email_us_5b22a82be4b0d4fc01fc61e6|title=DOJ Watchdog Slams 'Insubordinate' James Comey Over Clinton Email News Conference|last=Reilly|first=Ryan J.|date=June 14, 2018|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=June 16, 2018}}</ref> Comey's October decision to send a letter notifying Congress that the investigation had been re-opened one week before the election was described as \"[[ad-hoc]]\" and \"a serious error in judgment.\"<ref name = slams/> However, in June 2018 the IG concluded that the decision to not prosecute Clinton was not affected by bias and \"was consistent with the Department\u2019s historical approach in prior cases under different leadership, including in the 2008 decision not to prosecute former Attorney General Alberto Gonzales for mishandling classified documents.\"<ref name=cnn-comey14-6-18>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/14/politics/ig-report-clinton-email-investigation/index.html|title=Comey's actions 'extraordinary and insubordinate,' report says|date=June 14, 2018|work=CNN|accessdate=June 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>A Review of Various Actions by the Federal Bureau of Investigation and Department of Justice in Advance of the 2016 Election, Office of the Inspector General, p. vi: https://www.justice.gov/file/1071991/download</ref>\n\nThe IG report also commented on \"highly classified information\" in a purported Russian intelligence document obtained by the FBI that included an unconfirmed allegation that Attorney General [[Loretta Lynch]] assured a Clinton staffer that she would prevent the FBI investigation from digging too deeply into Clinton's affairs. The FBI long considered the document unreliable and a possible forgery, and Comey told IG investigators he knew the information was not true.<ref name=wapo-24-5-2017>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/how-a-dubious-russian-document-influenced-the-fbis-handling-of-the-clinton-probe/2017/05/24/f375c07c-3a95-11e7-9e48-c4f199710b69_story.html |title=How a dubious Russian document influenced the FBI's handling of the Clinton probe |date=May 24, 2017 |publisher= |access-date=January 22, 2018 |last1=Demirjian |first1=Karoun   |last2=Barrett |first2=Devlin }}</ref> The IG report stated: \"Comey said that he became concerned that the information about Lynch would taint the public's perception of the [Clinton] investigation if it leaked, particularly after DCLeaks and Guccifer 2.0 began releasing hacked emails in mid-June 2016,\" explaining why Comey chose to bypass Lynch and deputy AG [[Sally Yates]] to announce the FBI investigation findings himself.<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\">{{cite news |last1=EWING |first1=PHILIP |title=The Russia Investigations: What The Justice IG Report Revealed |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/06/16/620345643/the-russia-investigations-what-the-justice-ig-report-revealed |accessdate=January 11, 2019 |agency=NPR |date=June 16, 2018}}</ref> The ''[[Washington Post]]'' also stated that \"current and former officials\" told them that Comey relied on the questionable document in making his July decision to announce on his own without his superiors approval that the investigation was over.<ref name=wapo-24-5-2017/>\n\n===Opinions of journalists and experts===\nAccording to the ''New York Times'', if Clinton was a recipient of classified emails, \"it is not clear that she would have known that they contained government secrets, since they were not marked classified.\"<ref name=Allen0821>{{cite web|last1=Allen|first1= Jonathan|title=Exclusive: Dozens of Clinton emails were classified from the start, U.S. rules suggest|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/08/21/us-usa-election-clinton-emails-idUSKCN0QQ0BW20150821|agency=Reuters|accessdate=August 28, 2015|date=August 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=NYT72415/> The newspaper reported that \"most specialists believe the occasional appearance of classified information in the Clinton account was probably of marginal consequence\".<ref name=NYT8815/> Steven Aftergood, director of the Project on Government Secrecy at the [[Federation of American Scientists]], said that inadvertent \"spillage\" of classified information into an unclassified realm is a common occurrence.<ref name=\"NYT8815\"/>\n\n[[Reuters]]' August 2015 review of a set of released emails found \"at least 30 email threads from 2009, representing scores of individual emails,\" which include what the State Department identifies as \"foreign government information,\" defined by the U.S. government as \"any information, written or spoken, provided in confidence to U.S. officials by their foreign counterparts.\" Although unmarked, Reuters' examination appeared to suggest that these emails \"were classified from the start.\"<ref name=Allen0821/> [[J. William Leonard]], a former director of the NARA [[Information Security Oversight Office]], said that such information is \"born classified\" and that \"[I]f a foreign minister just told the secretary of state something in confidence, by U.S. rules that is classified at the moment it's in U.S. channels and U.S. possession.\"<ref name=Allen0821/> According to Reuters, the standard U.S. government [[nondisclosure agreement]] \"warns people authorized to handle classified information that it may not be marked that way and that it may come in oral form.\" The State Department \"disputed Reuters' analysis\" but declined to elaborate.<ref name=Allen0821/>\n\nThe [[Associated Press]] reported, \"Some officials said they believed the designations were a stretch\u2014a knee-jerk move in a bureaucracy rife with over-classification.\"<ref name=AP81415/> [[Jeffrey Toobin]], in an August 2015 ''[[The New Yorker|New Yorker]]'' article, wrote that the Clinton email affair is an illustration of overclassification, a problem written about by Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] in his book ''Secrecy: The American Experience''.<ref name=\"Toobin\">Jeffrey Toobin, [http://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/hillarys-problem-the-government-classifies-everything Hillary's Problem: The Government Classifies Everything], ''The New Yorker'', August 18, 2015.</ref> Toobin writes that \"government bureaucracies use classification rules to protect turf, to avoid embarrassment, to embarrass rivals\u2014in short, for a variety of motives that have little to do with national security.\"<ref name=\"Toobin\"/> Toobin wrote that \"It's not only the public who cannot know the extent or content of government secrecy. Realistically, government officials can't know either\u2014and this is Hillary Clinton's problem. Toobin noted that \"one of Clinton's potentially classified email exchanges is nothing more than a discussion of a newspaper story about [[Drone strikes in Pakistan|drones]]\" and wrote: \"That such a discussion could be classified underlines the absurdity of the current system. But that is the system that exists, and if and when the agencies determine that she sent or received classified information through her private server, Clinton will be accused of mishandling national-security secrets.\"<ref name=\"Toobin\"/>\n\nIn an analysis of the Clinton email controversy published by the [[Brookings Institution]], Richard Lempert wrote that \"security professionals have a reputation for erring in the direction of overclassification.\"<ref name=\"German\">German, Ben. [http://www.nationaljournal.com/twentysixteen/2015/08/19/other-top-secret-problem-hurting-hillary-clinton The Other 'Top Secret' Problem Hurting Hillary Clinton] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017184847/http://www.nationaljournal.com/twentysixteen/2015/08/19/other-top-secret-problem-hurting-hillary-clinton |date=October 17, 2015 }}, ''National Journal'', August 19, 2015.</ref> Elizabeth Goitein, co-director of the liberty and national security program at the [[Brennan Center for Justice]] at [[New York University School of Law]], says that \"The odds are good that any classified information in the Clinton emails should not have been classified,\" since an estimated 50 percent to 90 percent of classified documents could be made public without risking national security.<ref name=\"German\" /> Nate Jones, an expert with the [[National Security Archive]] at [[George Washington University]], said: \"Clinton's mistreatment of federal records and the intelligence community's desire to retroactively overclassify are two distinct troubling problems. No politician is giving the right message: Blame Clinton for poor records practices, but don't embrace overclassification while you do it.\"<ref name=\"German\" />\n\n====Russian intelligence and Comey's pronouncements====\nA number of journalists (Philip Ewing<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\"/> and [[Jane Mayer]]<ref name=\"mayer-1-10-18\">{{cite magazine |last1=Jane |first1=Mayer |title=How Russia Helped Swing the Election for Trump |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/10/01/how-russia-helped-to-swing-the-election-for-trump |accessdate=December 23, 2018 |magazine=New Yorker |date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> [[Karoun Demirjian]] and Devlin Barrett)<ref name=wapo-24-5-2017/> \nhave commented on the connection between the alleged Russian intelligence document given to the FBI that suggested Attorney General [[Loretta Lynch]] would prevent the FBI investigation from digging too deeply into Clinton's affairs (see above), and Comey's July announcement of the FBI investigation findings by himself without Lynch's permission,<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\"/><ref name=\"mayer-1-10-18\"/> which was later called \"extraordinary and insubordinate\" by the [[Inspector General report on FBI and DOJ actions in the 2016 election|Department of Justice Inspector General's report]].<ref name=cnn-comey14-6-18/> \u201cCurrent and former officials\u201d told Washington Post reporters Demirjian and Barrett that \u201cComey relied on the document in making his July decision to announce on his own,\u201d because he feared its contents would be leaked, tainting the public's perception of the FBI investigation.<ref name=wapo-24-5-2017/> This was despite the fact that Comey himself told investigators \u201che knew from the first moment\u201d that the document \u201cwasn't true\u201d<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\"/> and the FBI was later unable to corroborate the document.<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\"/>\n\nEwing and Mayer note the document's effect on the election. According to Ewing, \"to the degree\" that the document \"was intended to help disrupt the election, it worked\".<ref name=\"EWING-16-June-2018\"/> Jane Mayer describes the work of political scientist [[Kathleen Hall Jamieson]] who argues that Comey\u2019s \"damaging public pronouncements\" on Clinton\u2019s handling of classified e-mails\" in July and later ten days before the election can \"plausibly be attributed to Russian disinformation\".<ref name=\"mayer-1-10-18\"/> While it is difficult to determine how many voters Clinton lost from the pronouncements, Mayer also quotes the Democratic ranking member of the House Intelligence Committee, [[Adam Schiff]], who states that if \"the fake intelligence\" motivated Comey, then the document was \"probably was the most measurable\u201d and \u201cthe most significant way in which the Russians may have impacted the outcome of the election.\u201d<ref name=\"mayer-1-10-18\"/>\n\n==House Oversight Committee hearing==\nOn July 7, 2016, Comey was questioned for 5 hours by the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]. Comey stated that there was \"evidence of mishandling\" of classified information and that he believed that Clinton was \"extremely careless; I think she was negligent.\" He defended the FBI's recommendation against bringing charges because it \"... would have been unfair and virtually unprecedented ...\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-james-comey-hillary-clinton-email-probe/story?id=41044927|title=What FBI Director Really Said About Clinton Email Probe|first=Mike|last=Levine|date=August 2, 2016|publisher=ABC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-director-set-to-appear-before-congressional-committee-to-answer-questions-on-clinton-investigation/2016/07/07/eb43ec7e-43c1-11e6-88d0-6adee48be8bc_story.html|last=Zapotosky|first=Matt|title=House Republicans grill FBI director Comey on Clinton emails|work=The Washington Post|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Responses and analysis==\n===Clinton's initial response===\n[[File:2015 03 10 Hillary Clinton by Voice of America (cropped to collar).jpg|thumb|left|Clinton addressing email controversy with the media at the [[Headquarters of the United Nations|UN Headquarters]] on March 10, 2015]]\nClinton's spokesman Nick Merrill defended Clinton's usage of her personal server and email accounts as being ''in compliance with the \"letter and spirit of the rules.\"''\n\nClinton herself stated she had done so as a matter of \"convenience.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/10/politics/hillary-clinton-email-scandal-press-conference|title=Hillary Clinton email scandal does damage control \u2013 CNN|author=Alexandra Jaffe and Dan Merica, CNN|date=March 10, 2015|publisher=CNN|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2015, while attending a conference at the [[headquarters of the United Nations|headquarters of the United Nation]]s in [[Manhattan]], Clinton spoke with reporters for about 20 minutes.<ref name=WashPost3>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/hillary-clinton-to-answer-questions-about-use-of-private-e-mail-server/2015/03/10/4c000d00-c735-11e4-a199-6cb5e63819d2_story.html|title=Clinton: It 'might have been smarter' to use a State Dept. e-mail account|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref> Clinton said she had used a private email for convenience, \"because I thought it would be easier to carry just one device for my work and for my personal emails instead of two.\"<ref name=\"cnn03312015\">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/03/31/politics/hillary-clinton-ipad-e-mail-devices|title=Source: Clinton used iPad for personal email at State|publisher=CNN|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=August 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2015/03/10/first-take-hillary-clinton-emails/24705871|title=First Take: Clinton's even tone edges into exasperation |  work=USA Today | date=March 11, 2015 | accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>\nIt was later determined that Clinton had used both an [[iPad]] and a [[BlackBerry]] while Secretary of State.<ref name=cnn03312015/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/64f85b3a72184bd1b4604d5e1870116d/clinton-also-used-ipad-email-mixed-personal-work-chats|title=State Department found 4 emails about drones sent by Clinton|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=August 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/hillary-clinton-actually-used-two-devices-while-secretary-of-state-records-show-10147082.html|title=Hillary Clinton actually used two devices while secretary of state, records show |work=The Independent| accessdate=August 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2015/03/31/hillary-clinton-also-used-an-ipad-for-e-mails-undercutting-her-single-device-defense|title=Hillary Clinton also used an iPad for e-mails, undercutting her single-device defense|work=The Washington Post| accessdate = August 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nClinton turned over copies of 30,000 State Department business-related emails from her private server that belonged in the public domain; she later explained that she instructed her lawyer to err on the side of disclosure, turning over any emails that ''might'' be work-related. Her aides subsequently deleted about 31,000 emails from the server dated during the same time period that Clinton regarded as personal and private.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-hillary-clinton-email-un-20150310-story.html#page=2|title=Hillary Clinton tries to end controversy over private email account |quote=she disclosed that her aides had deleted more than 30,000 emails that she deemed personal. ... Clinton said that when she and her staff reviewed the emails last year, she instructed her lawyer to err on the side of turning over anything that might be considered work-related.|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/10/hillary-clinton-spam-deleted-214351|title=Most Clinton Spam Messages Likely Deleted|publisher=Politico|date=October 1, 2015|authors=Josh Gerstein and Joseph Marks|quote=[A]ccording to little-noticed language in a statement Clinton's office issued earlier this year. ... 'After her work-related emails were identified and preserved, Secretary Clinton chose not to keep her private, personal messages. ... '}}</ref><ref name=\"SchmidtPrivateEmails\">Michael S. Schmidt, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/12/us/justice-dept-says-hillary-clinton-had-authority-to-delete-certain-emails.html?_r=0 Justice Dept. Says Hillary Clinton Had Authority to Delete Certain Emails], ''The New York Times'', September 11, 2015.</ref> State Department employees do have the right to delete personal emails.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hillary Clinton had right to delete personal emails, says US justice department|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/sep/12/hillary-clinton-had-right-to-delete-personal-emails-says-us-justice-department|accessdate=November 4, 2016|work=The Guardian|agency=Associated Press|date=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nClinton has used humor to try to shrug off the scandals.<ref>O'Harrow, Robert. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/how-clintons-email-scandal-took-root/2016/03/27/ee301168-e162-11e5-846c-10191d1fc4ec_story.html \"How Clinton's email scandal took root\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', March 27, 2016.</ref><ref>Vorhees, Josh. [http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2015/08/20/hillary_clinton_email_scandal_explained.html A Crystal-Clear Explanation of Hillary's Confusing Email Scandal], ''Slate'', August 20, 2015.</ref> In August 2015, when asked by a reporter whether she had \"wiped\" her server, Clinton laughed and said: \"What? Like with a cloth or something? I don't know how it works digitally at all.\"<ref>Struyk, Ryan & Liz Kreutz, [http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/hillary-clinton-jokes-wiping-email-server-cloth/story?id=33165517 Hillary Clinton Jokes About Wiping Email Server 'With A Cloth Or Something'], ABC News, August 18, 2015.</ref> In September 2015, Clinton was asked in an interview with [[Jimmy Fallon]] on ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' about the content of the emails. She laughed it off, saying there was nothing interesting and joking that she was offended people found her emails 'boring.'<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/jimmy-fallon-gives-hillary-a-pass-on-boring-emails|title=Jimmy Fallon Gives Hillary a Pass on 'Boring' Emails|author=Wilstein, Matt|accessdate=April 16, 2016|publisher=Mediaite}}</ref>\n\n====Later responses====\nClinton's responses to the question, made during her presidential campaign, evolved over time.<ref name=\"Toobin\"/><ref name=politics>{{cite news|author1=Leonnig, Carol D., Karen Tumulty & Rosalind S. Helderman|title=Clinton's team went from nonchalant to nervous over e-mail controversy|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/how-clintons-team-went-from-nonchalant-to-nervous-over-e-mail-controversy/2015/08/14/347f1066-405e-11e5-9561-4b3dc93e3b9a_story.html|accessdate=August 18, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=August 14, 2015|quote= ... it has become clear that a number of her statements defending her actions now appear to be false.}}</ref> Clinton initially said that there was no classified material on her server. Later, after a government review discovered some of her emails contained classified information, she said she never sent or received information that was ''marked'' classified.<ref name=\"Toobin\" /> Her campaign claimed other emails contained information that is now classified, but was ''retroactively'' classified by U.S. intelligence agencies after Clinton had received the material.<ref name=\"Campaign Classified\">Tau, Byron & Robert McMillan. [https://www.wsj.com/articles/hillary-clinton-says-classified-emails-were-on-server-1440030491 Hillary Clinton Campaign Says Classified Emails Were on Server], ''The Wall Street Journal'', August 19, 2015.</ref> See also the section above on the [[Hillary Clinton email controversy#May 2016 report from State Department's inspector general|May 2016 IG report]] for a number of Clinton statements that were contradicted by the report, and how she and her supporters responded afterward.\n\nCampaign spokesman Brian Fallon said: \"She was at worst a passive recipient of unwitting information that subsequently became deemed as classified.\"<ref name=\"Campaign Classified\"/> Clinton campaign spokeswoman [[Jennifer Palmieri]] has \"stressed that Clinton was permitted to use her own email account as a government employee and that the same process concerning classification reviews would still be taking place had she used the standard 'state.gov' email account used by most department employees.\"<ref name=AP81415>{{cite news|author1=Bradley Klapper  |author2=Ken Dilanian|title=Top secret Clinton emails include drone talk|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b54a250a40e9410baaaca5f9fb58ea94/ap-exclusive-top-secret-clinton-emails-include-drone-talk|accessdate=August 19, 2015|work=AP Big Story|agency=Associated Press|date=August 14, 2015|quote=part of a covert program that is widely known and discussed}}</ref><ref name=\"KesslerFactCheck\">Kessler, Glenn, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/fact-checker/wp/2015/07/09/hillary-clintons-claim-that-everything-i-did-on-emails-was-permitted \"Hillary Clinton's claim that everything I did on e-mails was permitted\"], ''The Washington Post'', July 9, 2015.</ref> Palmieri later stated: \"Look, this kind of nonsense comes with the territory of running for president. We know it, Hillary knows it, and we expect it to continue from now until Election Day.\"<ref name=AP0813>Eric Tucker, [http://www.aol.com/article/2015/08/13/clinton-aides-agree-to-preserve-emails-after-judges-order/21222558 \"Clinton Aides Agree to Preserve Emails after Judge's Order\"], Associated Press, August 13, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn her first national interview about the 2016 presidential race, on July 7, 2015, Clinton was asked by [[CNN]]'s [[Brianna Keilar]] about her use of private email accounts while serving as Secretary of State. She said:\n\n{{quote|Everything I did was permitted. There was no law. There was no regulation. There was nothing that did not give me the full authority to decide how I was going to communicate. Previous secretaries of state have said they did the same thing ... Everything I did was permitted by law and regulation. I had one device. When I mailed anybody in the government, it would go into the government system.<ref>[http://cnnpressroom.blogs.cnn.com/2015/07/07/cnn-exclusive-hillary-clintons-first-national-interview-of-2016-race \"Hillary Clinton's first national interview of 2016 Race\"], CNN, July 7, 2015.</ref>}}\n\nOn September 9, 2015, Clinton apologized during an ABC News interview for using the private server, saying she was \"sorry for that.\"<ref name=\"abcsorry\">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/hillary-clinton-private-email-mistake-im/story?id=33608970|title=Hillary Clinton on Private Email: 'That Was a Mistake. I'm Sorry'|last=Kreutz|first=Liz|date=September 8, 2015|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> Appearing on NBC's ''[[Meet the Press]]'' on September 27, 2015, Clinton defended her use of the private email server while she was secretary of state, comparing the investigations to Republican-led probes of her husband's presidential administration more than two decades ago, saying, \"It is like a drip, drip, drip. And that's why I said, there's only so much that I can control.\"<ref name=Lerer0927>Lisa Lerer,  [http://www.aol.com/article/2015/09/27/clinton-compares-email-attacks-to-white-house-controversies/21241424/ Clinton Compares email Attacks to White House Controversies], Associated Press, September 27, 2015.</ref>\n\nClinton and the State Department said the emails were not marked classified when sent. However, Clinton signed a [[non-disclosure agreement]] which stated that classified material may be \"marked or unmarked.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/07/27/opinions/cox-clinton-email-controversy|title=Hillary Clinton email controversy: How serious is it?|author=Douglas Cox|date=July 27, 2015|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2016/02/04/how-did-top-secret-emails-end-up-on-hillary-clintons-server|title=How did 'top secret' emails end up on Hillary Clinton's server?|author=Glenn Kessler|date=February 4, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/clinton-emails-held-indirect-references-undercover-cia-officers-n510741|title=Clinton Emails Held Indirect References to Undercover CIA Officers|author=Ken Dilanian|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> Additionally, the author of an email is legally required to properly mark it as classified if it contains classified material, and to avoid sending classified material on a personal device, such as the ones used exclusively by Clinton.<ref>Gearan, Anne.  [https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/new-batch-of-clinton-e-mails-due-monday-minus-150-deemed-classified/2015/08/31/dcbdcbbc-501e-11e5-8c19-0b6825aa4a3a_story.html \"Big batch of Clinton e-mails released; some have redactions\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', August 31, 2015: \"Under the law, it is the responsibility of the author of e-mails to properly mark them as classified and to make sure they avoid discussing classified material over a nongovernment or personal device. Because the State Department deals in so many sensitive secrets, many employees use two computer networks for their daily communications: a non-classified system called the \"low side\" and a more secure classified system called the \"high side.\" But Clinton had no official State Department e-mail address and exclusively used a personal domain and personal server set up in her home for electronic correspondence.\"</ref>\n\nClinton maintained that she did not send or receive any confidential emails from her personal server. In a Democratic debate with [[Bernie Sanders]] on February 4, 2016, Clinton said, \"I never sent or received any classified material.\" In a Meet the Press interview on July 2, 2016, Clinton stated: \"Let me repeat what I have repeated for many months now, I never received nor sent any material that was marked classified.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"politifact.com\"/><ref name=\"washingtonpost.com1\"/>\n\nIn an interview with Fox News in late July 2016, Clinton stated \"Director Comey said my answers were truthful, and what I've said is consistent with what I have told the American people, that there were decisions discussed and made to classify retroactively certain of the emails.\" The Washington Post awarded Clinton four \"Pinocchios\", its worst rating, for her statement saying \"While Comey did say there was no evidence she lied to the FBI, that is not the same as saying she told the truth to the American public.\"<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2016/07/31/clintons-claim-that-the-fbi-director-said-her-email-answers-were-truthful \"Clinton\u2019s claim that the [[FBI]] director at the time, James Comey, said that Clinton's email answers were ''truthful''\"], ''The Washington Post'', July 31, 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/01/politics/washington-post-clinton-four-pinnochios-comey-emails/index.html][[Washington Post]]<span> hits Clinton with four 'Pinnochios' on emails</span>, CNN (August 1, 2016).</ref><ref>[http://nation.foxnews.com/2016/08/01/wapo-gives-hillary-four-pinocchios-claiming-comey-called-her-truthful-about-her-emails \"WaPo Gives Hillary Four Pinocchios For Claiming Comey Called Her ''Truthful'' About Her Emails\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819034501/http://nation.foxnews.com/2016/08/01/wapo-gives-hillary-four-pinocchios-claiming-comey-called-her-truthful-about-her-emails# |date=August 19, 2016 }}, Fox News Channel, August 1, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn her 2017 book ''What Happened?'', Clinton argued that the email controversy and FBI Director James Comey's actions contributed to her loss. A 2019 study in the journal ''Perspectives on Politics'' found little evidence to support the hypothesis.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Quinlan|first=Stephen|last2=Lewis-Beck|first2=Michael S.|date=2019|title=The Hillary Hypotheses: Testing Candidate Views of Loss|journal=Perspectives on Politics|language=en|volume=17|issue=3|pages=646\u2013665|doi=10.1017/S153759271800347X|issn=1537-5927|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Venice]] at the \u201cHillary: The Hillary Clinton Emails,\u201d a work on display in a balcony jutting out over a supermarket at the Despar Teatro Italia during the [[58th Venice Biennale|58th Biennale of Visual Arts]], Clinton made a surprise visit on Tuesday September 10, 2019, to this work of political theater and performance art. The exhibition created by the American poet and artist [[Kenneth Goldsmith]] is displayed from May 9, 2019, until November 24, 2019, during the Francesco Urbano Ragazzi's Biennale. During her appearance, she said that the attention given to her emails was one of the \u201cstrangest\u201d and most \u201cabsurd\u201d events in U.S. political history, adding, \u201cAnyone can go in and look at them. There is nothing there. There is nothing that should have been so controversial.\u201d<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/09/12/breaking-news/hillary-clinton-reads-her-emails-at-venice-art-show/| title=Hillary Clinton reads her emails at Venice art show| newspaper=[[Star-Advertiser]]| location=[[Honolulu]]| via=[[New York Times]]| date=September 12, 2019| access-date=September 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic response===\nIn August 2015, the ''New York Times'' reported on \"interviews with more than 75 Democratic governors, lawmakers, candidates and party members\" on the email issue.<ref name=\"FrustratesDems\">Patrick Healy, Jonathan Martin & Maggie Haberman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/28/us/politics/hillary-clintons-handling-of-email-issue-frustrates-democratic-leaders.html Hillary Clinton\u2019s Handling of Email Issue Frustrates Democratic Leaders], ''The New York Times'', August 27, 2015.</ref> The ''Times'' reported, \"None of the Democrats interviewed went so far as to suggest that the email issue raised concerns about Mrs. Clinton's ability to serve as president, and many expressed a belief that it had been [[manufactured controversy|manufactured]] by Republicans in Congress and other adversaries.\"<ref name=\"FrustratesDems\"/> At the same time, many Democratic leaders showed increasing frustration among party leaders of Clinton's handling of the email issue. For example, [[Edward G. Rendell]], former [[governor of Pennsylvania]], a Clinton supporter, said that a failure of the Clinton campaign to get ahead of the issue early on meant that the campaign was \"left just playing defense.\"<ref name=\"FrustratesDems\"/> Other prominent Democrats, such as Governor [[Dannel P. Malloy]] of [[Connecticut]], were less concerned, noting the campaign was at an early stage and that attacks on Clinton were to be expected.<ref name=\"FrustratesDems\"/>\n\nAt the October 2015 primary debate, Clinton's chief rival for the Democratic presidential nomination, Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] of [[Vermont]], defended Clinton, saying: \"Let me say this. Let me say something that may not be great politics. But I think the secretary is right. And that is that the American people are sick and tired of hearing about your damn emails!\"<ref name=\"DamnEmailsRoy\">Roy, Jessica. [http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pol-prez-bernie-sanders-damn-emails-20151013-htmlstory.html \"Watch Bernie Sanders slay the room with 'damn emails' line\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', October 13, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"Terkel\">Terkel, Amanda. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/bernie-sanders-hillary-clinton-emails_5623adaee4b02f6a900ca3b9 \"Bernie Sanders: No Regrets Defending Hillary Clinton on Emails\"], ''HuffPost'', October 19, 2015.</ref> Sanders later clarified that he thought Clinton's emails were a \"very serious issue,\"<ref name=\"Foley\">Foley, Elise. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/bernie-sanders-hillary-clinton-emails_us_56ae254be4b077d4fe8e7023 Bernie Sanders Calls Hillary Clinton\u2019s Emails \u2018A Very Serious Issue\u2019], Huffington Post (January 31, 2016).</ref> but Americans want a discussion on issues that are \"real\" to them, such as paid [[Family leave|family]] and [[medical leave]], [[College tuition in the United States|college affordability]], and [[campaign finance reform]].<ref name=\"Terkel\"/>\n\n\"But her emails!\" became a meme during and following the 2016 election, often used in a joking or mocking way.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brandwatch.com/blog/react-but-her-emails/|title=\"But Her Emails!\" Unpicking the Social Media Phenomenon That Is Hillary Clinton's Emails|last=Joyce|first=Gemma|date=October 12, 2017|work=Brandwatch|accessdate=August 3, 2018}}</ref> Clinton herself echoed the phrase in June 2018, when the Justice Department's Inspector General issued a [[Inspector General report on FBI and DOJ actions in the 2016 election|report]] on how the investigation of her use of email was conducted. It revealed that FBI Director Comey had used a personal email account to conduct FBI business; Clinton's response was a Twitter comment, \"But my emails!\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2018/06/14/hillary-clinton-justice-report-fbi/703886002/|title='But my emails': Hillary Clinton claps back after report reveals Comey used Gmail|last=Cummings|first=William|date=June 14, 2018|work=USA Today|accessdate=August 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Republican response===\n[[Chairman of the Republican National Committee|Republican National Committee chairman]] [[Reince Priebus]] said, in a statement regarding the June 30, 2015 email releases, \"These emails ... are just the tip of the iceberg, and we will never get full disclosure until Hillary Clinton releases her secret server for an independent investigation.\"<ref name=LATimes2/> [[Trey Gowdy]] said on June 29, 2015, that he would press the State Department for a fuller accounting of Clinton's emails, after the Benghazi panel retrieved 15 additional emails to Sidney Blumenthal that the department had not provided to the Committee.<ref name=Memoli1>Memoli, Michael A. [http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-hillary-clinton-state-emails-20150629-story.html Next batch of Hillary Clinton's emails will be released], ''Los Angeles Times'', June 30, 2015.</ref>\n\nOn September 12, 2015, Republican Senators [[Charles Grassley]] and [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]], chairmen of the Senate [[Senate Judiciary Committee|Judiciary]] and [[Senate Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs Committee|Homeland Security]] committees, respectively, said they would seek an independent review of the deleted emails, if they were recovered from Clinton's server, to determine if there were any government related items among those deleted.<ref name=WP0912/>\n\n===Comparisons and media coverage===\nAnalyses by Columbia Journalism Review, the [[Berkman Klein Center for Internet & Society|Berkman Klein Center]] for Internet and Society at Harvard University, and the [[Shorenstein Center on Media, Politics and Public Policy|Shorenstein Center]] at the Harvard Kennedy School show that the Clinton email controversy received more coverage in mainstream media outlets than any other topic during the 2016 presidential election.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> The ''New York Times'' coverage of the email controversy was notoriously extensive; according to a Columbia Journalism Review analysis, \"''in just six days, ''The New York Times'' ran as many cover stories about Hillary Clinton's emails as they did about all policy issues combined in the 69 days leading up to the election'' (and that does not include the three additional articles on October 18, and November 6 and 7, or the two articles on the emails taken from John Podesta).\"<ref name=\":4\" /> In attempting to explain the lopsided coverage, the Columbia Journalism Review speculates, \"In retrospect, it seems clear that the press in general made the mistake of assuming a Clinton victory was inevitable, and were setting themselves as credible critics of the next administration.\"<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n[[Pundit|Media commentators]] drew comparisons of Clinton's email usage to past political controversies. ''Pacific Standard Magazine'' published an article in May 2015, comparing email controversy and her response to it with the [[Whitewater controversy|Whitewater]] investigation 20 years earlier.<ref name=\"PS031615\">{{cite news|last1=Gerth|first1=Jeff|title=Hillary Clinton's Email Scandal Looks a Lot Like the Whitewater Investigation of 20 Years Ago|url=https://psmag.com/news/hillary-clintons-email-scandal-looks-a-lot-like-the-whitewater-investigation-of-20-years-ago|accessdate=October 13, 2015|work=Pacific Standard|date=March 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, ''Washington Post'' associate editor and [[investigative journalist]] [[Bob Woodward]], when asked about Clinton's handling of her emails, said they remind him of the [[Nixon White House tapes|Nixon tapes]] from the [[Watergate scandal]].<ref>[http://www.msnbc.com/morning-joe/watch/security-questions-linger-in-clinton-emails-508380739552 Security questions linger in Clinton emails], ''[[Morning Joe]]'', August 19, 2015.</ref> On March 9, 2015, liberal columnist and Clinton supporter [[Dana Milbank]] wrote that the email affair was \"a needless, self-inflicted wound\" brought about by \"debilitating caution\" in \"trying to make sure an embarrassing e-mail or two didn't become public,\" which led to \"obsessive secrecy.\" Milbank pointed out that Clinton herself had justifiably criticized the George W. Bush administration in 2007 for its \"secret\" White House email accounts.<ref name=CT3915>{{cite news|last1=Milbank|first1=Dana|title=Hillary Clinton, too cautious for her own good|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/hillary-clintons-debilitating-caution/2015/03/06/e3225638-c411-11e4-9ec2-b418f57a4a99_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=GWBSalon>{{cite news|last1=Boehlert|first1=Eric|title=The George W. Bush email scandal the media has conveniently forgotten|url=http://www.salon.com/2015/03/12/the_george_w_bush_email_scandal_the_media_has_conveniently_forgotten_partner/|work=Salon|date=March 12, 2015|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn ''[[Fox News Sunday]]'', [[political analyst]] [[Juan Williams]] contrasted the [[media coverage]] of Clinton's emails to the coverage of the 2007 [[Bush White House email controversy]] which he claimed received \"just about zero press coverage.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/punditfact/statements/2015/mar/15/juan-williams/media-reaction-george-w-bushs-email-controversy|title=The media reaction to George W. Bush's email controversy|publisher=[[PolitiFact]]|date=March 15, 2015|accessdate=October 13, 2015|last=Carroll|first=Lauren}}</ref> PolitiFact found Williams' assertion to be \"mostly false,\" concluding \"We found hundreds of articles and television transcripts referencing the issue. Still, Williams has something of a point that compared to the extensive recent coverage of Clinton's use of private email, media coverage of the 2007 Bush White House email controversy was thin.\"<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'' published an editorial opining that \"the only believable reason for the private server in her basement was to keep her emails out of the public eye by willfully avoiding freedom of information laws. No president, no secretary of state, no public official at any level is above the law. She chose to ignore it, and must face the consequences.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/opinion/clintons-absymal-record-on-open-government-b99696012z1-374014501.html|title=Clinton's abysmal record on open government|publisher=jsonline.com|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/2016-dem-primary-live-updates-and-results/2016/03/milwaukee-journal-sentinel-criticizes-hillary-clinton-221390|title=Wisconsin's largest paper blasts Clinton on transparency|work=POLITICO}}</ref> Pascal-Emmanuel Gobry wrote in ''[[The Week]]'' that \"Clinton set up a personal email server, in defiance or at least circumvention of rules, with the probable motive of evading federal records and transparency requirements, and did it with subpar security.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/articles/615382/hillary-clintons-litany-scandal|title=Hillary Clinton's litany of scandal|work=The Week|accessdate=March 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2, 2016, [[Fox News]] anchor [[Bret Baier]] reported that according to Fox's anonymous sources the FBI had discovered that Clinton's private server had been hacked by \"five foreign intelligence agencies.\"<ref name=Cummings>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2016/11/04/fox-news-apologizes-clinton-report/93300254|last1=Cummings|first1=William|title=Fox News anchor apologizes for false report of 'likely' Clinton indictment|work=USA Today|date=November 4, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Farhi>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-chief-plans-remarks-to-media-amid-heightened-focus-on-clinton-email-probe/2016/07/05/a53513c4-42b9-11e6-bc99-7d269f8719b1_story.html|last1=Farhi|first1=Paul|title=Fox News apologizes for falsely reporting that Clinton faces indictment|work=The Washington Post|date=November 4, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/11/tracking-the-fbi-stories-about-clinton/506642/|title=The Anatomy of a Leak: How Did a Mistaken Clinton Story Happen?|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=Nov 4, 2016|author=David Graham}}</ref> Baier further reported that according to an anonymous source an FBI investigation of the Clinton Foundation was \"likely\" to lead to an indictment of Hillary Clinton.<ref name=Cummings/><ref name=Farhi/> On November 4, 2016, he acknowledged that his assertions were a mistake, saying, \"indictment obviously is a very loaded word,\" and that he was sorry.<ref name=Snopes>{{cite web|url=http://www.snopes.com/homeland-security-indicts-hillary|last1=Emery|first1=David|title= Premature Litigation|website=Snopes.com|date=November 4, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Cummings/><ref name=Farhi/>\n\n==House Select Committee on Benghazi==\n{{main|United States House Select Committee on Benghazi}}\n\nOn March 27, 2015, Republican Congressman [[Trey Gowdy]], Chairman of the Select Committee on Benghazi, asserted that some time after October 2014, Clinton \"unilaterally decided to wipe her server clean\" and \"summarily decided to delete all emails.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://benghazi.house.gov/news/press-releases/statement-regarding-subpoena-compliance-and-server-determination-by-former|title=Statement Regarding Subpoena Compliance and Server Determination by Former Secretary of State Hillary Clinton &#124; Select Committee on Benghazi|publisher=Benghazi.house.gov|date=October 28, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402175403/http://benghazi.house.gov/news/press-releases/statement-regarding-subpoena-compliance-and-server-determination-by-former|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Perry|first=Mark|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/03/gowdy-clinton-wiped-her-server-clean-116472.html|title=Trey Gowdy: Hillary Clinton wiped email server clean|publisher=Politico.com|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref> Clinton's attorney, [[David E. Kendall]], said that day that an examination showed that no copies of any of Clinton's emails remained on the server. Kendall said the server was reconfigured to only retain emails for 60 days after Clinton lawyers had decided which emails needed to be turned over.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/28/us/politics/no-copies-of-hillary-clinton-emails-on-server-lawyer-says.html|title=No Copies of Hillary Clinton Emails on Server Lawyer Says|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2015, the Benghazi panel released emails between Clinton and [[Sidney Blumenthal]], who had been recently deposed by the committee. Committee chairman Gowdy issued a press release criticizing Clinton for not providing the emails to the State Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://benghazi.house.gov/news/press-releases/select-committee-adds-to-secretary-clinton-s-public-email-record|title=Select Committee Adds to Secretary Clinton's Public Email Record|work=Select Committee on Benghazi|accessdate=August 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901071429/http://benghazi.house.gov/news/press-releases/select-committee-adds-to-secretary-clinton-s-public-email-record|archive-date=September 1, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Clinton had said she provided all work-related emails to the State Department, and that only emails of a personal nature on her private server were destroyed. The State Department confirmed that 10 emails and parts of five others from Sidney Blumenthal regarding Benghazi, which the Committee had made public on June 22, could not be located in the Department's records, but that the 46 other, previously unreleased Libya-related Blumenthal emails published by the Committee, were in the Department's records. In response, Clinton campaign spokesman Nick Merrill, when asked about the discrepancy said: \"She has turned over 55,000 pages of materials to the State Department, including all emails in her possession from Mr. Blumenthal.\"<ref name=KlapperLee>Bradley Klapper & Matthew Lee, [http://www.aol.com/article/2015/06/25/state-dept-15-emails-missing-from-clinton-cache/21201434/ State Dept.: 15 emails missing from Clinton cache], Associated Press (June 25, 2015).</ref> Republican Committee members were encouraged about their probe, having found emails that Clinton failed to produce.<ref name=KlapperLee/><ref name=NJ1>{{cite news|author=Ben German|title=GOP's Benghazi Probe Ups Pressure on John Kerry as Team Clinton Returns Fire: Republican Rep. Trey Gowdy said he may call the secretary of State to testify about a lack of document production|work=National Journal|date=June 28, 2015|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/2016-elections/gop-s-benghazi-probe-ups-pressure-on-john-kerry-as-team-clinton-returns-fire-20150628|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150629135647/http://www.nationaljournal.com/2016-elections/gop-s-benghazi-probe-ups-pressure-on-john-kerry-as-team-clinton-returns-fire-20150628|archivedate=June 29, 2015}}</ref> Clinton campaign staff accused Gowdy and Republicans of \"clinging to their invented scandal.\"<ref name=NJ1/>\n\nIn response to comments that House Republican Majority Leader [[Kevin McCarthy (California politician)|Kevin McCarthy]] made on September 29, 2015, about damaging Clinton's poll numbers,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/kevin-mccarthys-truthful-gaffe/2015/09/30/f12a9fac-67a8-11e5-8325-a42b5a459b1e_story.html|title=Kevin McCarthy's truthful gaffe on Benghazi|first=E.J.|last=Dionne|authorlink=E.J. Dionne|date=September 30, 2015|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> Minority Leader [[Nancy Pelosi]] threatened to end the Democrats' participation in the committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/255625-pelosi-threatens-to-end-dem-participation-in-benghazi-probe|title=Pelosi threatens to end Dem participation in Benghazi probe|work=The Hill|first=Mike|last=Lillis|date=October 1, 2015|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2015/10/05/house-democrats-to-release-benghazi-interview-transcript|title=House Democrats to Release Benghazi Interview Transcript|author=Byron Tau|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2015/10/06/democrats-work-to-keep-heat-on-gowdy-mccarthy-ahead-of-clinton-benghazi-hearing|title=Democrats work to keep heat on Gowdy, McCarthy ahead of Clinton Benghazi hearing|author=Elise Viebeck|date=October 6, 2015|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> Representative [[Louise Slaughter]] (D-NY) introduced an amendment to disband the committee, which was defeated in a party-line vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/10/06/politics/benghazi-committee-democrats-threat/index.html?eref=rss_latest|title=Democrats go on offense after McCarthy's Benghazi gaffe|author1=Kopan, Tal  |author2=Deirdre Walsh|date=October 7, 2015|publisher=CNN|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> On October 7, the [[editorial board]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called for the end of the committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/07/opinion/shut-down-the-benghazi-committee.html|title=Shut Down the Benghazi Committee|work=The New York Times|date=October 7, 2015|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> Representative [[Alan Grayson]] (D-FL) took step towards filing an ethics complaint, calling the committee \"the new McCarthyism\", alleging it was violating both House rules and federal law by using official funds for political purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.rollcall.com/218/grayson-file-benghazi-ethics-complaint-mccarthy-gowdy|title=Grayson to File Benghazi Ethics Complaint Over Benghazi|work=Roll Call|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> [[Richard L. Hanna]], (R-NY),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/10/clinton_campaign_gop_rep_richard_hanna_admits_benghazi_probe_is_political_sham.html|title=GOP Rep. Richard Hanna suggests Benghazi probe targeted Hillary Clinton|publisher=syracuse.com|accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref> and conservative [[pundit]] [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]] acknowledged the partisan nature of the committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/10/bill-oreilly-benghazi-investigation-political-214620|title=Bill O'Reilly on Benghazi probe: 'Of course it's political'|work=Politico|accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:House Select Committee on Benghazi.png|thumb|Hillary Clinton's public hearing before the House Select Committee on Benghazi]]\nOn October 22, 2015, Clinton testified before the Committee and answered members' questions for eleven hours before the Committee in a public hearing.<ref name=\"ShearSchmidt\">Michael D. Shear & Michael S. Schmidt, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/23/us/politics/hillary-clinton-benghazi-committee.html Benghazi Panel Engages Clinton in Tense Session], ''The New York Times'', October 22, 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=David A.|last1=Fahrenthold|first2=Elise|last2=Viebeck|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/clintons-benghazi-testimony-today-has-high-political-stakes-for-both-sides/2015/10/22/beff40d2-7838-11e5-bc80-9091021aeb69_story.html|title=GOP lands no solid punches while sparring with Clinton over Benghazi|work=The Washington Post|date=October 22, 2015|accessdate=October 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2015/10/22/transcript-clinton-testifies-before-house-committee-on-benghazi|title=Full Text of Hearing: \"Clinton testifies before House committee on Benghazi\"|work=The Washington Post|date=October 22, 2015|accessdate=October 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' reported that \"the long day of often-testy exchanges between committee members and their prominent witness revealed little new information about an episode that has been the subject of seven previous investigations ... Perhaps stung by recent admissions that the pursuit of Mrs. Clinton's emails was politically motivated, Republican lawmakers on the panel for the most part avoided any mention of her use of a private email server.\"<ref name=\"ShearSchmidt\"/> The email issue did arise shortly before lunch, in \"a shouting match\" between Republican committee chair [[Trey Gowdy]] and two Democrats, [[Adam Schiff]] and [[Elijah Cummings]].<ref name=\"ShearSchmidt\"/> Late in the hearing, Republican Representative [[Jim Jordan (U.S. politician)|Jim Jordan]] of Ohio accused Clinton of changing her accounts of the email service, leading to a \"heated exchange\" in which Clinton said that she had erred in making a private email account, but denied having dealt with anything marked classified, instead seeking \"to be transparent by publicly releasing her emails.\"<ref name=\"ShearSchmidt\"/>\n\n==Freedom of Information lawsuits==\n===''Judicial Watch v. U.S. Department of State''===\n[[File:Huma Abedin handing Hillary Clinton notes and a pen.jpg|thumb|Huma Abedin and Hillary Clinton]]\n\n[[Judicial Watch]], a conservative activist group, filed a complaint against the Department of State in the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]] on September 10, 2013, seeking records under the [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|federal Freedom of Information Act]] relating to Clinton aide [[Huma Abedin]] (a former deputy chief of staff and former senior advisor at the State Department).<ref name=\"JW March 12, 2015\">Judicial Watch, [http://www.judicialwatch.org/press-room/press-releases/citing-misconduct-and-misrepresentation-by-hillary-clinton-and-state-department-judicial-watch-asks-federal-court-to-reopen-lawsuit-seeking-information-on-top-clinton-aide-huma-abedin/ Citing Misconduct and Misrepresentation by Hillary Clinton and State Department, Judicial Watch Asks Federal Court to Reopen Lawsuit Seeking Information on Top Clinton Aide Huma Abedin] (March 12, 2015).</ref><ref name=\"JW September 2013 Complaint\">Judicial Watch, [http://www.judicialwatch.org/document-archive/huma-employment/ Huma Outside Employment Complaint] (September 10, 2013)</ref> Judicial Watch was particularly interested in Abedin's role as a \"special government employee\" (SGE), a consulting position which allowed her to represent outside clients while also serving at the State Department. After corresponding with the State Department, Judicial Watch agreed to dismiss its lawsuit on March 14, 2014.<ref name=\"JW March 12, 2015\"/> On March 12, 2015, in response to the uncovering of Clinton's private email account, it filed a motion to reopen the suit, alleging that the State Department had misrepresented its search and had not properly preserved and maintained records under the act.<ref name=\"JW March 12, 2015\"/> U.S. District Judge [[Emmet G. Sullivan]] granted the motion to reopen the case on June 19, 2015.<ref>[http://www.judicialwatch.org/document-archive/court-order-state-department-01363-2/ Court order reopening case] (June 19, 2015).</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/19/idUSnMKWv47gXa+1c2+MKW20150619 Judicial Watch Statement in Response to Federal Court Reopening Lawsuit Seeking Information on Top Clinton Aide Huma Abedin] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924220619/http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/19/idUSnMKWv47gXa+1c2+MKW20150619 |date=September 24, 2015 }}, Judicial Watch (June 19, 2015).</ref>\n\nOn July 21, 2015, Judge Sullivan issued supplemental discovery orders, including one that Clinton, Abedin, and former Deputy Secretary of State [[Cheryl Mills]] disclose any required information they had not disclosed already, and promise under oath that they had done so, including a description of the extent Abedin and Mills had used Clinton's email server for official government business.<ref name=politico1>{{cite news|last1=Gerstein|first1=Josh|title=Judge wants Clinton certification on emails|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/08/judge-wants-clinton-to-certify-shes-turned-over-some-211652.html|accessdate=August 5, 2015|publisher=Politico|date=August 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=CBS>{{cite news|last1=Flores|first1=Reena|title=Judge wants Clinton confirmation on State Department emails|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/judge-wants-clinton-confirmation-on-state-department-emails/|accessdate=August 5, 2015|publisher=CBS News|date=August 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2015, Clinton filed her declaration, stating \"I have directed that all my emails on clintonemail.com in my custody that were or potentially were federal records be provided to the Department of State,\" and that as a result of this directive, 55,000 pages of emails were produced to the Department on December 5, 2014.<ref name=\"Clinton Declaration\"/><ref name=NYT81015>{{cite news|author1=Michael S. Schmidt|title=All Emails Were Provided, Hillary Clinton Says in Statement|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/us/politics/all-emails-were-provided-hillary-clinton-says-in-statement.html|accessdate=August 11, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=August 10, 2015|quote=I have directed that all my emails on clintonemail.com in my custody that were or potentially were federal records be provided to the Department of State, and on information and belief, this has been done}}</ref><ref name=\"HeldermanConfirmation\"/> She said in her statement that Abedin did have an email account through clintonemail.com that \"was used at times for government business,\" but that Mills did not.<ref name=\"Clinton Declaration\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/r/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2015/08/10/National-Politics/Graphics/HRC%208-10.pdf Clinton Declaration] (filed August 10, 2015).</ref><ref name=NYT81015/><ref name=\"HeldermanConfirmation\">Rosalind S. Helderman, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/hillary-clinton-swears-i-turned-over-all-my-required-e-mails/2015/08/10/36084f6a-3f8c-11e5-bfe3-ff1d8549bfd2_story.html Hillary Clinton swears: I turned over all my required e-mails], ''The Washington Post'', August 10, 2015.</ref> The statement was filed as Clinton faced questions over fifteen emails in exchanges with Blumenthal that were not among the emails she gave to the department the previous year. She did not address the matter of those emails in the statement.<ref name=NYT81015/> On September 25, 2015, several additional emails from her private server<ref name=CNN10252015>{{cite news|last1=Labott|first1=Elise|last2=Levitt|first2=Ross|title=New Hillary Clinton email chain discovered|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/09/25/politics/hillary-clinton-emails-david-petraeus-benghazi|accessdate=September 28, 2015|publisher=CNN|date=September 25, 2015}}</ref> surfaced which she had not provided to the State Department.<ref name=CNN10252015/><ref name=AP10252015>{{cite news|last1=Klapper|first1=Bradley|title=Officials: More work emails from Clinton's private account|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/f80adbe482e14366ad1cec38f597db86/officials-more-work-emails-clintons-private-account|accessdate=September 28, 2015|agency=Associated Press|date=September 25, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Guardian10252015>{{cite news|last1=Woolf|first1=Nicky|title=Officials uncover two chains of emails Hillary Clinton didn't turn over|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/sep/25/hillary-clinton-email-chain-discovered-david-petraeus|accessdate=September 28, 2015|work=The Guardian|date=September 25, 2015}}</ref> These emails between Clinton and General [[David Petraeus]], discussing personnel matters, were part of an email chain that started on a different email account before her tenure as Secretary of State,<ref name=CNN10252015/><ref name=AP10252015/><ref name=Guardian10252015/> but continued onto her private server in late January 2009 after she had taken office.<ref name=CNN10252015/><ref name=AP10252015/><ref name=Guardian10252015/> The existence of these emails also called into question Clinton's previous statement that she did not use the server before March 18, 2009.<ref name=NYT10252015>{{cite news|last1=Schmidt|first1=Michael|title=String of Emails Raises Questions About When Hillary Clinton Began Using Personal Account|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/26/us/politics/string-of-emails-raises-questions-about-when-hillary-clinton-began-using-personal-account.html|accessdate=September 28, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=September 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Judge Sullivan issued a discovery order in the case, ruling that [[Deposition (law)|depositions]] of State Department officials and top Clinton aides were to proceed.<ref>Hsu, Spenser S. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/us-judge-weighs-deeper-probe-into-clintons-private-email-system/2016/02/23/9c27412a-d997-11e5-81ae-7491b9b9e7df_story.html?tid=pm_pop_b U.S. judge orders discovery to go forward over Clinton\u2019s private email system], ''The Washington Post'', February 23, 2016.</ref> On May 26, 2016, Judicial Watch released the transcript of the deposition of Lewis Lukens,<ref>[http://www.judicialwatch.org/document-archive/jw-v-state-lukens-testimony-01363/ JW v. State Lukens Testimony 01363] (May 26, 2016).</ref> on May 31, 2016, the transcript of Cheryl Mills,<ref>[http://www.judicialwatch.org/document-archive/jw-v-state-mills-deposition-01363/ JW v State Mills deposition 01363].</ref> on June 7, 2016, the transcript of Ambassador Stephen Mull,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.judicialwatch.org/press-room/press-releases/clinton-email-update-judicial-watch-releases-clinton-email-deposition-testimony-amb-stephen-mull-former-executive-secretary-state-department|title=Clinton Email Update: Judicial Watch Releases Clinton Email Deposition Testimony of Amb. Stephen Mull, Former Executive Secretary for State Department \u2013 Judicial Watch|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> and on June 9, 2016, Karin Lang, Director of Executive Secretariat Staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.judicialwatch.org/press-room/press-releases/clinton-email-update-judicial-watch-releases-clinton-email-deposition-testimony-karen-lang-director-executive-secretariat-staff/|title=Clinton Email Update: Judicial Watch Releases Clinton Email Deposition Testimony of Karin Lang, Director, Executive Secretariat Staff \u2013 Judicial Watch|publisher=judicialwatch.org|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe testimony of Clarence Finney, who worked in the department responsible for [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|FOIA]] searches, said that he first became curious about Clinton's email setup after seeing the [[Texts from Hillary]] meme on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2016/06/hillary-clinton-emails-probe-blackberry-224154|title=Clinton BlackBerry photo led to State official's query about email account|work=Politico|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=June 11, 2016|first=Josh|last=Gerstein}}</ref>\n\n===''Jason Leopold v. U.S. Department of State''===\nIn November 2014, [[Jason Leopold]] of ''[[Vice News]]'' made a Freedom of Information Act request for Clinton's State Department records,<ref name=\"Brennan on Leopold\"/><ref name=\"Gerstein on Leopold\"/> and, on January 25, 2015, filed a lawsuit in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia seeking to compel production of responsive documents.<ref name=\"Brennan on Leopold\">Brennan, Margaret & Paula Reid, [http://www.cbsnews.com/news/state-dept-to-comply-with-court-order-on-hillary-clintons-emails/ State Dept. to comply with court order on Hillary Clinton's emails], CBS News, May 19, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"Gerstein on Leopold\">Gerstein, Josh. [http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/03/feds-fight-hillary-clintonfocused-email-lawsuit-204672.html Feds fight Hillary Clinton-focused email lawsuit], Politico.com, March 28, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://images.politico.com/global/2015/03/28/leopoldstatestatrep150327.pdf Joint Status Report Regarding Schedule] (filed March 27, 2015) (\"Plaintiff Jason Leopold initiated this Freedom of Information Act ('FOIA') lawsuit against Defendant U.S. Department of State on January 25, 2015. (ECF No. 1). The Department of State answered the complaint on March 2, 2015 (ECF No. 7)\").</ref> After some dispute between Leopold and the State Department over the request, U.S. District Judge [[Rudolph Contreras]] ordered rolling production and release of the emails on a schedule set by the State Department.<ref name=\"Brennan & Reid\">Margaret Brennan & Paula Reid, [http://www.cbsnews.com/news/state-dept-to-comply-with-court-order-on-hillary-clintons-emails \"State Dept. to comply with court order on Hillary Clinton's emails\"], [[CBS News]], May 19, 2015.</ref><ref>Andrew Zajac & Billy House, [https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2015/05/19/judge-orders-rolling-release-clinton-state-department-mail/WxUyky3HdtJJFBob9VG82O/story.html Judge orders rolling release of Clinton's State Department e-mail], Bloomberg News, May 20, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"Leopold May 19\">Jason Leopold, [https://news.vice.com/article/judge-orders-state-department-to-release-clinton-emails-on-rolling-basis \"Judge Orders State Department to Release Clinton Emails on Rolling Basis\"], ''Vice News'', May 19, 2015.</ref>\n\nOver the next several months, the State Department completed production of 30,068 emails, which were released in 14 batches, with the final batch released on February 29, 2016.<ref>Myers, Steven Lee & Julie Hirschfeld Davis. [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/01/us/politics/last-batch-of-hillary-clintons-emails-is-released.html?_r=0 Last Batch of Hillary Clinton\u2019s Emails Is Released], ''The New York Times'', February 29, 2016.</ref> Both the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' and [[WikiLeaks]] independently set up search engines for anyone who would like to search through the Clinton emails released by the State Department.<ref>[http://graphics.wsj.com/hillary-clinton-email-documents/ \"Search Hillary Clinton\u2019s Emails\"], ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''. Retrieved April 17, 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/wikileaks-publishes-searchable-archive-of-clinton-emails/article/2586017 \"WikiLeaks publishes searchable archive of Clinton emails\"], ''[[Washington Examiner]]''. Retrieved May 9, 2016.</ref>\n\nIt was revealed in October 2017 that during the 2016 US Presidential election, Cambridge Analytica funder and GOP mega-donor [[Rebekah Mercer]] had proposed creating a searchable data base for Hillary Clinton emails in the public domain and then forwarded this suggestion to several people, including Cambridge Analytica CEO [[Alexander Nix]], who personally emailed a request to Julian Assange for Clinton's emails.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/10/27/politics/rebekah-mercer-cambridge-analytica-clinton-emails/index.html|title=GOP megadonor requested Trump's data firm organize hacked Clinton emails|author=Dana Bash and Marshall Cohen|publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> Assange responded to the report by saying he denied Nix's request.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/25/us/julian-assange-wikileaks-trump.html|title=Assange Says WikiLeaks Rejected Request by Data Firm Tied to Trump|first=Nicholas|last=Confessore|date=October 25, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2018|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n\nThe emails showed that Blumenthal communicated with Clinton while Secretary on a variety of issues including Benghazi.<ref name=LATimes2>Halper, Evan and Michael A. Memoli, [http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-hillary-clinton-state-emails-20150629-story.html \"More of Hillary Clinton's emails say little about State Department tenure\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', June 30, 2015.</ref><ref name=NYT2>Baker, Peter & Steve Ederjune, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/01/us/politics/new-trove-of-hillary-clintons-emails-highlight-workaday-tasks-at-the-state-department.htm New Trove of Hillary Clinton's Emails Highlights Workaday Tasks at the State Department], ''The New York Times'', June 30, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"NJ 3d Batch\">Schultheis, Emily & Lauren Fox, [http://www.nationaljournal.com/2016-elections/state-dept-releases-more-hillary-clinton-emails-20150731 State Department Releases More Hillary Clinton Emails] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821141056/http://www.nationaljournal.com/2016-elections/state-dept-releases-more-hillary-clinton-emails-20150731 |date=August 21, 2015}}, ''National Journal'', July 31, 2015.</ref><ref>Kumar, Anita & Greg Gordon & Marisa Taylor, [http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/election/presidential-election/article31345289.html Investigators now examining 305 Clinton emails for classified information], McClatchy Washington Bureau (August 17, 2015).</ref><!-- preserve some refs\n<ref name=\"UPI First Batch\">Danielle Haynes, [http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2015/05/22/First-batch-of-Hillary-Clinton-emails-on-Benghazi-released/7431432313084/ First batch of Hillary Clinton emails on Benghazi released], UPI.com, May 22, 2015.</ref><ref name=BBC32853708>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-32853708|title=First set of Hillary Clinton emails published online|work=BBC News|date=May 22, 2015|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref><ref name=WP3>Gearan, Anne & Colby Itkowitz, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/a-glimpse-at-hillary-clintons-e-mails-from-celebrities-to-politicians/2015/06/30/ae0b96de-1f52-11e5-aeb9-a411a84c9d55_story.html \"A glimpse at Hillary Clinton's e-mails, from celebrities to politicians\"], ''The Washington Post'', July 1, 2015.</ref><ref name=NYT2 /><ref name=NJ2>Geman, Ben, [http://www.nationaljournal.com/2016-elections/here-are-the-3-000-pages-of-hillary-clinton-s-emails-just-released-by-the-state-department-20150630 Here Are the 3,000 Pages of Hillary Clinton\u2019s Emails Just Released by the State Department], ''National Journal'', June 30, 2015.</ref>-->\n\n===''Associated Press v. U.S. Department of State''===\nOn March 11, 2015, the day after Clinton acknowledged her private email account, the Associated Press (AP) filed suit against the State Department regarding multiple FOIA requests over the past five years. The requests were for various emails and other documents from Clinton's time as secretary of state and were still unfulfilled at the time.<ref name=\"APSuitFiled\">Associated Press, [http://www.cbsnews.com/news/associated-press-sues-state-department-for-hillary-clinton-emails/ Associated Press sues State Department for Hillary Clinton emails], CBS News, March 11, 2015.</ref><ref>[https://cryptome.org/2015/03/ap-001.pdf Complaint], ''Associated Press v. U.S. Department of State'' (filed March 11, 2015).</ref><ref name=\"Leon Schedule\">Eric Tucker, [http://bigstory.ap.org/article/17bb3935546b422ba4246e934e00d8d7/clinton-records-judge-sets-schedule-release-ap Clinton records: Judge sets schedule for release to AP] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811004955/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/17bb3935546b422ba4246e934e00d8d7/clinton-records-judge-sets-schedule-release-ap |date=August 11, 2015 }}, Associated Press, August 7, 2015.</ref> The State Department said that a high volume of FOIA requests and a large backlog had caused the delay.<ref name=\"APSuitFiled\"/><ref name=\"Gerstein July 20 Hearing\">Josh Gerstein, [http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/07/judge-slams-state-department-over-hillary-clintonrelated-210878.html Judge slams State Department over Hillary Clinton-related records], Politico.com, July 20, 2015.</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2015, U.S. District Judge [[Richard J. Leon]] reacted angrily to what he said was \"the State Department for four years dragging their feet.\"<ref name=\"Gerstein July 20 Hearing\"/> Leon said that \"even the least ambitious bureaucrat\" could process the request faster than the State Department was doing.<ref>David Francis, [https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/07/30/judge-the-least-ambitious-bureaucrat-could-process-clintons-personal-emails-faster \"Judge: The 'Least Ambitious' Bureaucrat Could Process Clinton's Personal Emails Faster\"], ''Foreign Policy'', July 30, 2015.</ref>\n\nOn August 7, 2015, Leon issued an order setting a stringent schedule for the State Department to provide the AP with the requested documents over the next eight months.<ref name=\"Leon Schedule\"/> The order issued by Leon did not include the 55,000 pages of Clinton emails the State Department scheduled to be released in the Leopold case, or take into account 20 boxes given to the State Department by [[Philippe Reines]], a former Clinton senior adviser.<ref name=\"Leon Schedule\"/>\n\n===Other suits and coordination of email cases===\nIn September 2015, the State Department filed a motion in court seeking to consolidate and coordinate the large number of Freedom of Information Act lawsuits relating to Clinton and Clinton-related emails. There were at the time at least three dozen lawsuits pending, before 17 different judges.<ref>Josh Gerstein, [http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/09/feds-move-to-consolidate-lawsuits-over-hillary-clinton-emails-213228 Feds move to consolidate lawsuits over Hillary Clinton emails], ''Politico'', September 1, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"TauCoordination\">Tau, Byron, [https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2015/10/08/court-declines-to-consolidate-clinton-emails-lawsuits/ Court Declines to Consolidate Clinton Emails Lawsuits], ''The Wall Street Journal'', October 8, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn a [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]] order issued on October 8, 2015, Chief U.S. District Judge [[Richard W. Roberts]] wrote that the cases did not meet the usual criteria for consolidation but: \"The judges who have been randomly assigned to these cases have been and continue to be committed to informal coordination so as to avoid unnecessary inefficiencies and confusion, and the parties are also urged to meet and confer to assist in coordination.\"<ref name=\"TauCoordination\"/>\n\nIn 2015, Judicial Watch and the Cause of Action Institute filed two lawsuits seeking a court order to compel the Department of State and the [[National Archives and Records Administration]] to recover emails from Clinton's server. In January 2016, these two suits (which were consolidated because they involved the same issues) were dismissed as [[Mootness|moot]] by U.S. District Judge [[James Boasberg]], because the government was already working to recover and preserve these emails.<ref>[http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b219d2da39454b799b653187d6ab2831/judge-dismisses-pair-lawsuits-arising-clinton-emails Judge dismisses pair of lawsuits arising from Clinton emails] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404032537/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b219d2da39454b799b653187d6ab2831/judge-dismisses-pair-lawsuits-arising-clinton-emails |date=April 4, 2016 }}, Associated Press, January 11, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the [[Republican National Committee]] filed four new [[complaint (law)|complaints]] in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia stemming from Freedom of Information Act requests it had filed the previous year. These new filings brought the total number of civil suits over access to Clinton's records pending in federal court to at least 38.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2016-03-15/gop-files-more-lawsuits-seeking-hillary-clinton-records|title=GOP files a flurry of new lawsuits seeking reams of government documents related to Clinton's tenure as secretary of state|date=March 15, 2016|work=[[U.S. News and World Report]]|first1=Michael|last1=Biesecker|agency=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, in response to the Republican National Committee's complaints filed in March 2016, the State Department estimates it will take 75 years to complete the review of documents which are responsive to the complaints.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2016/06/07/estimate-of-75-years-to-process-clinton-aides-email-not-an-outlandish-estimation|title=Estimate of 75 Years to Release Clinton Aides' Email 'Not an Outlandish Estimation'|last=Tau|first=Byron|website=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref> It has been observed that a delay of this nature would cause the documents to remain out of public view longer than the vast majority of classified documents which must be declassified after 25 years.<ref name=\"NYT20061221\">{{cite news|author=Scott Shane|title=U.S. to Declassify Secrets at Age 25|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/21/washington/21declassify.html|work=[[New York Times]]|date=December 21, 2006|accessdate=September 16, 2018|quote=Secret documents 25 years old or older will lose their classified status without so much as the stroke of a pen, unless agencies have sought exemptions on the ground that the material remains secret.}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2016 Democratic National Committee email leak]]\n* [[Clinton Foundation\u2013State Department controversy]]\n* [[White House FBI files controversy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hillary Rodham Clinton email use as United States Secretary of State}}\n\n* [https://www.archives.gov/press/press-releases/2016/nr16-29.html Press release] by the [[National Archives and Records Administration]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160505102708/http://thompsontimeline.com/The_Clinton_Email_Scandal_Timeline The Clinton Email Scandal Timeline] created by the author of [[The Terror Timeline]]\n* [https://foia.state.gov/Search/Results.aspx?collection=Clinton_Email Secretary Clinton Emails at the United States Department of State website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160311140652/https://www.hillaryclinton.com/briefing/factsheets/2015/07/13/email-facts/ The Facts About Hillary Clinton\u2019s Emails] at the Hillary Clinton campaign website\n* [https://vault.fbi.gov/hillary-r.-clinton 