{"title_page": "Amati Quartet", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Amati Quartet\n| image             = \n| alt         = \n| caption        = \n| image_size        = \n| background      = classical_ensemble\n| alias           = \n| origin          = [[Saskatoon]], Saskatchewan, Canada\n| genre           = \n| years_active    = {{Start date|2003-2018}}\n| label           = \n| associated_acts = \n| website             = www.amatiquartet.usask.ca/\n| current_members = \n| past_members    = \n}}\nThe '''Amati Quartet''' was a [[string quartet]], associated with the [[University of Saskatchewan]] in [[Saskatoon]], Canada.The ensemble performed with four instruments made by the [[Amati|Amati family]] of [[luthiers]], of [[Cremona]] Italy.\n\n==Acquisition of the Instruments==\nThe Amati instruments, two [[violin]]s, a [[viola]] and a [[cello]], were acquired in 1959, from [[Kindersley]] farmer and collector Stephen Kolbinson (1888-1986), who sold them to the university at the urging of his friend [[Murray Adaskin]], then the director of the music department. The sale price was [[Canadian dollar|C$]]20,000 (considerably less than their 1959 value), but both men held the deep desire that the instruments be shared with the people of [[Saskatchewan]]. In 2016, the combined value of the instruments exceeded C$3&nbsp;million.\n\n==The First Amati Quartet (1968-1971)==\nIn 1968, the first Amati String Quartet was founded by Murray Adaskin and three other faculty members of the University of Saskatchewan: Norma Lee Bisha (1926-2010)  (second violin), Michael Bowie (viola), and Edward Bisha (cello). It gave its first concert on 2 February 1969. Later that same year, Robert Klose was named second violin and Norma Lee Bisha replaced Michael Bowie. The personnel remained stable until the group was supplanted in 1971 by the Canadian Arts Trio after fewer than 10 formal concerts. The quartet was too short-lived to develop a wide repertoire or a distinctive style.<ref>[https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/amati-quartet-emc]</ref>\n\nFrom 1992 to 1998, the instruments were on loan to the [[University of Victoria]]'s Lafayette String Quartet, and were then returned to the University of Saskatchewan, held in storage and rarely used in performance. In 2003, in response to growing calls for the instruments to be heard, the Amati Quartet was established, with musicians who were already performing under the name The Cole Quartet.\n\n==The Amati Quartet (2003-)==\nThe Amati Quartet in Residence was established in August 2003 with Marla Cole (first violin), Michael Swan (second violin), Geoff Cole (viola) and Linda Bardutz (cello). In 2004, Luke Hnenny became second violinist and Peter Hedlin replaced Bardutz as cellist. The Amati Quartet performed a yearly recital series, and played at various University of Saskatchewan events. In May 2005, it performed for Queen [[Elizabeth II]] during her visit in honour of Saskatchewan\u2019s 100th anniversary, and  undertook a project to perform all of [[Joseph Haydn]]\u2019s string quartets.<ref>[https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/amati-quartet-emc]</ref>\n\n==''Passion for Haydn'', ''From the Heart''==\nIt was Marla Cole's wish that the quartet record an album. After she was diagnosed with breast cancer, she was able to secure financial help from The Cameco Riders Touchdown for Dreams program, a partnership between [[Cameco]], the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]], the Saskatchewan Cancer Agency, and the Cancer Foundation of Saskatchewan.<ref>[https://www.cameco.com/community/stories/touchdown-for-dreams-archive]</ref>. The album ''Passion for Haydn'' was released in 2016. Cole passed away in 2017<ref>[https://thestarphoenix.com/entertainment/local-arts/saskatoon-loses-passionate-violinist-marla-cole/]</ref>; in 2018, the quartet released the album ''From the Heart'', which is dedicated to her.<ref>[https://thestarphoenix.com/entertainment/local-arts/amati-quartets-new-album-dedicated-to-marla-cole/]</ref>\n\n==Final Concert, 2018==\nIn June of 2018, the Amati Quartet played its last concert, which was a fundraiser for the Marla Cole Memorial Fund<ref>[https://www.saskatooncommunityfoundation.ca/posts/fund/marla-cole-memorial-fund/]</ref>. The musicians were her husband Geoff Cole (viola), Rudy Sternadel (violin), Terence Sturge (cello) and, in Marla's place, violinist Sam Milner. \nThe instruments remain in the possession of the university.\n\n==Instruments==\nThe University of Saskatchewan instruments are the only set in Canada made by the [[Amati|Amati family]].\nThe 1937 violin previously belonged to the Australian concert violinist [[Daisy Kennedy]] (1893-1981). \nThe viola\u2019s back bears the painted crest, or [[Coat of Arms]], of the [[House of Borghese]], which originally commissioned it. \n* Violin 1637, [[Nicola Amati]] (Nicolo)\n* Violin 1627, [[Antonio Amati|Antonio]] & [[Girolamo Amati]]\n* Viola 1607, [[Antonio Amati|Antonio]] & [[Girolamo Amati]]\n* Cello 1690, Girolamo Amati II, aka Hieronymus II\n\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web | author=Lorraine Omness | title=About the Amati instruments | url=http://amatiquartet.usask.ca/instruments | publisher=University of Saskatchewan | year=2008 | accessdate=2008-04-29}}\n* {{cite web | author=U of S Archives | title=1969: Amati Quartet Makes its Debut | work=Deo et Patriae | url=http://scaa.usask.ca/gallery/uofs_events/articles/1969.php | publisher=University of Saskatchewan | year=2008 | accessdate=2008-04-29}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.amatiquartet.usask.ca/ Amati Quartet webpage]\n\n{{String quartets|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Amati instruments]]\n[[Category:Canadian string quartets]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Saskatoon]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Saskatchewan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Amati Quartet\n| image             = \n| alt         = \n| caption        = \n| image_size        = \n| background      = classical_ensemble\n| alias           = \n| origin          = [[Saskatoon]], Saskatchewan, Canada\n| genre           = \n| years_active    = {{Start date|2003-2018}}\n| label           = \n| associated_acts = \n| website             = www.amatiquartet.usask.ca/\n| current_members = \n| past_members    = \n}}\nThe '''Amati Quartet''' was a [[string quartet]], associated with the [[University of Saskatchewan]] in [[Saskatoon]], Canada.The ensemble performs with four instruments made by the [[Amati|Amati family]] of [[luthiers]], of [[Cremona]] Italy.\n\n==Acquisition of the Instruments==\nThe Amati instruments, two [[violin]]s, a [[viola]] and a [[cello]], were acquired in 1959, from [[Kindersley]] farmer and collector Stephen Kolbinson (1888-1986), who sold them to the university at the urging of his friend [[Murray Adaskin]], then the director of the music department. The sale price was [[Canadian dollar|C$]]20,000 (considerably less than their 1959 value), but both men held the deep desire that the instruments be shared with the people of [[Saskatchewan]]. In 2016, the combined value of the instruments exceeded C$3&nbsp;million.\n\n==The First Amati Quartet (1968-1971)==\nIn 1968, the first Amati String Quartet was founded by Murray Adaskin and three other faculty members of the University of Saskatchewan: Norma Lee Bisha (1926-2010)  (second violin), Michael Bowie (viola), and Edward Bisha (cello). It gave its first concert on 2 February 1969. Later that same year, Robert Klose was named second violin and Norma Lee Bisha replaced Michael Bowie. The personnel remained stable until the group was supplanted in 1971 by the Canadian Arts Trio after fewer than 10 formal concerts. The quartet was too short-lived to develop a wide repertoire or a distinctive style.<ref>[https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/amati-quartet-emc]</ref>\n\nFrom 1992 to 1998, the instruments were on loan to the [[University of Victoria]]'s Lafayette String Quartet, and were then returned to the University of Saskatchewan, held in storage and rarely used in performance. In 2003, in response to growing calls for the instruments to be heard, the Amati Quartet was established, with musicians who were already performing under the name The Cole Quartet.\n\n==The Amati Quartet (2003-)==\nThe Amati Quartet in Residence was established in August 2003 with Marla Cole (first violin), Michael Swan (second violin), Geoff Cole (viola) and Linda Bardutz (cello). In 2004, Luke Hnenny became second violinist and Peter Hedlin replaced Bardutz as cellist. The Amati Quartet performed a yearly recital series, and played at various University of Saskatchewan events. In May 2005, it performed for Queen [[Elizabeth II]] during her visit in honour of Saskatchewan\u2019s 100th anniversary, and  undertook a project to perform all of [[Joseph Haydn]]\u2019s string quartets.<ref>[https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/amati-quartet-emc]</ref>\n\n==''Passion for Haydn'', ''From the Heart''==\nIt was Marla Cole's wish that the quartet record an album. After she was diagnosed with breast cancer, she was able to secure financial help from The Cameco Riders Touchdown for Dreams program, a partnership between [[Cameco]], the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]], the Saskatchewan Cancer Agency, and the Cancer Foundation of Saskatchewan.<ref>[https://www.cameco.com/community/stories/touchdown-for-dreams-archive]</ref>. The album ''Passion for Haydn'' was released in 2016. Cole passed away in 2017<ref>[https://thestarphoenix.com/entertainment/local-arts/saskatoon-loses-passionate-violinist-marla-cole/]</ref>; in 2018, the quartet released the album ''From the Heart'', which is dedicated to her.<ref>[https://thestarphoenix.com/entertainment/local-arts/amati-quartets-new-album-dedicated-to-marla-cole/]</ref>\n\n==Final Concert, 2018==\nIn June of 2018, the Amati Quartet played its last concert, which was a fundraiser for the Marla Cole Memorial Fund<ref>[https://www.saskatooncommunityfoundation.ca/posts/fund/marla-cole-memorial-fund/]</ref>. The musicians were her husband Geoff Cole (viola), Rudy Sternadel (violin), Terence Sturge (cello) and, in Marla's place, violinist Sam Milner. \nThe instruments remain in the possession of the university.\n\n==Instruments==\nThe University of Saskatchewan instruments are the only set in Canada made by the [[Amati|Amati family]].\nThe 1937 violin previously belonged to the Australian concert violinist [[Daisy Kennedy]] (1893-1981). \nThe viola\u2019s back bears the painted crest, or [[Coat of Arms]], of the [[House of Borghese]], which originally commissioned it. \n* Violin 1637, [[Nicola Amati]] (Nicolo)\n* Violin 1627, [[Antonio Amati|Antonio]] & [[Girolamo Amati]]\n* Viola 1607, [[Antonio Amati|Antonio]] & [[Girolamo Amati]]\n* Cello 1690, Girolamo Amati II, aka Hieronymus II\n\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web | author=Lorraine Omness | title=About the Amati instruments | url=http://amatiquartet.usask.ca/instruments | publisher=University of Saskatchewan | year=2008 | accessdate=2008-04-29}}\n* {{cite web | author=U of S Archives | title=1969: Amati Quartet Makes its Debut | work=Deo et Patriae | url=http://scaa.usask.ca/gallery/uofs_events/articles/1969.php | publisher=University of Saskatchewan | year=2008 | accessdate=2008-04-29}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.amatiquartet.usask.ca/ Amati Quartet webpage]\n\n{{String quartets|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Amati instruments]]\n[[Category:Canadian string quartets]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Saskatoon]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Saskatchewan]]\n", "name_user": "LJA123", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amati_Quartet"}
{"title_page": "Bang Bang Busters", "text_new": "{{short description|Video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title         = Bang Bang Busters\n|image         = Neo Geo AES Bang Bang Busters cover art.jpg\n|caption       = North American Neo Geo AES cover art\n|developer     = [[Visco Corporation]]\n|publisher     = Neo Conception International<br />JoshProd <small>(Dreamcast)</small>\n|director      = Don Gabacho\n|producer      = Tetsuo Akiyama\n|designer      = Ebi Taisyo<br />Tel.Y\n|programmer    = Kenichi Imamatsu<br />Kentaro Masakane\n|artist        = Hirofumi Mawatari<br />Kaoru Ishizawa<br />Makoto Nobetani\n|writer        = Ebi Taisyo\n|composer      = Kiyoshi Kusatsu\n|platforms     = [[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[Dreamcast]], [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo AES]], [[Neo Geo CD]]\n|released      ={{collapsible list|title=[[2010 in video gaming|2010]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|'''Neo Geo AES'''{{vgrelease|JP|December 2010|NA|April [[2011 in video gaming|2011]]}} '''Arcade'''{{vgrelease|WW|15 August 2011}} '''Neo Geo CD'''{{vgrelease|WW|June [[2012 in video gaming|2012]]}} '''Dreamcast'''{{vgrelease|EU|July [[2018 in video gaming|2018]]|NA|November 2018}}}}\n|genre         = [[Platform game|Platform]]\n|modes         = {{flatlist|\n*[[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n*[[Cooperative gameplay|Co-op]]}}\n|cabinet       = [[Arcade cabinet#Upright cabinets|Upright]]\n|arcade system = [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo MVS]]\n|cpu           = [[Motorola 68000|M68000]] (@ 12 [[Hertz|MHz]]),<br />[[Zilog Z80|Z80A]] (@ 4 MHz)\n|sound         = [[Yamaha YM2610|YM2610]] (@ 8 MHz)<ref name=\"s16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=869&page=1#18488|title=SNK NeoGeo MVS Hardware (SNK)|website=system16.com|accessdate=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113012506/http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=869&page=1#18488|archive-date=2019-01-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|display       = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 304 \u00d7 224 pixels (Horizontal), 4096 [[color]]s\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Bang Bang Busters'''''|\u30d0\u30f3 \u30d0\u30f3 \u30d0\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ba|''Ban Ban Basut\u0101zu''|also known as '''''Bang Busters''''' and '''''Bang\u00b2 Busters'''''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[2010 in video gaming|2010]] [[Platform game|platform]] [[video game]] developed by [[Visco Corporation]] and originally published by Neo Conception International for the [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo AES]] (home).<ref>{{cite web|last=Reynolds|first=Stuart|url=http://www.neogeoforlife.com/articles.php?article_id=5|title=Neo Geo Prototypes|website=neogeoforlife.com|date=December 25, 2006|access-date=2019-11-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231071451/http://www.neogeoforlife.com/articles.php?article_id=5|archive-date=December 31, 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"nci\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bang2busters.com/faqs.html|title=BANG 2 BUSTERS'S FAQ  !|publisher=Neo Conception International|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110508123356/http://www.bang2busters.com/faqs.html|archive-date=2011-05-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ah2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=bang2-busters-model-ngh-071&page=detail&id=48105|title=Bang\u00b2 Busters [Model NGH-071] (AES)|website=arcade-history.com|accessdate=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420233401/http://www.arcade-history.com/?n=bang2-busters-model-ngh-071&page=detail&id=48105|archive-date=2016-04-20|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"gc\">{{cite web|last=Bravo|first=Roberto|url=https://www.gamercafe.cl/2010/12/10/neo-geo-hardcore-fans-rejoice-%C2%A1%C2%A1bang-bang-busters-saldra-oficialmente-en-aes/|title=Neo Geo hardcore fans rejoice: \u00a1\u00a1Bang Bang Busters saldr\u00e1 OFICIALMENTE en AES!!|publisher=Gamercafe|date=10 December 2010|access-date=2019-12-26|language=es}}</ref> Taking place on the [[fictional planet]] of Palua in the [[future]], where an evil being known as Honey plots to have his own [[galaxy]], players assume the role of Lazy and Refia in order to prevent Honey and his followers from realizing their plan. Its [[gameplay]] mainly consists of platforming mixed with [[Action game|action]] elements using a main two-button configuration.\n\nHeaded by Visco founder Tetsuo Akiyama and ''[[Breakers (1996 video game)|Breakers]]'' [[Video game producer|producer]] Don Gabacho, ''Bang Bang Busters'' was created by most of the same team that previously worked on several projects at Visco. Though it was initially launched for the Neo Geo AES, the game was later released for both Neo Geo MVS (arcade) and [[Neo Geo CD]] in [[2011 in video gaming|2011]] and [[2012 in video gaming|2012]] respectively, as well for the [[Dreamcast]] in [[2018 in video gaming|2018]].<ref name=\"BBBmb\">{{cite web|author=Sciere|url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/arcade/bang-busters/release-info|title=Bang\u00b2 Busters (2011) Arcade release dates|work=[[MobyGames]]|publisher=Blue Flame Labs|date=July 25, 2019|access-date=2019-12-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225172438/https://www.mobygames.com/game/arcade/bang-busters/release-info|archive-date=2020-02-25|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ah1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=bang2-busters-model-ngm-071&page=detail&id=3846|title=Bang\u00b2 Busters [Model NGM-071] (MVS)|website=arcade-history.com|accessdate=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812080522/http://www.arcade-history.com/?n=bang2-busters-model-ngm-071&page=detail&id=3846|archive-date=2016-08-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBNGCD\">{{cite web|last=Buchanan|first=Adam|url=http://www.retrocollect.com/News/bang-bang-busters-released-on-the-neo-geo-cd.html|title=Unreleased Neo Geo Prototype Bang Bang Busters Released For The Neo Geo CD|website=retrocollect.com|date=June 28, 2012|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712065023/http://www.retrocollect.com/News/bang-bang-busters-released-on-the-neo-geo-cd.html|archive-date=July 12, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBDCa\">{{cite web|last=McMurray|first=Jennifer|url=http://www.dreamcast-scene.com/news/bang%C2%B2-busters-is-coming-to-the-dreamcast/|title=Bang\u00b2 Busters Is Coming To The Dreamcast|work=Dreamcast-Scene|publisher=[[WordPress.com]]|date=May 9, 2018|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013085019/http://www.dreamcast-scene.com/news/bang%C2%B2-busters-is-coming-to-the-dreamcast/|archive-date=2018-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBDCb\">{{cite web|author=doceggfan|url=http://www.thedreamcastjunkyard.co.uk/2019/02/the-dreamcast-games-of-2018.html|title=The Dreamcast Games Of 2018|website=www.thedreamcastjunkyard.co.uk|date=February 2019|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617032642/http://www.thedreamcastjunkyard.co.uk/2019/02/the-dreamcast-games-of-2018.html|archive-date=2019-06-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:NEOGEO Bang Bang Busters (Bang\u00b2 Busters).png|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot.]]\n''Bang Bang Busters'' is a platform game similar to ''[[Snow Bros.]]'' and ''[[Nightmare in the Dark]]'', where the players assume control of Lazy (P1) and Refia (P2) across seven stages comprising multiple levels that take place on planet Palua, each with a [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]] at the end that must be fought before progressing any further, in order to stop an evil being known as Honey and his followers before the former has his own galaxy as the main objective.<ref name=\"ah1\"/><ref name=\"BBBAESmanual\">''Bang Bang Busters'' user's manual (Neo Geo AES, US)</ref><ref name=\"BBBDCmanual\">''Bang Bang Busters'' manual (Dreamcast, US)</ref><ref name=\"BBBngp\">{{cite web|last=Pitt|first=Billy|url=http://www.neogeoprotos.com/games/b2b.htm|title=Bang Bang Busters by Visco Games - NEO GEO MVS NGM-071|website=neogeoprotos.com|access-date=2020-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802111011/http://www.neogeoprotos.com/games/b2b.htm|archive-date=2019-08-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBcng\">{{cite web|url=https://www.culturaneogeo.com/protos1|title=Juegos Prototipo - Bang Bang Busters|publisher=Cultura Neo Geo|access-date=2020-02-25|language=es}}</ref>\n\nThe players must throw energy projectiles at enemies to inflate them with air, which is reminiscent of ''[[Dig Dug]]''.<ref name=\"BBBAESmanual\"/><ref name=\"BBBDCmanual\"/><ref name=\"BBBngp\"/> From there, players can grab the inflated enemies to perform a variety of actions such as launching them against other enemies at any direction by holding the attack button, perform a dash throw by double-tapping the [[joystick]] left or right, as well as float above the ground by repeatedly tapping the jump button.<ref name=\"BBBAESmanual\"/><ref name=\"BBBDCmanual\"/> Any enemy inflated with air cannot move until it shakes it off. Defeated enemies may spawn [[power-up]]s and [[Item (gaming)|item]]s like a speed increaser, a [[bomb]] that obliterates any enemy caught in its [[blast radius]], among others.<ref name=\"BBBAESmanual\"/><ref name=\"BBBDCmanual\"/> Players can sustain a number of enemy hits, at the expense of losing power as a penalty, but the [[Game over|game is over]] after taking one last hit unless the players decide to [[Glossary of video game terms#Continue|continue]] playing.\n\n== Development and release ==\n''Bang Bang Busters'' was created by most of the same team that previously worked on several projects at Visco Corporation.<ref name=\"BBBStaffroll\">{{cite video game|title=Bang\u00b2 Busters|developer=[[Visco Corporation]]|publisher=Neo Conception International|date=2000|platform=[[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo AES]]|level=Staff roll}}</ref> Its development was helmed by Visco founder Tetsuo Akiyama and ''Breakers'' producer Don Gabacho, with Yasuhisa Itoi acting as [[supervisor]].<ref name=\"BBBStaffroll\"/> Ebi Taisyo and Tel.Y served as [[Video game designer|designer]], with Taisyo also serving as [[Video game writer|writer]].<ref name=\"BBBStaffroll\"/> [[Video game artist|Artist]]s Hirofumi Mawatari, Makoto Nobetani and Kaoru Ishizawa designed the characters, while Kentaro Masakane and Kenichi Imamatsu were the [[Video game programmer|programmer]]s.<ref name=\"BBBStaffroll\"/> The music was composed by Kiyoshi Kusatsu, while other people also collaborated during development.<ref name=\"BBBStaffroll\"/>\n\n''Bang Bang Busters'' was initially showcased at [[trade show]]s and intended to be released in [[1994 in video gaming|1994]] but it was never released for unknown reasons until 2010, when independent developer and publisher Neo Conception International released the AES version as part of an acquisition deal with Visco in regards to the rights of their [[intellectual properties]].<ref name=\"nci\"/><ref name=\"gc\"/><ref name=\"BBBngp\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3ABeepMD_JP_1993-04.pdf&page=33|title=Mega AM Network - AOU: \u30d3\u30b9\u30b3 - \u30d0\u30f3 \u30d0\u30f3 \u30d0\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ba|magazine=[[:ja:\u30b2\u30fc\u30de\u30ac#BEEP!\u30e1\u30ac\u30c9\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6|Beep! MegaDrive]]|issue=43|publisher=[[SB Creative|SoftBank Creative]]|date=April 1993|page=31|lang=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.culturaneogeo.com/imagenes/entrevistas/nciesp.htm|title=Entrevista a NCI|publisher=Cultura Neo Geo|date=March 2016|accessdate=2019-12-26|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621002035/https://www.culturaneogeo.com/imagenes/entrevistas/nciesp.htm|archive-date=2019-06-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Although its production number during development remained unknown, it was later revealed to be officially assigned with the number 71.<ref name=\"ah2\"/><ref name=\"ah1\"/><ref name=\"BBBngp\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Giles|first=Aaron|url=https://github.com/mamedev/mame/blob/f15313bc070231f7fe13b2b63bf3d0ae55793171/src/mame/arcade.lst|title=arcade.lst|publisher=[[GitHub]]|access-date=2020-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231021824/https://github.com/mamedev/mame/blob/f15313bc070231f7fe13b2b63bf3d0ae55793171/src/mame/arcade.lst|archive-date=2018-12-31|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBngaul\">{{cite web|url=http://castleofcollectibles.com/U-List.txt|title=NEO\u2022GEO AES UNRELEASED LIST|website=castleofcollectibles.com|date=September 5, 2004|access-date=2020-02-25|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316032349/http://castleofcollectibles.com/U-List.txt|archivedate=March 16, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBngpb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.neo-geo.com/forums/showthread.php?117868-NEOGEO-PROTOS-breakdown-list|title=NEOGEO PROTOS breakdown list|website=neo-geo.com|date=April 22, 2005|access-date=2020-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405223836/http://www.neo-geo.com/forums/showthread.php?117868-NEOGEO-PROTOS-breakdown-list|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The title was then launched for Neo Geo MVS in 2011 and later for Neo Geo CD by N.C.I. in 2012.<ref name=\"nci\"/><ref name=\"BBBmb\"/><ref name=\"ah1\"/><ref name=\"BBBNGCD\"/> Years later, an officially licensed port by Visco for the Dreamcast was also released by JoshProd worldwide in 2018.<ref name=\"BBBDCa\"/><ref name=\"BBBDCb\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/dreamcast/238752-bang-bang-busters '' Bang Bang Busters''] at [[GameFAQs]]\n* [https://www.giantbomb.com/bang-bang-busters/3030-40978/ ''Bang Bang Busters''] at [[Giant Bomb]]\n* [https://www.mobygames.com/game/bang-busters ''Bang Bang Busters''] at [[MobyGames]]\n\n{{Neo Geo}}\n{{Portal bar|2010s|Japan|Video games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bang Bang Busters}}\n[[Category:2010 video games]]\n[[Category:Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:Dreamcast games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Neo Geo games]]\n[[Category:Neo Geo CD games]]\n[[Category:Platform games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 1994]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the 1990s]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the future]]\n[[Category:Video games set on fictional planets]]\n[[Category:Visco games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title         = Bang Bang Busters\n|image         = Neo Geo AES Bang Bang Busters cover art.jpg\n|caption       = North American Neo Geo AES cover art\n|developer     = [[Visco Corporation]]\n|publisher     = Neo Conception International<br />JoshProd <small>(Dreamcast)</small>\n|director      = Don Gabacho\n|producer      = Tetsuo Akiyama\n|designer      = Ebi Taisyo<br />Tel.Y\n|programmer    = Kenichi Imamatsu<br />Kentaro Masakane\n|artist        = Hirofumi Mawatari<br />Kaoru Ishizawa<br />Makoto Nobetani\n|writer        = Ebi Taisyo\n|composer      = Kiyoshi Kusatsu\n|platforms     = [[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[Dreamcast]], [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo AES]], [[Neo Geo CD]]\n|released      ={{collapsible list|title=[[2010 in video gaming|2010]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|'''Neo Geo AES'''{{vgrelease|JP|December 2010|NA|April [[2011 in video gaming|2011]]}} '''Arcade'''{{vgrelease|WW|15 August 2011}} '''Neo Geo CD'''{{vgrelease|WW|June [[2012 in video gaming|2012]]}} '''Dreamcast'''{{vgrelease|EU|July [[2018 in video gaming|2018]]|NA|November 2018}}}}\n|genre         = [[Platform game|Platform]]\n|modes         = {{flatlist|\n*[[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n*[[Cooperative gameplay|Co-op]]}}\n|cabinet       = [[Arcade cabinet#Upright cabinets|Upright]]\n|arcade system = [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo MVS]]\n|cpu           = [[Motorola 68000|M68000]] (@ 12 [[Hertz|MHz]]),<br />[[Zilog Z80|Z80A]] (@ 4 MHz)\n|sound         = [[Yamaha YM2610|YM2610]] (@ 8 MHz)<ref name=\"s16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=869&page=1#18488|title=SNK NeoGeo MVS Hardware (SNK)|website=system16.com|accessdate=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113012506/http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=869&page=1#18488|archive-date=2019-01-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|display       = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 304 \u00d7 224 pixels (Horizontal), 4096 [[color]]s\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Bang Bang Busters'''''|\u30d0\u30f3 \u30d0\u30f3 \u30d0\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ba|''Ban Ban Basut\u0101zu''|also known as '''''Bang Busters''''' and '''''Bang\u00b2 Busters'''''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[2010 in video gaming|2010]] [[Platform game|platform]] [[video game]] developed by [[Visco Corporation]] and originally published by Neo Conception International for the [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo AES]] (home).<ref>{{cite web|last=Reynolds|first=Stuart|url=http://www.neogeoforlife.com/articles.php?article_id=5|title=Neo Geo Prototypes|website=neogeoforlife.com|date=December 25, 2006|access-date=2019-11-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231071451/http://www.neogeoforlife.com/articles.php?article_id=5|archive-date=December 31, 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"nci\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bang2busters.com/faqs.html|title=BANG 2 BUSTERS'S FAQ  !|publisher=Neo Conception International|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110508123356/http://www.bang2busters.com/faqs.html|archive-date=2011-05-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ah2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=bang2-busters-model-ngh-071&page=detail&id=48105|title=Bang\u00b2 Busters [Model NGH-071] (AES)|website=arcade-history.com|accessdate=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420233401/http://www.arcade-history.com/?n=bang2-busters-model-ngh-071&page=detail&id=48105|archive-date=2016-04-20|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"gc\">{{cite web|last=Bravo|first=Roberto|url=https://www.gamercafe.cl/2010/12/10/neo-geo-hardcore-fans-rejoice-%C2%A1%C2%A1bang-bang-busters-saldra-oficialmente-en-aes/|title=Neo Geo hardcore fans rejoice: \u00a1\u00a1Bang Bang Busters saldr\u00e1 OFICIALMENTE en AES!!|publisher=Gamercafe|date=10 December 2010|access-date=2019-12-26|lang=es}}</ref> Taking place on the [[fictional planet]] of Palua in the [[future]], where an evil being known as Honey plots to have his own [[galaxy]], players assume the role of Lazy and Refia in order to prevent Honey and his followers from realizing their plan. Its [[gameplay]] mainly consists of platforming mixed with [[Action game|action]] elements using a main two-button configuration.\n\nHeaded by Visco founder Tetsuo Akiyama and ''[[Breakers (1996 video game)|Breakers]]'' [[Video game producer|producer]] Don Gabacho, ''Bang Bang Busters'' was created by most of the same team that previously worked on several projects at Visco. Though it was initially launched for the Neo Geo AES, the game was later released for both Neo Geo MVS (arcade) and [[Neo Geo CD]] in [[2011 in video gaming|2011]] and [[2012 in video gaming|2012]] respectively, as well for the [[Dreamcast]] in [[2018 in video gaming|2018]].<ref name=\"BBBmb\">{{cite web|author=Sciere|url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/arcade/bang-busters/release-info|title=Bang\u00b2 Busters (2011) Arcade release dates|work=[[MobyGames]]|publisher=Blue Flame Labs|date=July 25, 2019|access-date=2019-12-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225172438/https://www.mobygames.com/game/arcade/bang-busters/release-info|archive-date=2020-02-25|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ah1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=bang2-busters-model-ngm-071&page=detail&id=3846|title=Bang\u00b2 Busters [Model NGM-071] (MVS)|website=arcade-history.com|accessdate=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812080522/http://www.arcade-history.com/?n=bang2-busters-model-ngm-071&page=detail&id=3846|archive-date=2016-08-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBNGCD\">{{cite web|last=Buchanan|first=Adam|url=http://www.retrocollect.com/News/bang-bang-busters-released-on-the-neo-geo-cd.html|title=Unreleased Neo Geo Prototype Bang Bang Busters Released For The Neo Geo CD|website=retrocollect.com|date=June 28, 2012|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712065023/http://www.retrocollect.com/News/bang-bang-busters-released-on-the-neo-geo-cd.html|archive-date=July 12, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBDCa\">{{cite web|last=McMurray|first=Jennifer|url=http://www.dreamcast-scene.com/news/bang%C2%B2-busters-is-coming-to-the-dreamcast/|title=Bang\u00b2 Busters Is Coming To The Dreamcast|work=Dreamcast-Scene|publisher=[[WordPress.com]]|date=May 9, 2018|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013085019/http://www.dreamcast-scene.com/news/bang%C2%B2-busters-is-coming-to-the-dreamcast/|archive-date=2018-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBDCb\">{{cite web|author=doceggfan|url=http://www.thedreamcastjunkyard.co.uk/2019/02/the-dreamcast-games-of-2018.html|title=The Dreamcast Games Of 2018|website=www.thedreamcastjunkyard.co.uk|date=February 2019|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617032642/http://www.thedreamcastjunkyard.co.uk/2019/02/the-dreamcast-games-of-2018.html|archive-date=2019-06-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:NEOGEO Bang Bang Busters (Bang\u00b2 Busters).png|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot.]]\n''Bang Bang Busters'' is a platform game similar to ''[[Snow Bros.]]'' and ''[[Nightmare in the Dark]]'', where the players assume control of Lazy (P1) and Refia (P2) across seven stages comprising multiple levels that take place on planet Palua, each with a [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]] at the end that must be fought before progressing any further, in order to stop an evil being known as Honey and his followers before the former has his own galaxy as the main objective.<ref name=\"ah1\"/><ref name=\"BBBAESmanual\">''Bang Bang Busters'' user's manual (Neo Geo AES, US)</ref><ref name=\"BBBDCmanual\">''Bang Bang Busters'' manual (Dreamcast, US)</ref><ref name=\"BBBngp\">{{cite web|last=Pitt|first=Billy|url=http://www.neogeoprotos.com/games/b2b.htm|title=Bang Bang Busters by Visco Games - NEO GEO MVS NGM-071|website=neogeoprotos.com|access-date=2020-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802111011/http://www.neogeoprotos.com/games/b2b.htm|archive-date=2019-08-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBcng\">{{cite web|url=https://www.culturaneogeo.com/protos1|title=Juegos Prototipo - Bang Bang Busters|publisher=Cultura Neo Geo|access-date=2020-02-25|language=es}}</ref> \n\nThe players must throw energy projectiles at enemies to inflate them with air, which is reminiscent of ''[[Dig Dug]]''.<ref name=\"BBBAESmanual\"/><ref name=\"BBBDCmanual\"/><ref name=\"BBBngp\"/> From there, players can grab the inflated enemies to perform a variety of actions such as launching them against other enemies at any direction by holding the attack button, perform a dash throw by double-tapping the [[joystick]] left or right, as well as float above the ground by repeatedly tapping the jump button.<ref name=\"BBBAESmanual\"/><ref name=\"BBBDCmanual\"/> Any enemy inflated with air cannot move until it shakes it off. Defeated enemies may spawn [[power-up]]s and [[Item (gaming)|item]]s like a speed increaser, a [[bomb]] that obliterates any enemy caught in its [[blast radius]], among others.<ref name=\"BBBAESmanual\"/><ref name=\"BBBDCmanual\"/> Players can sustain a number of enemy hits, at the expense of losing power as a penalty, but the [[Game over|game is over]] after taking one last hit unless the players decide to [[Glossary of video game terms#Continue|continue]] playing.\n\n== Development and release ==\n''Bang Bang Busters'' was created by most of the same team that previously worked on several projects at Visco Corporation.<ref name=\"BBBStaffroll\">{{cite video game|title=Bang\u00b2 Busters|developer=[[Visco Corporation]]|publisher=Neo Conception International|date=2000|platform=[[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo AES]]|level=Staff roll}}</ref> Its development was helmed by Visco founder Tetsuo Akiyama and ''Breakers'' producer Don Gabacho, with Yasuhisa Itoi acting as [[supervisor]].<ref name=\"BBBStaffroll\"/> Ebi Taisyo and Tel.Y served as [[Video game designer|designer]], with Taisyo also serving as [[Video game writer|writer]].<ref name=\"BBBStaffroll\"/> [[Video game artist|Artist]]s Hirofumi Mawatari, Makoto Nobetani and Kaoru Ishizawa designed the characters, while Kentaro Masakane and Kenichi Imamatsu were the [[Video game programmer|programmer]]s.<ref name=\"BBBStaffroll\"/> The music was composed by Kiyoshi Kusatsu, while other people also collaborated during development.<ref name=\"BBBStaffroll\"/>\n\n''Bang Bang Busters'' was initially showcased at [[trade show]]s and intended to be released in [[1994 in video gaming|1994]] but it was never released for unknown reasons until 2010, when independent developer and publisher Neo Conception International released the AES version as part of a acquisition deal with Visco in regards to the rights of their [[intellectual properties]].<ref name=\"nci\"/><ref name=\"gc\"/><ref name=\"BBBngp\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3ABeepMD_JP_1993-04.pdf&page=33|title=Mega AM Network - AOU: \u30d3\u30b9\u30b3 - \u30d0\u30f3 \u30d0\u30f3 \u30d0\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ba|magazine=[[:ja:\u30b2\u30fc\u30de\u30ac#BEEP!\u30e1\u30ac\u30c9\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6|Beep! MegaDrive]]|issue=43|publisher=[[SB Creative|SoftBank Creative]]|date=April 1993|page=31|lang=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.culturaneogeo.com/imagenes/entrevistas/nciesp.htm|title=Entrevista a NCI|publisher=Cultura Neo Geo|date=March 2016|accessdate=2019-12-26|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621002035/https://www.culturaneogeo.com/imagenes/entrevistas/nciesp.htm|archive-date=2019-06-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Although its production number during development remained unknown, it was later revealed to be officially assigned with the number 71.<ref name=\"ah2\"/><ref name=\"ah1\"/><ref name=\"BBBngp\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Giles|first=Aaron|url=https://github.com/mamedev/mame/blob/f15313bc070231f7fe13b2b63bf3d0ae55793171/src/mame/arcade.lst|title=arcade.lst|publisher=[[GitHub]]|access-date=2020-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231021824/https://github.com/mamedev/mame/blob/f15313bc070231f7fe13b2b63bf3d0ae55793171/src/mame/arcade.lst|archive-date=2018-12-31|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBngaul\">{{cite web|url=http://castleofcollectibles.com/U-List.txt|title=NEO\u2022GEO AES UNRELEASED LIST|website=castleofcollectibles.com|date=September 5, 2004|access-date=2020-02-25|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316032349/http://castleofcollectibles.com/U-List.txt|archivedate=March 16, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"BBBngpb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.neo-geo.com/forums/showthread.php?117868-NEOGEO-PROTOS-breakdown-list|title=NEOGEO PROTOS breakdown list|website=neo-geo.com|date=April 22, 2005|access-date=2020-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405223836/http://www.neo-geo.com/forums/showthread.php?117868-NEOGEO-PROTOS-breakdown-list|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The title was then launched for Neo Geo MVS in 2011 and later for Neo Geo CD by N.C.I. in 2012.<ref name=\"nci\"/><ref name=\"BBBmb\"/><ref name=\"ah1\"/><ref name=\"BBBNGCD\"/> Years later, an officially licensed port by Visco for the Dreamcast was also released by JoshProd worldwide in 2018.<ref name=\"BBBDCa\"/><ref name=\"BBBDCb\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n